                <div class="topic-body">
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Why It Matters:</strong> Kadane's Algorithm is a linear-time DP technique that finds the maximum-sum contiguous subarray by maintaining one invariant: at each index i, compute the best subarray sum ending exactly at i â€” either extend the previous best or start fresh. The recurrence <code>maxEndingHere = max(nums[i], maxEndingHere + nums[i])</code> is deceptively simple, yet it underpins problems spanning circular arrays, products, 2D matrices, absolute values, and DP-on-tree variants. It appears consistently in top-tier interviews because (a) naive O(nÂ²) is trivially wrong, (b) the optimal is O(n), and (c) extensions like circular arrays and product subarrays test whether a candidate truly understands the invariant or has merely memorised the code.</div>
                    <div class="core-box"><strong>Core Invariant:</strong> <code>maxEndingHere = max(nums[i], maxEndingHere + nums[i])</code> â€” start fresh when maxEndingHere &lt; 0 because a negative prefix can never help. Global answer = max over all maxEndingHere values.<br><br><strong>State:</strong> dp[i] = max subarray sum ending at i &nbsp;Â·&nbsp; <strong>Recurrence:</strong> dp[i] = max(nums[i], dp[iâˆ’1] + nums[i]) &nbsp;Â·&nbsp; <strong>Preferred:</strong> Bottom-up, O(1) space with rolling variables (maxEndingHere, maxSoFar). Top-down adds call-stack overhead for zero benefit.</div>

