                    <div class="sec-title">When This Technique BREAKS</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>Non-adjacent / non-contiguous requirement</strong> â€” "No two adjacent elements" (House Robber) changes the recurrence to dp[i] = max(dp[iâˆ’1], dp[iâˆ’2] + nums[i]); Kadane's "extend or restart" is invalid.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>Exact sum required</strong> â€” "Find subarray with sum = k" with negatives: Kadane's shrink logic breaks. Use prefix sum + HashMap.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>Count of all subarrays satisfying a condition</strong> â€” Kadane's finds one optimal subarray; counting all requires prefix map or at-most decomposition.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>Maximum subarray of exact fixed length</strong> â€” Use a fixed sliding window of size k; Kadane's variable-length nature doesn't apply.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>Empty subarray allowed when all values are negative</strong> â€” If empty subarray is permitted the answer is 0; standard Kadane's (init to nums[0]) returns negative. Clarify the empty-subarray contract.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>Product with zeros</strong> â€” Max product subarray needs special handling: zeros reset both maxProd and minProd. Failing to handle zeros gives incorrect results.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>2D problem without column-compression</strong> â€” Running Kadane's row-by-row misses cross-row rectangles. Fix column boundaries â†’ compress rows â†’ apply 1D Kadane's.</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">3-Phase Mastery Plan</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Phase 1 â€” Solve (in order):</strong> #1 â†’ #2 â†’ #3 â†’ #4 â†’ #5 â†’ #9 â†’ #10 â†’ #6 â†’ #7 â†’ #14 â†’ #12 â†’ #18 â†’ #20 â†’ #21 â†’ #11 â†’ #13<br>
                        Problems 1â€“3 nail the three canonical forms (sum, product, circular). Problems 4â€“5 expand the state space. Custom #9â€“#10 force first-principles derivation, not memorisation. #18 (tree path sum) appears directly in Google interviews. #20 (largest variance) is the hardest recognition problem; do it after all Medium variants. #11 closes the 2D chapter.<br><br>
                        <strong>Phase 2 â€” Drill:</strong> Before coding each problem, explicitly write the Kadane's state variables: "What does maxEndingHere mean here? When do I reset? When do I update global?" Practise the 1Dâ†’2D transition: given any 2D sum problem, immediately compress to 1D using fixed column boundaries â€” this should become automatic. Always init to nums[0], never 0, unless empty subarray is explicitly allowed.<br><br>
                        <strong>Phase 3 â€” Validate:</strong> AtCoder ABC/ARC â€” search "maximum subarray" (several problems disguise Kadane's in scoring games). USACO Silver "Hoof, Paper, Scissors" â€” multi-state transitions extending Kadane's DP. HackerRank DP set: "Max Array Sum" and "The Maximum Subarray" test all-negative and non-adjacent variants back-to-back.
