                <div class="topic-body">
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Why It Matters:</strong> Merge Intervals models the fundamental computer science primitive of managing contiguous ranges on a linear axis â€” time slots, memory addresses, genomic base pairs, network port ranges, log timestamps. The core invariant is devastatingly simple: after sorting by start, two closed intervals [a,b] and [c,d] overlap iff c â‰¤ b. Every single variant in this topic â€” from classic merge to sweep-line to segment trees â€” is a direct consequence of this one inequality. It appears at Google, Meta, Stripe, and Jane Street because it tests greedy reasoning, proof justification, and the ability to escalate a simple idea into an online/streaming/2-D context under pressure.</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">The Mental Model</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Think of intervals as paint strokes on a number line.</strong> Merging is asking: after all strokes dry, what are the distinct painted segments? Every sub-variant reduces to this image:<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Classic merge</strong> â†’ what are the final painted segments?<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Count overlaps</strong> â†’ at which point is the paint thickest?<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Insert interval</strong> â†’ add one new stroke, re-report the segments<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Remove overlaps</strong> â†’ erase minimum strokes so no two wet strokes touch<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Gap detection</strong> â†’ where are the unpainted gaps?<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Weighted scheduling</strong> â†’ which strokes to keep to maximise total value?<br><br>
                        When stuck on any interval problem, return to this image and ask: "What am I computing about this paint?"
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Core Invariant &amp; Proof Sketch</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Invariant:</strong> After sorting intervals by start time, for any two consecutive intervals I<sub>i</sub> = [a<sub>i</sub>, b<sub>i</sub>] and I<sub>i+1</sub> = [a<sub>i+1</sub>, b<sub>i+1</sub>], they overlap iff a<sub>i+1</sub> â‰¤ b<sub>i</sub>.<br><br>
                        <strong>Proof sketch (why sorting by start is sufficient):</strong> Suppose intervals are sorted: a<sub>1</sub> â‰¤ a<sub>2</sub> â‰¤ ... â‰¤ a<sub>n</sub>. If I<sub>i</sub> and I<sub>j</sub> overlap with j &gt; i+1, then a<sub>j</sub> â‰¤ b<sub>i</sub>. But a<sub>i+1</sub> â‰¤ a<sub>j</sub> â‰¤ b<sub>i</sub>, so I<sub>i</sub> and I<sub>i+1</sub> also overlap. Therefore, any non-consecutive overlap is caught by a chain of consecutive overlaps.<br><br>
                        <strong>Consequence:</strong> We never need to look back more than one step â€” the greedy single-pass is complete.<br>
                        <strong>Corollary:</strong> The merged result is unique (order of merging does not matter), which justifies the greedy approach's correctness without needing an exchange argument.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Sub-Variants to Master (18 total with complexity)</div>
                    <div class="info-box" style="line-height:1.75">
                        <strong>1. Classic merge</strong> â€” collapse overlapping into disjoint set Â· O(n log n) Â· sorted array + linear scan<br>
                        <strong>2. Insert &amp; merge</strong> â€” insert one into already-merged list Â· O(n) Â· three-phase walk<br>
                        <strong>3. Count overlaps / min rooms</strong> â€” max active at any point Â· O(n log n) Â· min-heap of end-times OR diff array + prefix<br>
                        <strong>4. Interval removal (Activity Selection)</strong> â€” remove fewest to eliminate overlaps Â· O(n log n) Â· sort by end + greedy keep<br>
                        <strong>5. Interval coverage</strong> â€” cover [s,e] with fewest intervals Â· O(n log n) Â· sort by start, greedy extend reach<br>
                        <strong>6. Gap / missing-range detection</strong> â€” unpainted segments within boundary Â· O(n log n) Â· sorted merge + sentinels<br>
                        <strong>7. Interval intersection</strong> â€” present in BOTH sorted lists Â· O(m+n) Â· two-pointer<br>
                        <strong>8. Interval subtraction</strong> â€” subtract one interval from another Â· O(n) Â· linear scan + fragment split<br>
                        <strong>9. Weighted non-overlapping selection</strong> â€” maximise total weight Â· O(n log n) Â· DP + binary search (Weighted Job Scheduling)<br>
                        <strong>10. Point stabbing</strong> â€” count intervals containing query point Â· O((n+q) log n) Â· diff array + coord compression<br>
                        <strong>11. Online interval insert</strong> â€” streaming merged state Â· O(log n) per insert Â· TreeMap / balanced BST<br>
                        <strong>12. Online interval CRUD</strong> â€” add/query/remove dynamically Â· O(log n + k) per op Â· sorted map of disjoint intervals<br>
                        <strong>13. Sweep-line + active set</strong> â€” skyline, rectangle area Â· O(n log n) Â· sorted multiset / segment tree<br>
                        <strong>14. Range update, point query</strong> â€” apply +val to [l,r] Â· O(n+q) Â· difference array + prefix sum<br>
                        <strong>15. Range update, range query</strong> â€” simultaneous update/query Â· O(n log n) per op Â· segment tree with lazy propagation<br>
                        <strong>16. 2-D interval merge (rectangle union)</strong> â€” union area Â· O(n log n) Â· sweep + coord compression + segment tree<br>
                        <strong>17. Circular intervals</strong> â€” wrap around modular domain Â· O(n log n) Â· split + linear merge + restitch<br>
                        <strong>18. Multi-list interval merge</strong> â€” K sorted lists simultaneously Â· O(N log n) Â· heap or flatten + sort
                    </div>
