                    <div class="sec-title">Custom Problem Statements</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>ðŸ”§ #16 â€” Circular Interval Merge:</strong> Given a circle with M units (0 to Mâˆ’1) and N intervals [L_i, R_i]; an interval is circular if L_i &gt; R_i (wraps around). Return the merged disjoint intervals covering the union. If the full circle is covered, return ["FULL"]. Constraints: 1 â‰¤ N â‰¤ 10âµ, 2 â‰¤ M â‰¤ 10â¹, 0 â‰¤ L_i, R_i &lt; M. Example: M=24, [[22,3],[1,5],[4,10],[15,20]] â†’ [[1,10],[15,20],[22,3]]. Key Insight: Split every circular [L,R] with L&gt;R into [L, Mâˆ’1] and [0, R]. Run standard linear merge over [0, Mâˆ’1]. Then re-stitch: if first merged interval starts at 0 and last ends at Mâˆ’1, merge them into one circular interval. O(n log n).</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>ðŸ”§ #32 â€” Point-Stabbing Count Queries:</strong> Given N intervals [L_i, R_i] and Q query points p_j, return for each query the count of intervals containing p_j. Constraints: 1 â‰¤ N, Q â‰¤ 10âµ, 1 â‰¤ L_i â‰¤ R_i â‰¤ 10â¹. Example: intervals=[[1,5],[2,8],[4,10],[7,12]], queries=[3,6,11] â†’ [2, 3, 2]. Key Insight: Coordinate-compress all endpoints + query points. Create difference array: +1 at L_i, âˆ’1 at R_i+1. Prefix-sum gives count at each compressed coordinate. For each query, binary search its compressed position. O((N+Q) log N).</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>ðŸ”§ #33 â€” Minimum Interval Coverage of Target Range:</strong> Given a target range [S, E] and N intervals [L_i, R_i], find the minimum number of intervals needed to completely cover [S, E]. Each interval may be used at most once. If impossible, return -1. Constraints: 1 â‰¤ N â‰¤ 10âµ, âˆ’10â¹ â‰¤ S â‰¤ E â‰¤ 10â¹. Example: S=1, E=10, [[1,3],[2,6],[5,10],[8,12]] â†’ 2. Key Insight: Sort intervals by start. Greedy: at each step, among all intervals with start â‰¤ current_covered_end + 1, pick the one maximising end. Advance current_covered_end. O(n log n).</div>

