                    <div class="sec-title">When This Technique BREAKS</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>Intervals have weights and you want maximum total value</strong> â€” Greedy merge selects wrong intervals. Use Weighted Job Scheduling DP (binary search + DP sorted by end-time).</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>Intervals arrive online with O(log n) per-op requirement</strong> â€” Static sort-and-merge is O(n) rebuild per insert. Use TreeMap / SortedList for O(log n) predecessor/successor lookup.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>Axis is huge (up to 10â¹) and you need a difference array</strong> â€” Plain array of size 10â¹ causes MLE. Use coordinate compression or a Fenwick tree on compressed coordinates.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>Circular/modular intervals</strong> â€” Sort-by-start fails at wrap-around. Split circular intervals at 0/M boundary, run linear merge, then restitch.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>Intervals are 2-D (rectangles)</strong> â€” 1-D merge gives wrong area. Use sweep-line on x-axis + 1-D interval merge/segment tree on y-axis.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>Containment detection (is A fully inside B?)</strong> â€” Standard overlap check c â‰¤ b catches containment AND partial overlap â€” you need the stricter check a â‰¤ c AND d â‰¤ b. Classic merge logic silently gives wrong answer here.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>"Burst Balloons" style problems</strong> â€” The intervals represent DP sub-problems, not ranges to merge. Use Interval DP (dp[i][j]), not sweep-line.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>Streaming with hard memory limits</strong> â€” Storing all intervals for offline sort is impossible. Use reservoir-style online merge or accept approximate answers with a bounded-error sketch.</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Proof of Correctness Skeleton</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>1. Classic Greedy Merge (#1)</strong><br>
                        <em>Claim:</em> The sort + single-pass algorithm produces the unique minimum set of disjoint intervals covering the same union.<br>
                        <em>Invariant:</em> After processing the first k intervals (sorted by start), <code>result</code> contains the correct merged intervals for those k intervals.<br>
                        <em>Inductive step:</em> At interval k+1 with start s and end e: if s &gt; result.last.end, no previously processed interval reaches s (since all starts â‰¤ s by sort), so k+1 is disjoint â†’ append. If s â‰¤ result.last.end, they overlap; <code>max(result.last.end, e)</code> is the correct merged end because no future interval (start â‰¥ s) can "fill" a gap inside [result.last.start, sâˆ’1].<br>
                        <em>Uniqueness:</em> The merged output is unique because the union set is fixed and the greedy produces the coarsest partition.
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>2. Activity Selection / Non-overlapping Removal (#3)</strong><br>
                        <em>Claim:</em> Greedy "keep the interval with earliest end-time" maximises the number of kept non-overlapping intervals.<br>
                        <em>Exchange argument:</em> Let G = greedy solution, O = any optimal, both sorted by end-time. If they agree on the first k intervals but differ at k+1 â€” G picks g, O picks o with end(g) â‰¤ end(o) (greedy choice). Swap o for g in O: g doesn't overlap with O's (k+2)-th interval (since end(g) â‰¤ end(o) and O was valid). Count doesn't decrease.<br>
                        <em>Conclusion:</em> G can be transformed into O without reducing count â†’ G is optimal.
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>3. Weighted Job Scheduling DP (#17)</strong><br>
                        <em>Claim:</em> <code>dp[i] = max(dp[iâˆ’1], profit[i] + dp[p(i)])</code> where p(i) = latest job ending before start[i] gives maximum profit.<br>
                        <em>Observation:</em> For job i, either it is NOT included (best = dp[iâˆ’1]) or it IS included (best = profit[i] + best using only jobs ending before start[i] = dp[p(i)]). These two cases are exhaustive and disjoint, so dp[i] is correct.<br>
                        <em>Complexity:</em> p(i) found via binary search on end-times in O(log n), giving O(n log n) total.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Implementation Pitfalls (Code-Level)</div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 1 â€” Forgetting to append the final in-progress interval</strong><br>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG (running variables variant)
