                    <div class="sec-title">Red Flags / Common Mistakes</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>Applying greedy merge to weighted intervals</strong> â€” Classic merge has no notion of value â€” it merges all overlapping intervals regardless. If any interval carries a weight and you need to SELECT a subset, you must use Weighted Job Scheduling DP. This is the single most common wrong approach at the Hard level.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>Confusing "overlap" with "containment"</strong> â€” [1,10] and [3,5] overlap AND contain each other. Problems asking to remove covered intervals (LC 1288) require checking a â‰¤ c AND d â‰¤ b, not just c â‰¤ b. Using the overlap check here silently over-counts removals.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>Forgetting the heap pop in Meeting Rooms II</strong> â€” Not popping before pushing means you never reuse a freed room, inflating the answer. Always check heap[0] â‰¤ cur.start before deciding to push vs. heapreplace.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>Online vs offline conflation</strong> â€” Collecting all intervals and sorting at the end is wrong for streaming problems (My Calendar, Range Module). It breaks the online contract and will fail any follow-up that asks "what if intervals arrive in real time?"</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>Difference array with values up to 10â¹</strong> â€” Allocating <code>diff = [0] * (10**9 + 1)</code> causes MLE. Coordinate-compress the endpoints first, then build the difference array on compressed indices only.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>Not handling the empty input or single-interval edge cases</strong> â€” Many interval bugs surface only when len(intervals) == 0 or == 1. Always handle these before the loop.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>Circular interval wraparound</strong> â€” Treating [22, 3] on a 24-hour clock as a normal interval with start &gt; end causes incorrect sort ordering and false non-overlap conclusions. Always split first.</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Interviewer Follow-Up Questions</div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Follow-Up Question</th><th>Intended Answer Direction</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>1</td><td>"What's the time complexity? Can you do better than O(n log n)?"</td><td>Sort is the bottleneck; O(n log n) is optimal in comparison-based model (proven by sort lower bound). If input is already sorted, O(n).</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>2</td><td>"What if intervals are given as a stream â€” you can't store all of them?"</td><td>Use a balanced BST (TreeMap); insert each interval and merge with neighbours in O(log n). Memory = O(k) where k = current distinct merged intervals.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>3</td><td>"What if N = 10â¹ intervals?"</td><td>Can't store; need a streaming/summarisation approach. If intervals are uniform random, reservoir sampling. If structured (e.g. monotone starts), sliding window. Discuss trade-off between exactness and memory.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>4</td><td>"How would you parallelise this for a distributed system?"</td><td>Partition intervals by coordinate ranges across machines; each machine merges its partition; a coordinator merges boundary intervals between adjacent partitions. O(n/k) per machine, O(k) merge at coordinator.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>5</td><td>"What if intervals can be added AND removed dynamically?"</td><td>Range Module (#25): sorted map of disjoint intervals. Each add/remove is O(log n + k) where k = number of intervals affected.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>6</td><td>"For every point x, how many intervals contain x?"</td><td>Offline: difference array + coordinate compression, O((n+q) log n). Online per-query: Fenwick tree / segment tree on compressed coordinates.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>7</td><td>"What if endpoints are floating point?"</td><td>Algorithm is identical â€” float comparison works the same. Beware epsilon issues; use exact rational arithmetic or a problem-specific epsilon if needed.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>8</td><td>"Prove your greedy is correct for Activity Selection."</td><td>Exchange argument: any optimal solution can have its choices swapped one-by-one with greedy's choices without reducing the count (see Proof section).</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>9</td><td>"How would you handle 2-D intervals (rectangles)?"</td><td>Sweep line on x-axis; maintain active y-intervals in a segment tree; compute y-coverage via interval merge on segment tree after each x-event. O(n log n).</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>10</td><td>"What if the problem asks for the MEDIAN overlap count at any point, not the max?"</td><td>Sweep-line with sorted multiset of depths; at each event record the depth; find median of all recorded depths. Or offline: sort events, track depth array, find median via order statistics.</td></tr>
                        </tbody></table></div>

