                <div class="topic-body">
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Why It Matters:</strong> Prefix Sums is the foundational pre-computation primitive of competitive programming. The core invariant is: <code>sum(i, j) = prefix[j+1] âˆ’ prefix[i]</code> â€” any contiguous subarray sum reduces to a single O(1) subtraction after O(n) preprocessing. This single identity unlocks an enormous class of problems: range sum queries, subarray count problems, 2D rectangle queries, difference arrays for range updates, and hash-map-augmented subarray problems. It appears in virtually every Google/Meta interview round because it tests whether a candidate instinctively pre-computes rather than recomputes â€” a fundamental signal of algorithmic maturity. At the ICPC/IOI level, prefix sums compose with segment trees, sparse tables, and Fenwick trees to form the backbone of nearly all range query algorithms.</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">The Mental Model</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>A prefix sum array is a "running water level"</strong> â€” <code>prefix[i]</code> is the total water accumulated up to position i. The water between two banks i and j is simply the level at j minus the level at i. You measure the river once; you answer every query in one subtraction.<br><br>
                        <strong>How the mental model scales through the 5 stages:</strong><br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 1:</strong> <code>prefix[j+1] âˆ’ prefix[i] = sum of arr[i..j]</code>. One array, one subtraction.<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 2:</strong> The "water" is not integers but modular residues, XORs, or parities. The subtraction becomes a modular operation or XOR â€” same shape, different algebra.<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 3:</strong> The river becomes a 2D lake. <code>prefix[r][c]</code> = total water in the rectangle from (0,0) to (r,c). Inclusion-exclusion replaces the single subtraction.<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 4:</strong> The problem never says "subarray sum." You must recognise that a condition like <code>sum(i,j) = k</code> is secretly <code>prefix[j] âˆ’ prefix[i] = k â†’ prefix[i] = prefix[j] âˆ’ k</code>. The water level is hidden inside a counting or existence question.<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 5:</strong> There are 10â¹ positions but only 10âµ updates. The river is sparse. A Fenwick tree or segment tree replaces the static array â€” the identity <code>prefix[j] âˆ’ prefix[i]</code> still holds, but each level query is now O(log n).
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Core Invariant &amp; Proof Sketch</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Invariant:</strong> For a 1-indexed array <em>a</em>, define <code>prefix[0] = 0</code> and <code>prefix[i] = a[1] + a[2] + ... + a[i]</code>. Then for any 0 â‰¤ i â‰¤ j â‰¤ n:<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<code>sum(i+1, j) = prefix[j] âˆ’ prefix[i]</code><br><br>
                        <strong>Proof sketch (by telescoping):</strong> By definition, <code>prefix[j] = a[1] + ... + a[j]</code> and <code>prefix[i] = a[1] + ... + a[i]</code>. Subtracting: <code>prefix[j] âˆ’ prefix[i] = a[i+1] + ... + a[j]</code> â€” the shared prefix <code>a[1..i]</code> cancels exactly.<br><br>
                        <strong>Generalisation:</strong> This telescoping works for any associative operation with an inverse: addition (subtraction), XOR (XOR again), multiplication (division if non-zero). It does NOT work for max/min because there is no inverse â€” this is the fundamental limitation.<br><br>
                        <strong>2D corollary:</strong> <code>rect(r1,c1,r2,c2) = prefix[r2][c2] âˆ’ prefix[r1âˆ’1][c2] âˆ’ prefix[r2][c1âˆ’1] + prefix[r1âˆ’1][c1âˆ’1]</code> by inclusion-exclusion on the same telescoping identity applied twice.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Sub-Variants to Master (15 total)</div>
                    <div class="info-box" style="line-height:1.75">
                        <strong>1. 1D range sum query</strong> â€” Stage 1 Â· O(n) build, O(1) query Â· static array Â· <em>New idea:</em> prefix array definition; telescoping subtraction<br>
                        <strong>2. 1D range sum with modular/XOR algebra</strong> â€” Stage 2 Â· O(n) build, O(1) query Â· static array Â· <em>New idea:</em> the "subtraction" changes algebra (XOR is its own inverse; mod requires careful handling)<br>
                        <strong>3. Subarray sum equals K (count)</strong> â€” Stage 2 Â· O(n) Â· hash map on prefix values Â· <em>New idea:</em> count pairs (i,j) where prefix[j] âˆ’ prefix[i] = k â†’ frequency map of prefix values<br>
                        <strong>4. Subarray sum divisible by K (modular)</strong> â€” Stage 2 Â· O(n) Â· hash map on prefix mod K Â· <em>New idea:</em> (prefix[j] âˆ’ prefix[i]) % K = 0 â†’ same prefix mod â†’ group by remainder<br>
                        <strong>5. 2D rectangle sum query</strong> â€” Stage 3 Â· O(nm) build, O(1) query Â· 2D prefix array Â· <em>New idea:</em> inclusion-exclusion on four corners; prefix is now 2-indexed<br>
                        <strong>6. 2D rectangle sum count / submatrix target</strong> â€” Stage 3 Â· O(nÂ²m) with hash map Â· 2D prefix + hash map Â· <em>New idea:</em> fix two rows, reduce to 1D subarray-sum-equals-K on column sums<br>
                        <strong>7. Difference array (range add, point query)</strong> â€” Stage 3 Â· O(n+q) Â· difference array + prefix sum Â· <em>New idea:</em> prefix sum's INVERSE operation â€” store differences, recover values via prefix sum<br>
                        <strong>8. Difference array 2D (rectangle add, point query)</strong> â€” Stage 3 Â· O(nm+q) Â· 2D difference array Â· <em>New idea:</em> 2D inclusion-exclusion on the difference array<br>
                        <strong>9. Prefix sum on transformed values (sqrt, log, boolean)</strong> â€” Stage 4 Â· O(n) Â· static array Â· <em>New idea:</em> the array being summed is not the raw input â€” requires a transformation first<br>
                        <strong>10. Prefix XOR (subarray XOR queries)</strong> â€” Stage 2 Â· O(n) build, O(1) query Â· static array Â· <em>New idea:</em> XOR is its own inverse, so xor(i,j) = prefix_xor[j] ^ prefix_xor[iâˆ’1]<br>
                        <strong>11. Prefix XOR + hash map (count subarray XOR = k)</strong> â€” Stage 4 Â· O(n) Â· hash map Â· <em>New idea:</em> same shape as subarray-sum-equals-K but with XOR algebra; requires recognising the reduction<br>
                        <strong>12. Sparse prefix sum (dynamic updates + queries)</strong> â€” Stage 5 Â· O(log n) per op Â· Fenwick tree / segment tree Â· <em>New idea:</em> prefix array is no longer static; each update requires partial reconstruction<br>
                        <strong>13. Prefix sum on a tree (path sum queries)</strong> â€” Stage 4 Â· O(n) DFS build, O(1) query with LCA Â· Euler tour + static prefix Â· <em>New idea:</em> "prefix" runs down a root-to-node path; sum(u,v) = depth[u] + depth[v] âˆ’ 2Â·depth[LCA]<br>
                        <strong>14. Sliding window prefix (fixed or variable length)</strong> â€” Stage 4 Â· O(n) Â· prefix array + two pointers Â· <em>New idea:</em> prefix enables O(1) window sum; two-pointer finds the valid window bounds<br>
                        <strong>15. Circular prefix sum</strong> â€” Stage 2 Â· O(n) Â· prefix array with modular indexing Â· <em>New idea:</em> wrap-around subarray splits into two segments; handle via total_sum âˆ’ complement
                    </div>

