                    <div class="sec-title">Custom Problem Statements</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>ðŸ”§ #13 â€” 2D Range Add, Point Query:</strong> Given an NÃ—M grid initialised to all zeros, process Q operations. Each operation is (r1, c1, r2, c2, v): add v to every cell (r, c) where r1 â‰¤ r â‰¤ r2 and c1 â‰¤ c â‰¤ c2. After all operations, answer P point queries: what is the value at cell (r, c)?<br>
                        <strong>Constraints:</strong> 1 â‰¤ N, M â‰¤ 1000, 1 â‰¤ Q, P â‰¤ 10âµ, 1 â‰¤ v â‰¤ 100.<br>
                        <strong>Example:</strong> N=3, M=3; ops=[(1,1,2,2,5), (2,2,3,3,3)]; queries=[(1,1),(2,2),(3,3)] â†’ [5, 8, 3].<br>
                        <strong>Intended solution:</strong> Maintain 2D difference array <code>diff[N+2][M+2]</code>. For each op (r1,c1,r2,c2,v):<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;<code>diff[r1][c1] += v; diff[r1][c2+1] âˆ’= v; diff[r2+1][c1] âˆ’= v; diff[r2+1][c2+1] += v</code><br>
                        After all ops, compute 2D prefix sum of diff to recover the grid. O(NM + Q) total.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Pattern Recognition Triggers</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Linguistic Triggers:</strong><br>
                        â€¢ "sum of elements between index i and j" â†’ Stage 1 â€” direct range query; build prefix array<br>
                        â€¢ "number of subarrays with sum equal to k" â†’ Stage 2 â€” prefix[j] âˆ’ prefix[i] = k; hash map on prefix values<br>
                        â€¢ "add v to all elements in range [l,r], then query point" â†’ Stage 3 â€” difference array (inverse prefix)<br>
                        â€¢ "submatrix sum" or "rectangle sum" â†’ Stage 3 â€” 2D prefix with inclusion-exclusion<br>
                        â€¢ "count subarrays where [some property of sum holds]" â†’ Stage 4 â€” transform property into prefix condition; check what algebra applies
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Structural Triggers:</strong><br>
                        â€¢ Input is an array + multiple (l, r) range queries with no updates â†’ Stage 1/2, static prefix array<br>
                        â€¢ Input is an array + multiple (l, r, v) range updates + point queries â†’ Stage 3, difference array<br>
                        â€¢ Input is a 2D grid + rectangle queries or updates â†’ Stage 3, 2D prefix or 2D difference array
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Constraint Triggers:</strong><br>
                        â€¢ N â‰¤ 10âµ with Q â‰¤ 10âµ queries AND updates â†’ Stage 5; static prefix rebuild is O(n) per update â†’ use Fenwick tree<br>
                        â€¢ Values up to 10â¹ and N â‰¤ 10âµ with no updates â†’ Stage 1â€“4; static prefix is fine
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Anti-Triggers (when NOT to use prefix sums):</strong><br>
                        ðŸš© "maximum subarray" or "maximum of subarray [i..j]" â†’ NOT prefix sum (max has no inverse) â†’ Kadane's algorithm or sparse table (static) or segment tree (dynamic)<br>
                        ðŸš© "number of subarrays with sum â‰¥ k" â†’ NOT hash-map prefix (inequality â‰  equality) â†’ Monotone deque on prefix (LC 862) or binary search + BIT<br>
                        ðŸš© "sum of all subsets" â†’ NOT prefix sum; it's a bitmask/combinatorics problem counting each element's contribution across 2â¿ subsets
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Decision Framework</div>
                    <div class="core-box" style="font-family:monospace;font-size:.88em;white-space:pre-wrap;line-height:1.55">
<strong>Q1:</strong> Does the problem ask about a contiguous range (subarray,
    submatrix, path segment) of an array/grid?
  â†’ NO:  Not a prefix sum problem. Stop.
  â†’ YES: Continue.

<strong>Q2:</strong> Are there UPDATES to array values between queries?
  â†’ YES: Go to Q8 (dynamic prefix â€” Stage 5).
  â†’ NO:  Continue.

<strong>Q3:</strong> Is the query asking for RANGE SUM (or equivalent: XOR,
    product, count of property)?
  â†’ NO:  Go to Q7.
  â†’ YES: Continue.

<strong>Q4:</strong> Is the answer a single range sum value?
  â†’ YES: Stage 1 â€” build prefix array, answer = prefix[j+1] âˆ’ prefix[i].
         Expected complexity: O(n) build + O(1)/query.
  â†’ NO:  Continue (you need to count pairs or find a target).

<strong>Q5:</strong> Is the condition an EQUALITY (sum = k, sum % k = 0, XOR = k)?
  â†’ YES: Stage 2 â€” hash map on prefix values.
         Key: transform "sum(i,j) = k" â†’ "prefix[j] âˆ’ k exists in map".
         Expected complexity: O(n).
  â†’ NO:  Go to Q6.

<strong>Q6:</strong> Is the condition an INEQUALITY (sum â‰¥ k, sum in [lo, hi])?
  â†’ YES: âš ï¸ Hash map BREAKS here.
         Stage 5 â€” monotone deque (if sliding window) or
         merge sort / BIT with coordinate compression (if arbitrary).
         Expected complexity: O(n log n).
  â†’ NO:  Recheck problem statement.

<strong>Q7:</strong> Are you applying RANGE UPDATES (add v to [l,r]) and then
    reading point values?
  â†’ YES: Stage 3 â€” difference array.
         diff[l] += v, diff[r+1] âˆ’= v; final values = prefix sum of diff.
         Expected complexity: O(n + q).
  â†’ NO:  Is the input 2D?
         â†’ YES: Stage 3 â€” 2D prefix or 2D difference array.
         â†’ NO:  Does the problem have a hidden linear structure?
                â†’ YES: Stage 4 â€” identify the transformation first.

<strong>Q8 (Dynamic):</strong> Do you need POINT UPDATES + PREFIX QUERIES?
  â†’ YES: Stage 5 â€” Fenwick tree (BIT). O(log n) per op.
  â†’ NO:  Do you need RANGE UPDATES + RANGE QUERIES?
         â†’ YES: Stage 5 â€” Segment tree with lazy propagation.
                Expected complexity: O(log n) per op.

<strong>Stage identification summary:</strong>
  Q4 YES â†’ Stage 1. O(n) build, O(1) query.
  Q5 YES â†’ Stage 2. O(n) total.
  Q7 YES â†’ Stage 3. O(n+q).
  Hidden transform needed â†’ Stage 4. O(n) after transform.
  Updates present â†’ Stage 5. O(log n) per op.
  If your solution is slower than these bounds, look for the
  Stage 5 data structure optimisation.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">When This Technique BREAKS</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>Range MAX or MIN queries (no inverse exists)</strong> â€” max(i..j) cannot be expressed as f(prefix[j]) âˆ’ f(prefix[i]) because max has no inverse operation. [Stage 1â€“2 mistake] â†’ Sparse Table (O(1), static) or Segment Tree (O(log n), dynamic).</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>Inequality conditions on subarray sums (â‰¥ k, â‰¤ k, âˆˆ [lo,hi])</strong> â€” Hash map lookup requires exact equality. [Stage 2 mistake] â†’ Monotone Deque for contiguous window variants; Merge Sort on Prefix Array / BIT with coordinate compression for arbitrary ranges.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>Dynamic updates to the array (online, streaming)</strong> â€” Rebuilding the entire prefix array after each update is O(n) per update = O(nq) total. [Stage 5 mistake] â†’ Fenwick Tree (BIT) for point updates + prefix queries; Segment Tree for range updates + range queries.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>Non-associative operations (e.g. GCD, LCM of a range)</strong> â€” GCD has no simple inverse (gcd(a,b) âˆ’ gcd(a,c) â‰  gcd(b,c)). [Stage 1 mistake] â†’ Sparse Table for static GCD/LCM range queries in O(1).</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>2D difference array with overlapping boundaries</strong> â€” A common Stage 3 mistake is applying 1D logic to 2D â€” forgetting the +v at (r2+1, c2+1) (inclusion-exclusion term). [Stage 3 mistake] â†’ Always derive the 2D formula from first principles: four corners, alternating signs.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>Circular/wrap-around subarrays</strong> â€” prefix[j] âˆ’ prefix[i] breaks when the subarray wraps around index 0. [Stage 2 mistake] â†’ Handle as total_sum âˆ’ (non-wrapping complement), or double the array and apply standard prefix on arr + arr.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>Very large axis (up to 10â¹) with sparse updates</strong> â€” A static array of size 10â¹ causes MLE. [Stage 5 mistake] â†’ Coordinate-compress endpoints to O(q) distinct values, then apply difference array or BIT on compressed indices.</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Proof of Correctness Skeleton</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 1 â€” 1D Range Sum (Telescoping Invariant)</strong><br>
                        <em>Claim:</em> prefix[j] âˆ’ prefix[i] = a[i+1] + ... + a[j] for all 0 â‰¤ i â‰¤ j.<br>
                        <em>Proof by definition and telescoping:</em> Define prefix[0] = 0; prefix[k] = prefix[kâˆ’1] + a[k] for k â‰¥ 1. Then prefix[j] âˆ’ prefix[i] = (a[1]+...+a[j]) âˆ’ (a[1]+...+a[i]) = a[i+1]+...+a[j]. â–¡<br>
                        <em>Note:</em> Correctness is unconditional â€” no edge cases beyond index bounds.
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 2 â€” Subarray Sum Equals K (Hash Map Correctness)</strong><br>
                        <em>Claim:</em> The running hash-map algorithm counts exactly the number of pairs (i,j) with i &lt; j and sum(i+1..j) = k.<br>
                        <em>Proof by invariant maintenance:</em><br>
                        â€¢ Invariant: at step j, freq[v] = number of indices i â‰¤ j with prefix[i] = v.<br>
                        â€¢ At each step, we query freq[prefix[j] âˆ’ k] = number of i &lt; j with prefix[i] = prefix[j] âˆ’ k = number of valid left endpoints for subarrays ending at j.<br>
                        â€¢ We initialise freq[0] = 1 (empty prefix at i=0), ensuring subarrays starting from index 1 are counted.<br>
                        â€¢ We update freq[prefix[j]] AFTER querying, preventing i = j from being counted. â–¡
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 3 â€” Difference Array (Inverse Correctness)</strong><br>
                        <em>Claim:</em> After applying all (l, r, v) operations to diff, computing prefix_sum(diff) recovers the final array value at every index.<br>
                        <em>Proof by linearity:</em> Each operation contributes v to every index in [l, r]. Encoding as diff[l] += v, diff[r+1] âˆ’= v means prefix_sum(diff)[i] = Î£ v over all operations where l â‰¤ i â‰¤ r. This holds because for operation (l, r, v), prefix sum accumulates v starting at l (where it was added) and stops at r+1 (where it was subtracted). The contribution to index i is v iff l â‰¤ i â‰¤ r. â–¡
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Implementation Pitfalls (Code-Level)</div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 1 (Stage 1) â€” Off-by-one: 0-indexed vs 1-indexed prefix array</strong>
