                 TOPIC 8 â€” BACKTRACKING (MASTERY)
            â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â• -->
            <div class="topic-card" id="tp8">
                <div class="topic-header">
                    <div class="topic-num">08</div>
                    <div style="flex:1">
                        <div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:.5rem;flex-wrap:wrap">
                            <div class="topic-title">Backtracking</div>
                            <span class="tier-badge tier-T1">Algorithms</span>
                            <span class="topic-type">Recursion Â· Constraint Search Â· Pruning Â· Bitmask Â· DLX</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="topic-meta">30 problems Â· 5 stages Â· subsets, permutations, grid, CSP, memoised backtracking</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="topic-body">
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Why It Matters:</strong> Backtracking is <em>systematic constrained search with undo</em> â€” the universal algorithm for problems where you must explore a decision tree, commit to choices one at a time, and retract them when they violate constraints or exhaust possibilities. The core invariant is: at every node in the decision tree, the partial solution is valid; when a dead end is reached, exactly one decision is undone and the next alternative is tried. It appears in every top-tier interview because it tests recursive reasoning, state management, pruning intuition, and the ability to convert a combinatorial description into executable code. At ICPC/IOI, backtracking with aggressive pruning (branch-and-bound, constraint propagation) solves NP-complete problems like SAT, graph colouring, and exact cover â€” appearing in competitions disguised as scheduling, placement, or configuration problems.</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">The Mental Model</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Backtracking is building a sentence word by word.</strong> At each position you try every valid word, write it down, move to the next position, and erase it when you get stuck â€” trying the next word instead. You never erase more than the last word you wrote.<br><br>
                        <strong>How the mental model scales through the 5 stages:</strong><br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 1:</strong> You choose from a fixed set at each position; every choice is independent. The "sentence" is a permutation or combination.<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 2:</strong> One constraint flips â€” elements can repeat, or you can't reuse the same position, or order doesn't matter. The choice set shrinks by one rule.<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 3:</strong> The state itself becomes 2-dimensional â€” you're filling a grid, a board, or making choices across two linked structures simultaneously.<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 4:</strong> The problem doesn't say "enumerate" or "find all." It says "is it possible?" or "find minimum cuts." You must recognise that the search space IS a backtracking tree, hidden inside a constraint satisfaction or optimisation problem.<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 5:</strong> The naive tree is too wide â€” exponential branches at every node. Pruning transforms it: constraint propagation eliminates branches before exploring them, memoisation collapses subtrees, or bitmask DP replaces the explicit tree.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Core Invariant &amp; Proof Sketch</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Invariant:</strong> At every recursive call <code>backtrack(state, choices)</code>, the partial state satisfies all constraints imposed so far, and <code>choices</code> is exactly the set of valid extensions of state.<br><br>
                        <strong>Soundness:</strong> Every solution added to the result satisfies all constraints because we only add when the base case is reached AND all constraints have been checked at each decision point. No invalid partial state is ever extended.<br><br>
                        <strong>Completeness:</strong> Every valid solution is found because the algorithm explores ALL branches of the decision tree â€” it never skips a valid extension. Pruning only eliminates subtrees that can be proven to contain zero valid solutions.<br><br>
                        <strong>Termination:</strong> The recursion depth is bounded by the solution length (at most n), and at each level the choice set strictly decreases (each element is either used or the index advances). The tree is finite.<br><br>
                        <strong>Undo correctness:</strong> The undo step restores the state to exactly what it was before the choice, because backtracking modifies state in exactly one way per call and reverts that exact modification. This is the key implementation invariant â€” <em>state before = state after</em> for any failed branch.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Sub-Variants to Master (18 total)</div>
                    <div class="info-box" style="line-height:1.75">
                        <strong>1. Subsets / power set enumeration</strong> â€” Stage 1 Â· O(2â¿ Â· n) Â· recursion with include/exclude Â· <em>New idea:</em> binary choice tree â€” include element or skip it<br>
                        <strong>2. Combinations (choose k of n)</strong> â€” Stage 1 Â· O(C(n,k) Â· k) Â· recursion with start-index Â· <em>New idea:</em> start-index parameter prevents reusing earlier elements<br>
                        <strong>3. Permutations (all orderings)</strong> â€” Stage 1 Â· O(n! Â· n) Â· recursion with visited array Â· <em>New idea:</em> visited/used array tracks which elements are placed<br>
                        <strong>4. Subsets with duplicates</strong> â€” Stage 2 Â· O(2â¿ Â· n) Â· sort + skip-duplicate Â· <em>New idea:</em> sort input first; skip nums[i]==nums[iâˆ’1] at same recursion level<br>
                        <strong>5. Combinations with duplicates</strong> â€” Stage 2 Â· O(2â¿ Â· k) Â· sort + skip-duplicate Â· <em>New idea:</em> same duplicate-skip logic applied to combinations<br>
