                    <div class="sec-title">Custom Problem Statement</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>ðŸ”§ Bridge Problem â€” Backtracking with Constraint Propagation (Stage 4â†’5 bridge):</strong> You are given an NÃ—N grid. Place exactly K non-attacking rooks such that no two rooks share a row or column, AND each rook must be placed in a white cell (cells are 0 = black or 1 = white). Return the count of valid placements.<br>
                        <strong>Constraints:</strong> 1 â‰¤ N â‰¤ 8, 1 â‰¤ K â‰¤ N.<br>
                        <strong>Example:</strong> N=3, K=2, grid=[[1,0,1],[0,1,0],[1,1,1]] â†’ 6.<br>
                        <strong>Intended solution:</strong> Backtrack row by row. At row r, try each column c where grid[r][c]==1 and col_used[c]==False. Mark col_used[c]=True, recurse to r+1, unmark. Base case: placed K rooks â†’ count++. Pruning: if remaining_rows &lt; K âˆ’ placed, return (can't place enough). Bridges Stage 3 (N-Queens structure) into Stage 4 (recognising applicability in a new domain) with Stage 5 entry-level pruning.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Pattern Recognition Triggers</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Linguistic Triggers:</strong><br>
                        â€¢ "generate all / enumerate all / find all possible" â†’ Stage 1/2 â€” exhaustive enumeration of a decision tree<br>
                        â€¢ "partition into groups / segments / subsets satisfying [constraint]" â†’ Stage 3/4 â€” partitioning backtracking; each decision splits the input<br>
                        â€¢ "place N pieces on a board such that no two [conflict]" â†’ Stage 3 â€” placement backtracking with conflict sets<br>
                        â€¢ "is it possible to [reach / form / achieve] using [limited resources]" â†’ Stage 4 â€” feasibility search; decision tree over resource allocation<br>
                        â€¢ "restore / reconstruct / decode all valid [strings/sequences]" â†’ Stage 4 â€” reconstruction backtracking; validity check gates each branch
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Structural Triggers:</strong><br>
                        â€¢ Output is <code>List[List[...]]</code> (all combinations, all partitions) â†’ backtracking with path collection at base case<br>
                        â€¢ Output is a single boolean ("is it possible?") with no polynomial algorithm obvious â†’ backtracking with early-exit on first valid solution<br>
                        â€¢ Input is a small N (â‰¤ 20) with exponential search space but no DP state definition â†’ backtracking with pruning
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Constraint Triggers:</strong><br>
                        â€¢ N â‰¤ 20 with output as a count or existence â†’ backtracking (possibly with bitmask DP if overlapping subproblems detected)<br>
                        â€¢ N â‰¤ 9 for board-filling problems (Sudoku, N-Queens) â†’ backtracking with constraint sets; O(9^N) feasible
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Anti-Triggers (when NOT to use backtracking):</strong><br>
                        ðŸš© "minimum number of operations to reach target" â†’ NOT backtracking (exponential) â†’ BFS (unweighted) or Dijkstra (weighted)<br>
                        ðŸš© "count the number of ways to [fill / partition]" where N &gt; 20 â†’ NOT plain backtracking â†’ DP with memoisation; count is too large to enumerate<br>
                        ðŸš© "find the shortest path / minimum cost path" â†’ NOT backtracking â†’ BFS / Dijkstra / Bellman-Ford; backtracking has no shortest-path guarantee
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Decision Framework</div>
                    <div class="core-box" style="font-family:monospace;font-size:.88em;white-space:pre-wrap;line-height:1.55">
<strong>Q1:</strong> Does the problem ask to ENUMERATE, CONSTRUCT, or CHECK
    EXISTENCE of solutions in a combinatorial space?
  â†’ NO:  Not a backtracking problem. Stop.
  â†’ YES: Continue.

<strong>Q2:</strong> Is N â‰¤ ~20 (making exponential search feasible)?
  â†’ NO (N &gt; 20): Backtracking will TLE. Go to Q9 (DP/BFS alternative).
  â†’ YES: Continue.

<strong>Q3:</strong> Does the problem ask for ALL solutions or ONE solution?
  â†’ ALL: Full enumeration backtracking â€” collect at base case.
  â†’ ONE: Backtracking with EARLY EXIT on first valid solution.

<strong>Q4:</strong> Is the choice at each step drawn from a SET (subsets/combinations)
    or a SEQUENCE (permutations/orderings)?
  â†’ SET (order doesn't matter): Use START-INDEX to avoid revisiting.
    â†’ Reusable? YES â†’ pass same i. NO â†’ pass i+1.
    â†’ Duplicates? YES â†’ sort + same-level skip.
    â†’ Stage 1/2. O(2â¿) to O(n!).
  â†’ SEQUENCE (order matters): Use VISITED ARRAY.
    â†’ Duplicates? YES â†’ sort + skip if nums[i]==nums[i-1] and not used[i-1].
    â†’ Stage 1/2. O(n!).

<strong>Q5:</strong> Does the state involve a 2D GRID or BOARD?
  â†’ YES: Grid backtracking. Use 2D visited array or in-place marking.
    â†’ Fixed depth (N-Queens, Sudoku)? Use constraint SETS for O(1) checks.
    â†’ Variable path (Word Search)? Use DFS with visited marking.
    â†’ Stage 3. O(n!) to O(9^m).
  â†’ NO: Continue.

<strong>Q6:</strong> Is there a CONSTRAINT determining valid choices
    (not just "not visited")?
  â†’ YES: Constraint-guided backtracking.
    â†’ Can you PROPAGATE forward before recursing?
       YES â†’ Forward checking / constraint propagation (Stage 5).
       NO  â†’ Check at each node (Stage 3/4).
  â†’ NO: Pure enumeration (Stage 1/2).

<strong>Q7:</strong> Does the problem require tracking RUNNING STATE
    across decisions (e.g., running sum, current expression value)?
  â†’ YES: Stage 4 â€” pass running state as parameter; undo on backtrack.
         Watch for operator-precedence traps (Expression Add Operators).
  â†’ NO: Continue.

<strong>Q8:</strong> Are there OVERLAPPING SUBPROBLEMS in the search tree
    (same partial state reached via different paths)?
  â†’ YES: Stage 5 â€” add memoisation on the state (bitmask or tuple).
         This converts backtracking to bitmask DP.
         Expected: O(2â¿ Â· n).
  â†’ NO: Pure backtracking without memo.

<strong>Q9 (N too large):</strong> Can the problem be solved with DP, BFS, or greedy?
  â†’ DP: Overlapping subproblems with optimal substructure.
  â†’ BFS: Shortest path / minimum steps in state space.
  â†’ Greedy: Local optimal = global optimal (exchange argument holds).

<strong>Stage identification summary:</strong>
  Q4 (set/sequence, no grid) â†’ Stage 1/2. O(2â¿) to O(n!).
  Q5 (grid/board) â†’ Stage 3. O(n!) to O(9^m).
  Q7 (running state, disguised) â†’ Stage 4. Exponential with pruning.
  Q8 (overlapping subproblems) â†’ Stage 5. O(2â¿ Â· n).
  If your solution is slower than O(2â¿ Â· n) for N â‰¤ 20,
  look for the Stage 5 memoisation or pruning optimisation.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">When This Technique BREAKS</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 1] N &gt; 20 for enumeration problems</strong> â€” O(2Â²â°) â‰ˆ 10â¶ is feasible; O(2Â³â°) â‰ˆ 10â¹ is not. â†’ Use bitmask DP if overlapping subproblems, or meet-in-the-middle (split into two halves of size n/2, enumerate each, combine).</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 2] Counting problems with large N</strong> â€” Backtracking counts by enumerating every solution â€” O(result size), can be astronomical. Use DP where the count is accumulated without enumeration.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 3] Shortest-path or minimum-cost problems on a graph</strong> â€” Backtracking finds valid solutions but not minimum-cost ones efficiently. Use BFS (unweighted minimum steps) or Dijkstra (weighted).</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 4] Polynomial solutions disguised as search</strong> â€” Some "NP-hard-looking" problems have greedy or DP solutions. Always check: optimal substructure (â†’ DP), exchange argument (â†’ greedy) before reaching for backtracking.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 5] Backtracking without memoisation on repeated states</strong> â€” If same (remaining, constraint-state) is reached via multiple paths, pure backtracking recomputes it. Convert to memoised recursion / bitmask DP. Classic symptom: TLE on N â‰ˆ 15â€“20.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 3] Sudoku-style without constraint propagation</strong> â€” Bare backtracking Sudoku is O(9^81) worst case. Without "only try digits missing from row/col/box," TLE on hard puzzles. Forward checking is mandatory at this stage.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 5] Undo bugs making state corrupted</strong> â€” If undo is incomplete (global variable modified in one branch, not restored), subsequent branches see corrupted state. Symptom: wrong answers that are hard to reproduce. Every mutation in the choose step must be explicitly reversed in unchoose.</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Proof of Correctness Skeleton</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 1 â€” Subset Enumeration (Invariant Maintenance)</strong><br>
                        <em>Claim:</em> <code>backtrack(i, path)</code> adds to result exactly all subsets of nums[i:] that extend path.<br>
                        <em>Proof by strong induction on n âˆ’ i:</em><br>
                        â€¢ <em>Base case</em> (i = n): No elements remain; path itself is the only valid extension â†’ add path to result. âœ“<br>
                        â€¢ <em>Inductive step:</em> Assume correct for all calls with i' &gt; i. At index i, we make two recursive calls: <em>include</em> â€” backtrack(i+1, path+[nums[i]]) correctly enumerates all subsets of nums[i+1:] extended by path+[nums[i]] by induction; <em>exclude</em> â€” backtrack(i+1, path) correctly enumerates all subsets of nums[i+1:] extended by path. Together they cover all subsets of nums[i:] extended by path. âœ“<br>
                        â€¢ <em>Completeness:</em> every include/exclude combination is tried. <em>No duplicates:</em> each path corresponds to a unique include/exclude sequence. â–¡
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 3 â€” N-Queens (Constraint-Set Invariant)</strong><br>
                        <em>Claim:</em> The algorithm places exactly one queen per row such that no two queens share a column, diagonal, or anti-diagonal.<br>
                        <em>Proof by invariant maintenance:</em><br>
                        â€¢ <em>Invariant:</em> Before placing queen in row r, sets cols, diag (râˆ’c), anti_diag (r+c) contain exactly the columns/diagonals attacked by queens in rows 0..râˆ’1.<br>
                        â€¢ <em>Placement:</em> we only place at column c if c âˆ‰ cols, (râˆ’c) âˆ‰ diag, (r+c) âˆ‰ anti_diag â€” ensuring no conflict.<br>
                        â€¢ <em>Update:</em> add c, râˆ’c, r+c to the three sets, maintaining invariant for row r+1.<br>
                        â€¢ <em>Undo:</em> after recursion, remove c, râˆ’c, r+c, restoring invariant for trying next column in row r. âœ“<br>
                        â€¢ <em>Completeness:</em> all columns 0..nâˆ’1 are tried for each row. No valid placement is skipped. â–¡
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 5 â€” Memoised Backtracking (Overlapping Subproblem Collapse)</strong><br>
                        <em>Claim:</em> Adding memoisation on (index, state) to backtracking produces the same result as without memoisation.<br>
                        <em>Proof by substitution:</em> If <code>backtrack(i, state)</code> is called twice with identical arguments, both operate on identical remaining choices and constraints. By the Stage 1 inductive proof, both produce identical results. Therefore storing and returning the cached result is correct. âœ“<br>
                        <em>Complexity improvement:</em> Without memo, the same (i, state) subtree may be recomputed exponentially many times. With memo, each unique (i, state) is computed once â†’ O(states Â· branching factor) total.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Implementation Pitfalls (Code-Level)</div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 1 (Stage 1) â€” Not copying the path when adding to results (reference bug)</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: all entries in result point to the same list object
