                 TOPIC 9 â€” GREEDY (MASTERY)
            â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â• -->
            <div class="topic-card" id="tp9">
                <div class="topic-header">
                    <div class="topic-num">09</div>
                    <div style="flex:1">
                        <div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:.5rem;flex-wrap:wrap">
                            <div class="topic-title">Greedy</div>
                            <span class="tier-badge tier-T1">Algorithms</span>
                            <span class="topic-type">Exchange Argument Â· Sort Key Â· Heap Â· Regret Â· Matroid</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="topic-meta">32 problems Â· 5 stages Â· activity selection, heap greedy, regret, matroid, greedy + binary search</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="topic-body">
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Why It Matters:</strong> Greedy algorithms make the locally optimal choice at each step â€” the proof that local optimality cascades into global optimality is an <em>exchange argument</em>: any optimal solution can be transformed into the greedy solution by swapping choices one at a time without worsening the result. Greedy is the most dangerous topic in competitive programming because it is simultaneously the easiest to apply and the easiest to apply wrongly â€” a greedy that looks correct on examples can fail on a single adversarial case. It appears in every Google interview because it tests mathematical reasoning (can you prove your greedy?), not just implementation. At ICPC/IOI, the hardest greedy problems require recognising that a problem with no obvious greedy structure reduces to a canonical greedy form (scheduling, matroid, exchange-argument) after a non-obvious transformation.</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">The Mental Model</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Greedy is a vending machine that always dispenses the "best available" item.</strong> The key question is never "which item is best?" â€” it's "what does 'best' mean in this problem, and does picking it now guarantee we never regret it later?"<br><br>
                        <strong>How the mental model scales through the 5 stages:</strong><br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 1:</strong> "Best" is obvious â€” largest value, smallest cost, earliest deadline. Pick greedily in sorted order. No regret possible.<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 2:</strong> "Best" changes based on one flipped constraint â€” earliest end instead of largest value, or smallest ratio instead of smallest absolute value. The sort key changes; the algorithm skeleton is identical.<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 3:</strong> Two competing greedy criteria must be balanced simultaneously. The state tracks two quantities; the sort key is a composite function of both.<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 4:</strong> The problem doesn't look like a greedy problem. You must first transform the input or reframe the objective before the "best available" principle becomes visible.<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 5:</strong> The greedy choice requires knowing the current minimum/maximum of a dynamic set â€” a data structure (heap, segment tree, sorted set) makes each greedy step O(log n) instead of O(n).
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Core Invariant &amp; Proof Sketch â€” The Exchange Argument</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Invariant:</strong> Let G = greedy solution, O = any optimal solution. We show G is at least as good as O.<br><br>
                        <strong>3-step template applicable to ANY greedy problem:</strong><br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Step 1 (Align):</strong> Order both solutions by the greedy sort key. Find the first position k where G and O differ â€” G chose element g, O chose element o, with greedy_key(g) â‰¤ greedy_key(o) (G chose "better" by its criterion).<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Step 2 (Exchange):</strong> Swap o for g in O at position k. Show that after the swap, O' is still a valid solution AND cost(O') â‰¤ cost(O) (or value(O') â‰¥ value(O)). The entire proof lives here.<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Step 3 (Iterate):</strong> Repeat until O has been transformed into G. Since each swap didn't worsen O, cost(G) â‰¤ cost(O). Since O was optimal, G is also optimal. â–¡<br><br>
                        <strong>Why this matters:</strong> If you cannot execute Step 2, your greedy is wrong. The exchange argument IS the proof. Every greedy problem at Google requires you to sketch this argument when asked "how do you know this is correct?"
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Sub-Variants to Master (15 total)</div>
                    <div class="info-box" style="line-height:1.75">
                        <strong>1. Sort + linear scan (activity selection)</strong> â€” Stage 1 Â· O(n log n) Â· sort array Â· <em>New idea:</em> sort by end time; keep if start â‰¥ last end<br>
                        <strong>2. Sort by ratio / composite key (fractional knapsack)</strong> â€” Stage 1 Â· O(n log n) Â· sort by value/weight Â· <em>New idea:</em> sort key is a ratio, not a raw value<br>
                        <strong>3. Two-pointer greedy (matching min to max)</strong> â€” Stage 2 Â· O(n log n) Â· two pointers on sorted array Â· <em>New idea:</em> optimal pairing uses two sorted ends simultaneously<br>
                        <strong>4. Greedy with constraint flip (earliest deadline first)</strong> â€” Stage 2 Â· O(n log n) Â· sort by deadline Â· <em>New idea:</em> sort key changes from value to deadline; same skeleton, different comparator<br>
                        <strong>5. Prefix-greedy (always extend current reach)</strong> â€” Stage 2 Â· O(n) Â· linear scan with reach variable Â· <em>New idea:</em> maintain max_reach greedily; answer is steps taken when reach is exhausted<br>
                        <strong>6. Stack-based greedy (remove to optimise)</strong> â€” Stage 3 Â· O(n) Â· monotone stack Â· <em>New idea:</em> greedy removal uses a stack to maintain order; each element compared to stack top<br>
                        <strong>7. Heap-based greedy (always process best available)</strong> â€” Stage 3 Â· O(n log n) Â· min/max heap Â· <em>New idea:</em> "best available" is dynamic â€” heap maintains sorted order across insertions<br>
                        <strong>8. Two-heap greedy (balance two populations)</strong> â€” Stage 3 Â· O(n log n) Â· two heaps Â· <em>New idea:</em> two competing criteria; median or balance point maintained via dual heaps<br>
                        <strong>9. Greedy on sorted events (sweep line)</strong> â€” Stage 3 Â· O(n log n) Â· sort events + active set Â· <em>New idea:</em> process start/end events in order; greedy assigns resources at each event<br>
                        <strong>10. Greedy with exchange argument on strings</strong> â€” Stage 4 Â· O(n log n) Â· custom comparator sort Â· <em>New idea:</em> comparator derived from exchange argument, not natural order (e.g., ab &lt; ba iff a+b &lt; b+a)<br>
                        <strong>11. Regret-based greedy (undo a previous choice)</strong> â€” Stage 4 Â· O(n log n) Â· heap + virtual undo Â· <em>New idea:</em> make a greedy choice, then "undo" it by adding a negative-weight virtual item; enables globally optimal correction<br>
                        <strong>12. Matroid greedy (independent set maximisation)</strong> â€” Stage 4 Â· O(n log n) Â· sort + independence oracle Â· <em>New idea:</em> greedy on a matroid is always optimal; recognising matroid structure IS the insight<br>
                        <strong>13. Greedy + binary search (optimise the sort-key threshold)</strong> â€” Stage 5 Â· O(n logÂ² n) Â· binary search on answer + greedy check Â· <em>New idea:</em> binary search on a parameter; greedy verifies feasibility at each midpoint<br>
                        <strong>14. Greedy + segment tree (range min/max for greedy choice)</strong> â€” Stage 5 Â· O(n log n) Â· segment tree Â· <em>New idea:</em> greedy choice requires range query on dynamic set; segment tree replaces O(n) scan<br>
                        <strong>15. Online greedy (decisions without future knowledge)</strong> â€” Stage 5 Â· O(n log n) Â· sorted set / BIT Â· <em>New idea:</em> items arrive in stream; greedy must use only past information; sorted set enables O(log n) best-match lookup
                    </div>

