                    <div class="sec-title">Custom Problem Statement (#29)</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>ðŸ”§ Weighted Matroid Greedy â€” Maximum Weight Spanning Forest (Stage 4):</strong> Given an undirected graph with N vertices and M weighted edges, find the maximum-weight spanning forest (a set of edges with no cycle, not necessarily connected, with maximum total weight).<br>
                        <strong>Constraints:</strong> 2 â‰¤ N â‰¤ 10âµ, 1 â‰¤ M â‰¤ 3Ã—10âµ, 1 â‰¤ weight â‰¤ 10â¹.<br>
                        <strong>Example:</strong> N=4, M=5, edges=[(1,2,10), (2,3,6), (1,3,5), (3,4,4), (1,4,3)] â†’ 20 (edges: (1,2,10) + (2,3,6) + (3,4,4)).<br>
                        <strong>Intended solution:</strong> Sort edges by weight descending. Greedily add each edge if it doesn't form a cycle (Union-Find check). This is Kruskal's algorithm for maximum spanning forest. <em>Why greedy works:</em> the set of acyclic subgraphs of a graph forms a graphic matroid â€” and greedy always finds the maximum-weight independent set in a matroid. <em>Exchange argument:</em> any two spanning forests of the same size can exchange edges one at a time without losing the forest property.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Pattern Recognition Triggers</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Linguistic Triggers:</strong><br>
                        â€¢ "minimum number of [operations / jumps / arrows] to [achieve]" â†’ Stage 1/2 greedy â€” activity selection or reach-extension; local minimum choice is never regretted<br>
                        â€¢ "maximum number of [events / tasks / intervals] you can [attend / complete]" â†’ Stage 2/3 â€” activity selection sorted by end time; heap for dynamic scheduling<br>
                        â€¢ "arrange / order / sequence to [maximise / minimise] total" â†’ Stage 4 â€” sort key derived from exchange argument; comparator aÂ·B vs bÂ·A or a+b vs b+a<br>
                        â€¢ "at each step, you can [action]; find minimum steps" â†’ Stage 2 â€” prefix-reach greedy; reach = max(reach, f(i))<br>
                        â€¢ "assign [resources] to [tasks] optimally" â†’ Stage 3/5 â€” heap-based greedy; assign best-available resource at each step
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Structural Triggers:</strong><br>
                        â€¢ Input is a list of items each with two attributes (value + weight, start + end, cost_A + cost_B) â†’ sort by a function of both attributes; exchange argument determines the function<br>
                        â€¢ Output is a single number (min count, max count) NOT a specific arrangement â†’ likely greedy with proof, not backtracking<br>
                        â€¢ Problem has a "never regret" property visible in examples (choosing X now never prevents a better choice later) â†’ greedy applicable
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Constraint Triggers:</strong><br>
                        â€¢ N â‰¤ 10âµ with no obvious DP state â†’ greedy is the intended solution; DP states would require O(nÂ²) or more<br>
                        â€¢ Items have two attributes and you must select ALL items (not a subset) in an optimal order â†’ custom comparator sort; exchange argument for sort key
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Anti-Triggers (when NOT to use greedy):</strong><br>
                        ðŸš© "maximum value subset of weight â‰¤ W" â†’ NOT greedy (fractional knapsack is greedy, 0/1 knapsack is NOT) â†’ use 0/1 Knapsack DP<br>
                        ðŸš© "minimum cost path from source to destination" â†’ NOT greedy scan â†’ Dijkstra (non-negative) / Bellman-Ford (negative)<br>
                        ðŸš© "number of ways to [achieve target]" â†’ NOT greedy (greedy gives one way, not a count) â†’ DP with counting recurrence
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Decision Framework</div>
                    <div class="core-box" style="font-family:monospace;font-size:.88em;white-space:pre-wrap;line-height:1.55">
<strong>Q1:</strong> Does the problem ask for an OPTIMAL (min/max) outcome achievable
    by making sequential choices?
  â†’ NO:  Not a greedy problem. Stop.
  â†’ YES: Continue.

<strong>Q2:</strong> Does the problem have OPTIMAL SUBSTRUCTURE without OVERLAPPING
    SUBPROBLEMS (i.e., choices don't interact with each other)?
  â†’ NO (choices interact): â†’ Use DP.
  â†’ YES (choices are independent once sorted): Continue.

<strong>Q3:</strong> Can you identify a SORT KEY such that processing in that order
    never creates regret (a later element is NEVER hurt by an earlier choice)?
  â†’ YES (obvious: end time, ratio, etc.): â†’ Stage 1/2.
     Sort, then linear scan. Expected: O(n log n).
  â†’ MAYBE (sort key requires exchange argument): â†’ Stage 4.
     Derive comparator: "does choosing a before b improve result?"

<strong>Q4:</strong> Does the greedy choice depend on the CURRENT BEST AVAILABLE item
    in a DYNAMIC collection (items arrive over time or are unlocked)?
  â†’ YES: â†’ Stage 3/5 â€” use a HEAP.
     Min-heap if smallest-cost; max-heap if largest-value.
     Expected: O(n log n).
  â†’ NO: Continue.

<strong>Q5:</strong> Does making a greedy choice sometimes turn out to be WRONG
    and need to be UNDONE based on future information?
  â†’ YES: â†’ Stage 4 â€” REGRET GREEDY.
     Make the greedy choice; push an "undo token" to a heap;
     if a better option arrives, swap via the heap.
     Examples: Course Schedule III, Furthest Building, Min Refueling Stops.
  â†’ NO: Continue.

<strong>Q6:</strong> Is the problem a STRING ORDERING or ARRANGEMENT problem?
  â†’ YES: â†’ Stage 4 â€” EXCHANGE ARGUMENT COMPARATOR.
     For two items a, b, ask: "Is a+b better than b+a?"
     Derive the comparator from this comparison.
     Sort by custom comparator. Expected: O(n log n).
  â†’ NO: Continue.

<strong>Q7:</strong> Is the greedy check INSIDE a binary search on the answer?
  â†’ YES: â†’ Stage 5 â€” GREEDY + BINARY SEARCH.
     Binary search on threshold/count; greedy verifies feasibility.
     Expected: O(n logÂ² n) or O(n log n Â· log(value_range)).
  â†’ NO: â†’ Stage 5 â€” GREEDY + SEGMENT TREE / SORTED SET.
     Greedy choice requires range min/max on dynamic collection.

<strong>Stage identification summary:</strong>
  Q3 YES (obvious sort key) â†’ Stage 1/2. O(n log n).
  Q4 YES (dynamic heap) â†’ Stage 3. O(n log n).
  Q5 YES (regret/undo) â†’ Stage 4. O(n log n).
  Q6 YES (string comparator) â†’ Stage 4. O(n log n).
  Q7 YES (binary search wrapper) â†’ Stage 5. O(n logÂ² n).
  If your solution is O(nÂ²), look for the heap or sorted-set
  optimisation that makes each greedy step O(log n).
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">When This Technique BREAKS</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 1] 0/1 Knapsack disguised as fractional knapsack</strong> â€” Greedy by value/weight ratio is optimal for fractional but provably WRONG for 0/1. Always check: are items divisible? If not, use 0/1 Knapsack DP.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 1] Activity selection with weighted intervals</strong> â€” Greedy (sort by end, take non-overlapping) maximises COUNT but not total WEIGHT. For weighted intervals, use Weighted Job Scheduling DP (sort by end + binary search + DP).</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 2] Greedy on circular arrays without handling wrap-around</strong> â€” Circular problems (Gas Station, circular interval coverage) silently fail without wrap-around handling. Strategy: run the greedy twice on the doubled array, or use the "total feasibility + start-point" two-observation approach.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 3] Greedy on strings without the exchange-argument comparator</strong> â€” Alphabetical or length-based order for "largest number" or "minimum cost arrangement" gives wrong answers. Always derive the comparator from the exchange argument: a+b vs b+a.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 4] Regret greedy without the "virtual undo" mechanism</strong> â€” Problems like Min Refueling Stops require decisions that look non-greedy. Without the deferred-decision heap mechanism, the solution seems to require DP. Recognise: "collect all options passed; pick best when forced to decide."</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 4] Exchange argument comparator that is not a total order</strong> â€” If a &lt; b is not transitive or antisymmetric, std::sort / Python's sorted gives undefined behaviour. Always verify: key(a) &lt; key(b) and key(b) &lt; key(c) implies key(a) &lt; key(c).</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 5] Greedy + binary search: checking feasibility incorrectly</strong> â€” A bug in the inner greedy check produces a wrong binary-search boundary. Test the greedy check independently before wrapping in binary search.</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Proof of Correctness Skeleton</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 1 â€” Activity Selection (Exchange Argument)</strong><br>
                        <em>Claim:</em> Sorting by end time and greedily keeping non-overlapping intervals maximises the count.<br>
                        â€¢ Let G = greedy solution (sorted by end), O = optimal (same sort). Suppose they first differ at position k: G chose interval g, O chose o, with end(g) â‰¤ end(o).<br>
                        â€¢ Swap o for g in O â†’ O'. Since end(g) â‰¤ end(o), interval g ends no later than o. Therefore any interval compatible with o after k is also compatible with g. O' is valid and |O'| = |O|.<br>
                        â€¢ Repeat for all differing positions. G transforms to O without reducing count. âˆ´ G is optimal. â–¡
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 4 â€” Largest Number (String Comparator)</strong><br>
                        <em>Claim:</em> Sorting strings by the comparator a+b &gt; b+a produces the largest concatenation.<br>
                        â€¢ Consider any two adjacent strings a, b in the sorted order. If a+b â‰¥ b+a, then a comes before b.<br>
                        â€¢ Swapping them produces ...b+a... whose concatenation is â‰¤ ...a+b.... So no swap improves the result â€” sorted order is globally optimal by the bubble-sort argument.<br>
                        â€¢ <em>Transitivity:</em> must be verified; string concatenation comparison over the same alphabet IS transitive. â–¡
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 4 â€” Regret Greedy: Minimum Refueling Stops</strong><br>
                        <em>Claim:</em> The "collect all passed stations in max-heap, refuel from best when empty" strategy minimises refueling stops.<br>
                        â€¢ <em>Invariant:</em> At every moment, the heap holds exactly the stations we could have refueled at and are still available for retrospective use.<br>
                        â€¢ Retrospectively choosing the highest-capacity passed station is equivalent to having made the optimal real-time choice at that station.<br>
                        â€¢ <em>Proof:</em> Consider any optimal O that refuels at station i before our greedy does. Our greedy has the same tank level when reaching i (same route, same prior choices). If greedy later picks a higher-capacity station j &gt; i, it has at least as much fuel at all subsequent points. â–¡
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Implementation Pitfalls (Code-Level)</div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 1 (Stage 1) â€” Activity selection: sorting by START instead of END</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: sorts by start â€” classic wrong answer
intervals.sort(key=lambda x: x[0])
# FIX: sort by END time
intervals.sort(key=lambda x: x[1])</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 2 (Stage 2) â€” Jump Game II: incrementing steps at wrong position</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: steps for every index, not every jump boundary
for i in range(n):
    next_end = max(next_end, i + nums[i])
    steps += 1
# FIX: step only when crossing current boundary
    if i == cur_end and i &lt; n - 1:
        steps += 1
        cur_end = next_end</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 3 (Stage 2) â€” Gas Station: not resetting tank when finding new start</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: tank carries over across candidate start resets
for i in range(n):
    tank += gas[i] - cost[i]
    if tank &lt; 0:
        start = i + 1
        # tank = 0  â† MISSING
# FIX: reset tank to 0 when choosing new start
        tank = 0</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 4 (Stage 1) â€” Two City Scheduling: sorting with wrong sign</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># Correct: ascending on (cost_A - cost_B) â†’ small diff = cheaper for A, goes to A
people.sort(key=lambda x: x[0] - x[1])
# BUG: flipped sign sends the wrong half to A
people.sort(key=lambda x: x[1] - x[0])</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 5 (Stage 4) â€” Largest Number: using integer comparison instead of string concat</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: plain numeric/lexicographic sort
nums.sort(reverse=True)
# FIX: compare as concatenated strings
from functools import cmp_to_key
nums.sort(key=cmp_to_key(
    lambda a, b: 1 if str(a)+str(b) &gt; str(b)+str(a) else -1),
    reverse=True)</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 6 (Stage 3) â€” Task Scheduler: formula misses when all frequencies equal</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: formula can be less than len(tasks) when idle slots = 0
result = (max_freq - 1) * (n + 1) + count_max_freq
return result
# FIX: take max with actual task count
return max(result, len(tasks))</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 7 (Stage 3) â€” Meeting Rooms II: not reusing freed rooms</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: always pushes, never reuses
for start, end in intervals:
    heapq.heappush(heap, end)
# FIX: reuse freed room if available
for start, end in intervals:
    if heap and heap[0] &lt;= start:
        heapq.heapreplace(heap, end)
    else:
        heapq.heappush(heap, end)</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 8 (Stage 4) â€” Remove K Digits: not stripping leading zeros</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: "0200" returned as-is
result = ''.join(stack)
return result
# FIX:
return result.lstrip('0') or '0'</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 9 (Stage 4) â€” Course Schedule III: not tracking cumulative time</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: only checks single course fit; ignores cumulative
for duration, end in courses:
    if duration &lt;= end:
        taken.append(duration)
# FIX: track running total; regret-swap if exceeded
    total_time += duration
    heapq.heappush(max_heap, -duration)
    if total_time &gt; end:
        total_time += heapq.heappop(max_heap)  # pops largest</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 10 (Stage 5) â€” Minimize Deviation: forgetting to re-add halved max</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: pops max, halves it, but doesn't add back
while max_val % 2 == 0:
    sorted_set.remove(max_val)
    max_val //= 2
    # sorted_set.add(max_val)  â† MISSING
# FIX: always re-add the halved value
    sorted_set.add(max_val)
    deviation = sorted_set[-1] - sorted_set[0]</code></pre>
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Red Flags / Common Mistakes</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 1] Applying greedy to 0/1 knapsack</strong> â€” Ratio-based greedy is a common instinct. It is ONLY correct when items are divisible or structure is a matroid. For 0/1 knapsack, two medium items beat one large. <em>Correct model:</em> "Greedy on ratios requires provable independence â€” verify via exchange argument or matroid."</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 1] Forgetting that exchange argument requires TOTALITY</strong> â€” If the comparator is not transitive, sort() produces implementation-defined results. <em>Correct model:</em> "If a &lt; b and b &lt; c then a &lt; c. Test with three examples before trusting your comparator."</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 3] Not considering the regret mechanism</strong> â€” Min Refueling Stops and Course Schedule III LOOK like DP because "future info seems necessary." Regret greedy gives the optimal answer because the "best retrospective choice" equals the "best real-time choice." <em>Correct model:</em> "If the best retrospective and best real-time choice are the same element, regret greedy is correct."</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 4] Left-to-right greedy on digit problems</strong> â€” Remove K Digits, Monotone Increasing Digits require right-to-left or a monotone stack because cascading effects propagate rightward. <em>Correct model:</em> "Digit problems with cascading effects need a stack (to undo recent choices) or right-to-left processing."</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 4] Missing the input transformation</strong> â€” Jump Game variants, Min Taps, Talent Show require a non-trivial pre-processing step before greedy. <em>Correct model:</em> "First ask: what is the canonical form? Transform input, THEN apply greedy."</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 2] Using &lt; instead of &lt;= for interval overlap</strong> â€” Balloon problems use &lt;= (touching counts); meeting-room problems use &lt;. One character determines correctness. <em>Correct model:</em> "Always check: does the problem treat touching endpoints as overlapping? Match the comparator precisely."</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 3] Two-pass greedy: both passes in the same direction</strong> â€” For Candy, running both passes left-to-right misses the right-to-left constraint. <em>Correct model:</em> "Directional constraints require one pass in each direction; merge with max() to satisfy both simultaneously."</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Interviewer Follow-Up Questions</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 2 Follow-Ups (Constraint Mutations)</strong></div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Question</th><th>Intended Answer Direction</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>1</td><td>"What if each interval has a value â€” maximise total value of non-overlapping intervals?"</td><td>Greedy by end-time now fails (maximises COUNT not VALUE). Use Weighted Job Scheduling DP: sort by end, dp[i] = max(dp[iâˆ’1], val[i] + dp[last_non_overlap(i)]) with binary search.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>2</td><td>"What if the gas station problem is on a LINE, not a circle?"</td><td>No wrap-around; find leftmost start where running sum never goes negative. Single pass, O(n).</td></tr>
                        </tbody></table></div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 3 Follow-Ups (State Expansion)</strong></div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Question</th><th>Intended Answer Direction</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>3</td><td>"Extend Meeting Rooms II: each room has a capacity; tasks have worker-counts."</td><td>Heap stores (end_time, capacity); assign to the room with earliest end that has sufficient capacity. Sorted set or multi-key heap.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>4</td><td>"Task Scheduler but tasks have dependencies (must complete A before B)."</td><td>Frequency approach breaks â€” dependencies create a DAG. Use topological sort + greedy (always pick highest-frequency available task).</td></tr>
                        </tbody></table></div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 4 Follow-Ups (Hidden Reductions)</strong></div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Question</th><th>Intended Answer Direction</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>5</td><td>"Prove your Largest Number comparator is correct."</td><td>Exchange argument on any adjacent pair a, b: swapping produces b+a â‰¤ a+b by comparator. Since no swap improves, sorted order is globally optimal.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>6</td><td>"What if Candy requires each child gets at most 3 candies?"</td><td>Adds upper bound to directional greedy. Two-pass still works but each pass also enforces â‰¤ 3: min(max(left_pass, right_pass), 3) at each position.</td></tr>
                        </tbody></table></div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 5 Follow-Ups (Optimisation Pressure)</strong></div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Question</th><th>Intended Answer Direction</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>7</td><td>"Minimize Deviation: what if numbers can also be doubled (not just halved)?"</td><td>All odd numbers can be multiplied by 2 once (doubling more is wasteful). Normalise all odds first; then only halving is needed. Same algorithm.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>8</td><td>"What if tasks in the scheduler arrive online and you must schedule in real time?"</td><td>Same min-heap; tasks added as they arrive. This is Shortest Remaining Processing Time (SRPT) â€” optimal for minimising average completion time.</td></tr>
                        </tbody></table></div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Beyond Stage 5 (Adversarial / Distributed)</strong></div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Question</th><th>Intended Answer Direction</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>9</td><td>"You're scheduling tasks across 1000 machines in a distributed system. How does greedy scale?"</td><td>Each machine runs a local greedy scheduler; a global coordinator uses a heap of (next_available_time, machine_id). MapReduce-style partitioning: O(n log k) for k machines.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>10</td><td>"An adversary designs task sequences to maximise idle time in Task Scheduler. What's the worst case?"</td><td>All tasks frequency 1 and n large â†’ max idle. Adversary sets max_freq â‰ˆ ceil(total / (n+1)). Defence: no algorithm beats max(len(tasks), (max_freqâˆ’1)*(n+1)+count_max) â€” this bound is tight.</td></tr>
                        </tbody></table></div>

                    <div class="sec-title">3-Phase Mastery Plan</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Phase 1 â€” Solve (strictly by Stage across all sub-variants):</strong><br>
