                    <div class="sec-title">Graduation Test</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        These three problems are NOT in the table above. Solving all three cold (no hints, no editorial, 45 min each) certifies full mastery.<br><br>
                        <strong>Test 1 â€” LC 1686: Stone Game VI</strong> (Stage 3 + Stage 4)<br>
                        <em>Why valid:</em> The greedy is to sort stones by alice_value + bob_value descending and alternate picks. This is NOT obvious â€” sorting by either player's value alone is wrong. The sort key comes purely from the exchange argument: "does Alice gain more by taking stone i before j?" Deriving this cold proves Stage 4 mastery. Implementing the alternating simulation proves Stage 3.<br><br>
                        <strong>Test 2 â€” CF 1257E: The Contest</strong> (Stage 4 + Stage 5)<br>
                        <em>Why valid:</em> Requires binary searching on a threshold combined with a greedy feasibility check that itself needs a data structure. A candidate who has not internalised the "greedy inside binary search" pattern (Stage 5) will not recognise the approach. Solving cold under 45 minutes certifies Stage 4+5 fusion.<br><br>
                        <strong>Test 3 â€” USACO Gold: Rental Service</strong> (Stage 3 + Stage 4)<br>
                        <em>Why valid:</em> Disguises a multi-criteria greedy as a farm optimisation problem. Candidate must (1) recognise the greedy structure, (2) derive the correct ordering (sort cows by milk, high-milk cows rented first), and (3) use prefix sums to optimise matching. All three stages firing simultaneously on an unseen USACO problem is the highest bar for greedy mastery.
