            <!-- DP 30-42 -->
            <!-- â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•
                 TOPIC 30 â€” 1D LINEAR DP (MASTERY)
            â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â• -->
            <div class="topic-card" id="tp30">
                <div class="topic-header">
                    <div class="topic-num">30</div>
                    <div style="flex:1">
                        <div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:.5rem;flex-wrap:wrap">
                            <div class="topic-title">1D Linear DP</div>
                            <span class="tier-badge tier-T1">Dynamic Programming</span>
                            <span class="topic-type">Fixed-Window Â· Kadane Â· Knapsack Â· LIS Â· State Machine Â· CHT</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="topic-meta">45 problems Â· 5 stages Â· fixed-window, knapsack, LIS family, state machines, CHT/deque/D&amp;C optimisations</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="topic-body">
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Why It Matters:</strong> 1D Linear DP is the foundational engine of all dynamic programming â€” it solves problems where the answer at position i depends only on answers at earlier positions in a single sequence. The core invariant is: dp[i] represents the optimal answer for the subproblem ending at or considering only the first i elements, and this value is computed exactly once from previously computed values. It appears in virtually every interview and competition because it is both the gateway to all harder DP (2D, tree, bitmask) and a source of non-trivial hard problems in its own right. The critical skill tested is not implementation â€” the recurrence is often one line â€” but <em>state definition</em>: choosing what dp[i] means precisely enough that the recurrence is correct and the transitions are O(1) or O(log n). At the ICPC/IOI level, the gap between a naÃ¯ve O(nÂ²) 1D DP and its O(n log n) optimised form separates correct solutions from AC solutions.</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">The Mental Model</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>1D Linear DP is a conveyor belt.</strong> Each item i arrives and you ask one question: "What is the best outcome I can achieve that ends with or includes item i?" You answer using only items already processed. You stamp the answer on item i and it joins the belt, available for all future items.<br><br>
                        <strong>How the mental model scales through the 5 stages:</strong><br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 1:</strong> The stamp (dp[i]) depends on a fixed, small number of previous stamps â€” dp[i-1], dp[i-2]. Constant-time recurrence.<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 2:</strong> One constraint changes what "best" means â€” no two adjacent, at most k uses, circular boundary, count instead of optimise. The formula shifts by one condition.<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 3:</strong> The stamp now has two dimensions â€” you track TWO aspects of the state simultaneously. dp[i][state] where state encodes an additional binary, small-integer, or hash-map-keyed condition.<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 4:</strong> The conveyor belt is not the raw input. You must transform the input (sort, re-index, convert problem) before the belt runs. The stamping logic is identical to a known pattern â€” recognition of the transformation IS the hard part.<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 5:</strong> Computing the stamp requires the best of all previous stamps satisfying some range condition â€” naÃ¯vely O(n) per step. A data structure (binary search, deque, segment tree, CHT) collapses this to O(log n) per step.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Core Invariant &amp; Proof Sketch</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Invariant:</strong> dp[i] holds the optimal value of the subproblem defined on the prefix arr[0..i], with arr[i] as the "anchor" (last/included element).<br><br>
                        <strong>Proof sketch (by strong induction):</strong><br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Base case:</strong> dp[0] is correct by direct computation â€” no previous elements.<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Inductive hypothesis:</strong> Assume dp[j] correct for all j &lt; i.<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Inductive step:</strong> dp[i] = f(dp[jâ‚], dp[jâ‚‚], ..., arr[i]) where all jâ‚– &lt; i. Each dp[jâ‚–] is correct by hypothesis â†’ dp[i] is correct.<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Optimal substructure check:</strong> The recurrence is valid ONLY if "the optimal solution for arr[0..i] that uses arr[i] as its last element consists of arr[i] itself, plus the optimal solution for some arr[0..j]." Verify this explicitly for every new problem.<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Answer extraction:</strong> Either dp[n-1], max(dp[0..n-1]), or some aggregation â€” depends on problem definition.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Sub-Variants to Master (29 total)</div>
                    <div class="info-box" style="line-height:1.75">
                        <strong>1. Fixed-window recurrence (Fibonacci / Climbing Stairs)</strong> â€” Stage 1 Â· O(n) Â· two variables<br>
                        <strong>2. Linear scan with reset (Kadane / max subarray)</strong> â€” Stage 1 Â· O(n) Â· single variable with reset<br>
                        <strong>3. Count of valid subarrays ending at i (Arithmetic Slices)</strong> â€” Stage 2 Â· O(n) Â· additive reset recurrence<br>
                        <strong>4. Skip-one constraint (House Robber)</strong> â€” Stage 2 Â· O(n) Â· two variables<br>
                        <strong>5. Circular skip-one constraint</strong> â€” Stage 2 Â· O(n) Â· run linear DP twice<br>
                        <strong>6. Counting variant (number of ways)</strong> â€” Stage 2 Â· O(n) Â· additive recurrence<br>
                        <strong>7. Catalan number DP (product of two sub-DPs)</strong> â€” Stage 3 Â· O(nÂ²) Â· product recurrence<br>
                        <strong>8. Boolean partition DP (Word Break)</strong> â€” Stage 2 Â· O(nÂ²) Â· boolean DP with inner loop<br>
                        <strong>9. Unbounded knapsack (Coin Change min/count)</strong> â€” Stage 2 Â· O(nÂ·target) Â· forward iteration<br>
                        <strong>10. 0/1 Knapsack (boolean/value)</strong> â€” Stage 2 Â· O(nÂ·target) Â· reverse iteration<br>
                        <strong>11. Tiling DP with partial boundary state (Domino/Tromino)</strong> â€” Stage 3 Â· O(n) Â· profile state<br>
                        <strong>12. Two-state Kadane (one deletion allowed)</strong> â€” Stage 3 Â· O(n) Â· two parallel Kadane states<br>
                        <strong>13. 3-state machine DP (Paint House)</strong> â€” Stage 3 Â· O(n) Â· 3 variables per row<br>
                        <strong>14. k-state machine, optimised (Paint House II)</strong> â€” Stage 5 Â· O(nk) Â· min1/min2 trick<br>
                        <strong>15. Multi-constraint state machine (Student Attendance II)</strong> â€” Stage 3 Â· O(n) Â· 6 states<br>
