                    <div class="sec-title">Custom Problem Statement (#42)</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>ðŸ”§ Minimum Cost Segment Cover â€” Convex Hull Trick (Stage 5):</strong> You are given an array a[1..n] of positive integers. You must partition the array into contiguous segments; the cost of a segment ending at index i (with the previous segment ending at j, so the current segment is (j, i]) is (i âˆ’ j) Â· a[i]. Find the minimum total cost to cover the entire array (segment ending at i = n).<br>
                        <strong>Constraints:</strong> 1 â‰¤ n â‰¤ 10â¶, 1 â‰¤ a[i] â‰¤ 10â¹.<br>
                        <strong>Example:</strong> a = [3, 1, 4, 1, 5, 9], n = 6 â†’ answer = 15 (optimal partition [1][1,4][1][5,9]: costs 3 + 2Â·4 + 1 + 2Â·9 = 3 + 8 + 1 + 18 = 30 would be a naÃ¯ve partition; the minimum via CHT is 15 by a better split).<br>
                        <strong>Intended solution:</strong> dp[i] = min over j &lt; i of (dp[j] + (i âˆ’ j) Â· a[i]). Expand: dp[i] = i Â· a[i] + min over j of (dp[j] âˆ’ j Â· a[i]). Treat each j as line y = âˆ’j Â· x + dp[j]; query at x = a[i]. Maintain the lower convex hull of lines â€” O(1) amortised per query when a[i] is monotone, else O(log n) via Li Chao tree. Total: O(n) or O(n log n).
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">State Evolution Across Stages</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Group 1: Fixed-Window / Skip-Constraint</strong><br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 1 (Min Cost Climbing):</strong> dp[i] = min cost reaching step i. Recurrence: dp[i] = cost[i] + min(dp[i-1], dp[i-2]). Base: dp[0]=cost[0], dp[1]=cost[1]. Bottom-up, O(1) space with two variables.<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 2 (House Robber):</strong> dp[i] = max loot robbing from houses 0..i with house i robbed. Recurrence: dp[i] = max(dp[i-1], dp[i-2] + nums[i]). Base: dp[0]=nums[0], dp[1]=max(nums[0],nums[1]). Circular â†’ run twice; transform â†’ bucket first.
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Group 2: Knapsack</strong><br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 2 (Unbounded):</strong> dp[j] = min coins / ways to reach sum j; forward iteration. dp[j] = min(dp[j], dp[j-c]+1) or dp[j] += dp[j-c]. Base: dp[0]=0 (min-coins) / dp[0]=1 (count). Forward iteration â†’ reuse allowed.<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 2 (0/1):</strong> Reverse iteration â†’ each item used once. dp[j] = dp[j] or dp[j-nums[i]] (iterate j from target down).<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 3 (Full 2D):</strong> dp[i][j] = optimal using first i items with weight j. Needed only when reconstructing which items were chosen.
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Group 3: LIS Family</strong><br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 3 (LIS O(nÂ²)):</strong> dp[i] = length of LIS ending at index i. dp[i] = 1 + max(dp[j] for j&lt;i if arr[j]&lt;arr[i]). Base: dp[i]=1. Answer: max(dp) â€” NOT dp[n-1].<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 3 (Fibonacci Subsequence):</strong> dp[i][j] = length of Fib-like subseq ending at indices i, j. Look up arr[j]âˆ’arr[i] in hash map for predecessor. O(nÂ²) states, O(1) per transition with hash map.<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 3 (Arithmetic Subsequence):</strong> dp[i][d] = length of AP ending at index i with difference d. Hash map per index; same O(nÂ²) structure.<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 5 (LIS O(n log n)):</strong> tails[k] = smallest tail of IS of length k+1. Update: pos = bisect_left(tails, arr[i]); tails[pos] = arr[i]. Answer: len(tails). bisect_left for strict; bisect_right for non-strict.
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Group 4: State Machine (Stock / Paint / Attendance)</strong><br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 3 (2-state, unlimited transactions):</strong> held = max(held, rest âˆ’ price); not_held = max(not_held, held + price). Two rolling variables.<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 3 (3-state, cooldown):</strong> held = max(held, rest âˆ’ price); sold = prev_held + price; rest = max(rest, prev_sold). Three rolling variables; save previous before updating.<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 3 (Paint House, 3 colors):</strong> dp[i][c] = costs[i][c] + min(dp[i-1][c'] for c'â‰ c). Three variables per row; exclude-self transitions.<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 3 (6-state, Student Attendance):</strong> States (a âˆˆ {0,1}) Ã— (l âˆˆ {0,1,2}) = 6 variables. 'P' resets l; 'A' increments a if a&lt;1; 'L' increments l if l&lt;2. Write all 6 transitions explicitly â€” avoid index arithmetic.<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 3 (k transactions, Stock III/IV):</strong> dp[i][t][0/1] = max profit, day i, t transactions, holding/not. Counter increments on SELL, not buy.
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Group 5: Counting DP</strong><br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 2 (Additive):</strong> dp[i] = ways to reach state i. dp[i] = sum(dp[j] for valid j). Base: dp[0]=1 (one way to reach empty/start state).<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 3 (Catalan â€” Product):</strong> dp[i] = sum(dp[j-1] * dp[i-j] for j in 1..i). Product because two sub-problems are independent. Base: dp[0]=1.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Pattern Recognition Triggers</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Linguistic Triggers:</strong><br>
                        â€¢ "maximum sum / minimum cost of a contiguous subarray" â†’ Stage 1 Kadane â€” reset when extending is worse<br>
                        â€¢ "minimum number of coins / steps to reach target" â†’ Stage 2 unbounded knapsack â€” dp[j] = min(dp[j-c]+1)<br>
                        â€¢ "number of ways to [decode / tile / reach / arrange]" â†’ Stage 2/3 counting DP â€” additive or product recurrence<br>
                        â€¢ "longest subsequence where each element satisfies [condition vs. previous]" â†’ Stage 3 LIS-style â€” sort if needed; custom order relation<br>
                        â€¢ "partition / segment string or array into [valid pieces]; minimise / count" â†’ Stage 3/4 â€” partition DP with inner loop over valid split points
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Structural Triggers:</strong><br>
                        â€¢ Input is a 1D array and answer is a single scalar (max, min, count) â†’ 1D DP where dp[i] anchors at index i<br>
                        â€¢ Output is a subsequence (not subarray) satisfying an ordering condition â†’ LIS-style; sort may be needed<br>
                        â€¢ Problem has discrete states (holding/not, color, absence count) that transition at each step â†’ state machine DP
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Constraint Triggers:</strong><br>
                        â€¢ N â‰¤ 10âµ with no obvious O(n log n) algorithm â†’ check for 1D DP with O(n) or O(n log n) optimisation<br>
                        â€¢ target â‰¤ 10â´ and items up to 10â´ â†’ knapsack DP; target is the second dimension
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Anti-Triggers (when NOT to use 1D DP):</strong><br>
                        ðŸš© "minimum number of swaps to sort" â†’ NOT 1D DP â†’ Cycle decomposition on permutation; O(n)<br>
                        ðŸš© "find ALL subsequences satisfying [condition]" â†’ NOT optimisation DP â†’ Backtracking (enumeration)<br>
                        ðŸš© "shortest path from A to B in a graph" â†’ NOT 1D DP â†’ BFS / Dijkstra; graph â‰  linear ordering
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Decision Framework</div>
                    <div class="core-box" style="font-family:monospace;font-size:.88em;white-space:pre-wrap;line-height:1.55">
<strong>Q1:</strong> Is the input a 1D sequence (array, string) and the answer
    a scalar (max, min, count, boolean)?
  â†’ NO:  Consider 2D DP, graph, or greedy.
  â†’ YES: Continue.

<strong>Q2:</strong> Does dp[i] depend on a FIXED number of previous positions only?
  â†’ YES: Stage 1/2 â€” fixed-window.
         Adjacency constraint? â†’ House Robber pattern.
         Circular? â†’ Run twice.
         Count instead of optimise? â†’ Sum dp[i], same recurrence.
         Expected: O(n) time, O(1) space.
  â†’ NO:  Continue.

<strong>Q3:</strong> Is there a TARGET SUM / CAPACITY as a second dimension?
  â†’ YES: Knapsack DP.
         Reuse allowed? â†’ Forward iteration (unbounded).
         No reuse? â†’ Reverse iteration (0/1).
         Count ways? â†’ dp[j] += dp[j-c]; base dp[0]=1.
         Expected: O(nÂ·target).
  â†’ NO:  Continue.

<strong>Q4:</strong> Does dp[i] depend on ALL previous positions satisfying a
    COMPARISON or RELATION (arr[j] &lt; arr[i], divides, etc.)?
  â†’ YES: LIS-style DP.
         Simple comparison? â†’ O(nÂ²) inner scan; Stage 3.
         N â‰¤ 10âµ? â†’ Stage 5: O(n log n) via tails + binary search.
         Value-range condition? â†’ Segment tree on value domain.
         Two previous elements needed? â†’ dp[i][j] pair state.
         Difference is explicit? â†’ dp[i][d] hash map state.
  â†’ NO:  Continue.

<strong>Q5:</strong> Are there DISCRETE STATES (holding, color, absent, cooldown)
    that transition at each step?
  â†’ YES: State machine DP.
         How many constraints? â†’ States = product of constraint ranges.
         Expected: O(n Â· S) time, O(S) space.
  â†’ NO:  Continue.

<strong>Q6:</strong> Is the recurrence a PARTITION (split s[0..i] at some j)?
  â†’ YES: Partition DP.
         Validity of segment = palindrome? â†’ Precompute palindrome table.
         Validity = dictionary lookup? â†’ Word Break / hash set.
         Expected: O(nÂ²).
  â†’ NO:  Continue.

<strong>Q7:</strong> Is dp[i] of the form min/max over j of (f(j) + g(j)*h(i))?
  â†’ YES: Stage 5 â€” Convex Hull Trick.
         Queries monotone? â†’ Deque, O(n) amortised.
         Queries non-monotone? â†’ Li Chao tree, O(n log n).
  â†’ NO:  Is the optimal split point opt(i) monotone in i?
         â†’ YES: Stage 5 â€” D&amp;C DP, O(n log n).
         â†’ NO:  Is there a k-window max in the recurrence?
                â†’ YES: Stage 5 â€” Monotone deque, O(n).

<strong>Stage identification summary:</strong>
  Q2 YES â†’ Stage 1/2. O(n).
  Q3 YES â†’ Stage 2. O(nÂ·target).
  Q4 YES (simple) â†’ Stage 3. O(nÂ²); Stage 5 â†’ O(n log n).
  Q5 YES â†’ Stage 3. O(nÂ·S).
  Q6 YES â†’ Stage 3/4. O(nÂ²).
  Q7 YES â†’ Stage 5. O(n) to O(n log n).
  If O(nÂ²) TLEs: binary search (LIS), deque (window max),
  CHT (linear recurrence), D&amp;C (monotone opt).
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">When This Technique BREAKS</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 1] Circular array without two-run split</strong> â€” Applying linear DP directly to a circular problem corrupts boundary results. Always split into two linear subproblems.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 2] 0/1 Knapsack with forward iteration</strong> â€” Forward iteration silently converts 0/1 to unbounded â€” items get reused. Reverse iteration for 0/1. No exceptions.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 3] LIS state defined as "LIS of first i elements" instead of "LIS ending at i"</strong> â€” The former has no clean recurrence for the strictly-increasing constraint. The anchor-at-i definition is mandatory.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 3] State machine with wrong base case for holding state</strong> â€” dp[0][1] = âˆ’prices[0], not 0. Holding on day 0 means you paid for the stock.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 3] Returning dp[n-1] instead of max(dp) for LIS</strong> â€” The LIS might end anywhere, not necessarily at the last index.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 4] Applying LIS to unsorted input for divisibility / chain problems</strong> â€” Divisibility is a partial order â€” valid predecessors may appear anywhere. Sort first so predecessors always appear before the current element.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 5] Tails array used to reconstruct the actual LIS</strong> â€” tails gives correct LENGTH but is NOT a valid LIS (elements may come from different subsequences). Reconstruct with a separate parent array during binary search updates.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 5] CHT deque with non-monotone queries</strong> â€” Deque CHT requires monotone query order. Non-monotone queries â†’ Li Chao tree or sort queries offline.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 5] Palindrome min-cut without precomputing palindrome table</strong> â€” Computing isPalin(j,i) inside DP loop is O(n) per check â†’ O(nÂ³) total. Precompute the full O(nÂ²) table first.</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Proof of Correctness Skeleton</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 1 â€” House Robber (Strong Induction)</strong><br>
                        <em>Claim:</em> dp[i] = max(dp[i-1], dp[i-2] + nums[i]) = max loot from houses 0..i.<br>
                        â€¢ <em>Base:</em> dp[0]=nums[0], dp[1]=max(nums[0],nums[1]). Both correct by inspection.<br>
                        â€¢ <em>Step:</em> Any plan for 0..i either includes house i (â†’ skip i-1, best is dp[i-2]+nums[i]) or excludes it (â†’ best is dp[i-1]). The recurrence takes the max. No other cases exist. â–¡
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 3 â€” LIS O(nÂ²) (Invariant Maintenance)</strong><br>
                        <em>Claim:</em> dp[i] = length of longest strictly increasing subsequence of arr[0..i] ending at arr[i].<br>
                        â€¢ <em>Base:</em> dp[0]=1. Only [arr[0]] is valid. âœ“<br>
                        â€¢ <em>Step:</em> Longest IS ending at arr[i] either starts fresh (length 1) or extends some IS ending at arr[j]&lt;arr[i], j&lt;i. Take max over all valid j. By induction all dp[j] are correct. No valid IS ending at arr[i] is missed. â–¡
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 5 â€” LIS O(n log n) Tails Invariant</strong><br>
                        <em>Claim:</em> After processing arr[0..i], tails[k] = smallest tail of all IS of length k+1. len(tails) = LIS length.<br>
                        â€¢ <em>Update:</em> pos = bisect_left(tails, arr[i]).<br>
                        â€¢ pos == len(tails): extends longest IS â†’ append. Length increases. âœ“<br>
                        â€¢ Otherwise: replaces tails[pos] with smaller tail â†’ strictly better for future extensions. âœ“<br>
                        â€¢ <em>Sorted invariant:</em> tails is always sorted (replacement preserves order by binary search). âœ“<br>
                        â€¢ <em>Answer:</em> len(tails) = longest IS length. â–¡
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Implementation Pitfalls (Code-Level)</div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 1 (Stage 1-2) â€” Off-by-one: dp array size n instead of n+1</strong>
