                    <div class="sec-title">Red Flags / Common Mistakes</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 1] Defining dp[i] as "optimal for first i elements" instead of "optimal ending at element i"</strong> â€” The "ending at i" definition anchors the state, making the recurrence tractable. The "first i elements" definition silently adds a hidden dimension (what was the last chosen element?). <em>Correct model:</em> "dp[i] = best answer for the prefix WITH arr[i] as the last chosen element; final answer = max/min over all i."</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 2] Forgetting that the knapsack base case identity depends on the objective</strong> â€” For min-coins: dp[0]=0, dp[j]=âˆž. For count-ways: dp[0]=1, dp[j]=0. For boolean: dp[0]=True. Swapping these produces subtly wrong answers that pass small tests. <em>Correct model:</em> "dp is the identity element of the recurrence operation: 0 for min, 1 for product/count, True for OR."</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 3] LIS: returning dp[n-1] instead of max(dp)</strong> â€” The LIS might end at any index, not the last. House Robber's answer is dp[n-1] because you must consider all houses. LIS terminates the subsequence at the best possible position. <em>Correct model:</em> "For 'ending-at-i' formulations, aggregate over ALL positions."</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 3] State machine DP: transaction counter incremented on both buy and sell</strong> â€” One buy + one sell = one transaction. Increment counter exactly once per complete cycle. <em>Correct model:</em> "Pick one side (buy OR sell) to increment; be consistent."</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 4] Applying LIS to unsorted input for divisibility/chain problems</strong> â€” Valid predecessors may appear anywhere in an unsorted array. Sort first so that valid predecessors always precede the current element in array order. <em>Correct model:</em> "LIS-style DP requires valid predecessors to always appear earlier in the array. If the problem's order relation doesn't match array order, sort first."</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 5] Tails array mistaken for the actual LIS</strong> â€” tails gives the correct length, but the array itself is not a valid subsequence. To recover the actual sequence, maintain a separate parent/predecessor array indexed by the position where each element was placed in tails. <em>Correct model:</em> "Tails is a bookkeeping structure for length computation, not a valid output."</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 5] CHT deque with non-monotone queries producing silent wrong answers</strong> â€” Deque CHT gives O(1) amortised only when queries are monotone. Non-monotone queries cause the pointer to move backward, violating the deque invariant and reading wrong hull segments. <em>Correct model:</em> "Verify query monotonicity before using deque CHT. If in doubt, use Li Chao tree."</div>

