                    <div class="sec-title">Custom Problem Statement (#27)</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>ðŸ”§ Maximum Cherries with Exactly K Robots â€” Multi-Agent Generalisation (Stage 4):</strong> You are given an nÃ—m grid where each cell contains a non-negative integer of cherries. K robots start at different columns of row 0 (you choose which columns). All robots move simultaneously, one row per step, and each robot moves to an adjacent column (left, same, or right) at each step. A cherry at cell (i,j) is collected only ONCE regardless of how many robots visit it. Find the maximum cherries collectible when all K robots reach the last row.<br>
                        <strong>Constraints:</strong> 1 â‰¤ n â‰¤ 50, 1 â‰¤ m â‰¤ 50, 1 â‰¤ K â‰¤ min(m, 5), 0 â‰¤ grid[i][j] â‰¤ 100.<br>
                        <strong>Example:</strong> n=3, m=3, K=2, grid=[[3,1,1],[2,5,1],[1,5,5]] â†’ Answer: 24.<br>
                        <strong>Intended solution:</strong> Bottom-up DP with state dp[row][câ‚][câ‚‚]...[câ‚–]; cherry deduplication when any two columns are equal. For K=2 this is Cherry Pickup II. For K&gt;2, state space is O(nÂ·má´·). Maintain câ‚ â‰¤ câ‚‚ â‰¤ ... â‰¤ câ‚– (column order doesn't matter) to cut state space by K! Divide-and-conquer on the agent axis (process pairs of agents, merge their optimal column assignments) reduces to O(nÂ·mÂ²Â·K).
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">State Evolution Across Stages</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Group 1: Single-Agent Path DP</strong><br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 1 â€” Min Path Sum:</strong> dp[i][j] = minimum cost to reach (i,j) from (0,0). dp[i][j] = grid[i][j] + min(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1]). Base: dp[0][0]=grid[0][0]; first row/col are prefix sums. Bottom-up row-major; O(m) space with rolling row.<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 2 â€” Dungeon Game (Reverse):</strong> dp[i][j] = minimum HP needed AT cell (i,j) to reach exit alive. dp[i][j] = max(1, min(dp[i+1][j], dp[i][j+1]) âˆ’ dungeon[i][j]). Base: dp[n-1][m-1] = max(1, 1 âˆ’ dungeon[n-1][m-1]). Bottom-up from bottom-right â€” forward DP cannot express lower-bound constraint.<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 3 â€” Out of Boundary Paths (3D):</strong> dp[i][j][k] = number of ways to leave grid from (i,j) in exactly k steps. dp[i][j][k] = sum over 4 directions of dp[ni][nj][k-1] (out-of-bounds counts as 1). Fill layer by layer; O(m) space per step.
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Group 2: Geometric Constraint DP</strong><br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 1 â€” Unique Paths:</strong> dp[i][j] = number of distinct paths from (0,0) to (i,j) moving right/down. dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j] + dp[i][j-1]. Base: dp[0][j]=1, dp[i][0]=1. Equivalent to Pascal's triangle.<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 2 â€” Maximal Square:</strong> dp[i][j] = side length of largest square of 1s with bottom-right at (i,j). dp[i][j] = min(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1], dp[i-1][j-1]) + 1 if grid[i][j]=='1' else 0. Answer = max(dp)Â².<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 4 â€” Maximal Rectangle:</strong> For each row i, compute heights[j] = number of consecutive 1s in column j ending at row i. Then largest rectangle in histogram (monotone stack) â†’ O(m) per row. Total: O(nm), O(m) space. The 2D â†’ 1D reduction IS the Stage 4 transformation.
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Group 3: Multi-Agent DP</strong><br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 3 â€” Cherry Pickup II:</strong> dp[row][c1][c2] = max cherries with two robots ending at columns c1, c2 in first row+1 rows. Transitions over (dc1, dc2) âˆˆ {-1, 0, 1}Â²; cherries(row, c1, c2) = grid[row][c1] + (grid[row][c2] if c2â‰ c1 else 0). By symmetry c1 â‰¤ c2 cuts state space in half.<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 4 â€” Cherry Pickup I (step reduction):</strong> Both agents travel (0,0)â†’(n-1,n-1). On step t, r1+c1 = r2+c2 = t â†’ r = t âˆ’ c. State reduces from dp[r1][c1][r2][c2] to dp[t][c1][c2]. Transitions over (dc1, dc2) âˆˆ {0, 1}Â². Base: dp[0][0][0] = grid[0][0]. Answer: max(dp[2(n-1)][n-1][n-1], 0).
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Group 4: Falling Path DP (Optimised)</strong><br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 2 â€” Minimum Falling Path Sum II:</strong> dp[i][j] = min falling path sum ending at (i,j) with no consecutive same-column. NaÃ¯ve: dp[i][j] = matrix[i][j] + min(dp[i-1][j'] for j'â‰ j) â€” O(nÂ³).<br>
                        â€¢ <strong>Stage 5 optimisation:</strong> Track min1 (global row min), min2 (second row min), min1_col: dp[i][j] = matrix[i][j] + (min1 if jâ‰ min1_col else min2). O(nÂ²) time, O(n) space.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Pattern Recognition Triggers</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Linguistic Triggers:</strong><br>
                        â€¢ "minimum/maximum cost path from top-left to bottom-right" â†’ Stage 1/2 grid DP â€” dp[i][j] = grid[i][j] + min/max(up, left)<br>
                        â€¢ "number of distinct paths / ways to reach" â†’ Stage 1 counting DP â€” dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j] + dp[i][j-1]<br>
                        â€¢ "maximum square / rectangle of 1s" â†’ Stage 2 geometric DP â€” dp[i][j] = side length or histogram height<br>
                        â€¢ "two robots / players move simultaneously through the same grid" â†’ Stage 3/4 multi-agent â€” joint state (c1, c2) per row; deduplication when positions coincide<br>
                        â€¢ "minimum health / resource required to survive the path" â†’ Stage 2 reverse DP â€” traverse from exit to start; state = lower bound to survive
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Structural Triggers:</strong><br>
                        â€¢ Input is nÃ—m grid, movement only right/down â†’ row-major bottom-up; O(m) rolling space<br>
                        â€¢ nÃ—m grid + 4-directional movement + monotone condition (strictly inc/dec) â†’ DFS + memoisation (data-dependent topological order)<br>
                        â€¢ Two (r1,c1) AND (r2,c2) both move through the same grid â†’ check if step = r+c is conserved; if so, reduce 4D to 3D
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Constraint Triggers:</strong><br>
                        â€¢ 1 â‰¤ n, m â‰¤ 200 with O(nm) or O(nmÂ²) budget â†’ standard grid DP, optional rolling space<br>
                        â€¢ 1 â‰¤ n, m â‰¤ 50 with third dimension k â‰¤ 50 â†’ 3D DP acceptable; O(nmÂ·k) â‰¤ 125,000
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Anti-Triggers (when NOT to use 2D Grid DP):</strong><br>
                        ðŸš© "distance to nearest 0/obstacle for each cell" â†’ NOT grid DP â†’ multi-source BFS; DP two-pass works but BFS is simpler and more general<br>
                        ðŸš© "minimum path with 8-directional movement or can revisit" â†’ NOT standard grid DP â†’ BFS (unweighted) or Dijkstra (weighted); DP breaks when topological order doesn't exist<br>
                        ðŸš© "largest connected region of 1s" â†’ NOT geometric grid DP â†’ DFS/BFS flood fill; irregular shape can't be expressed as square/rectangle invariant
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Decision Framework</div>
                    <div class="core-box" style="font-family:monospace;font-size:.88em;white-space:pre-wrap;line-height:1.55">
<strong>Q1:</strong> Is the input a 2D grid (matrix) or triangle/jagged array,
    and is the answer a scalar (count, min, max)?
  â†’ NO:  Not 2D grid DP. Consider 1D DP, graph, or greedy.
  â†’ YES: Continue.

<strong>Q2:</strong> What is the movement rule?
  â†’ RIGHT/DOWN only (or DOWN only, fixed direction):
       Row-major bottom-up DP. O(nm) time, O(m) space.
       Go to Q3.
  â†’ 4-directional with a MONOTONE condition (strict inc/dec):
       DFS + memoisation (topological order data-dependent).
       Stage 4. O(nm).
  â†’ 4-directional with NO monotone condition (arbitrary):
       â†’ Unweighted: BFS. â†’ Weighted: Dijkstra. NOT grid DP.

<strong>Q3:</strong> Is the answer a path VALUE (sum, product, min, max along path)?
  â†’ YES: Value-accumulation DP.
         Negative values? â†’ Track both max_dp and min_dp (dual-tracking).
         Lower-bound constraint (survive)? â†’ Reverse DP from exit.
         Go to Q4.
  â†’ NO (counting paths): Counting DP. dp[i][j] = sum of valid predecessors.
         Go to Q4.

<strong>Q4:</strong> Are there additional constraints beyond position?
  â†’ Step budget / remaining moves:
       Step counter as third dim. O(nmÂ·steps).
  â†’ Running sum mod k:
       Sum mod k as third dim. O(nmÂ·k).
  â†’ Cut count / partition:
       Cut counter as third dim + 2D prefix sum. O(nmÂ·k) to O(nÂ²mÂ²k).
  â†’ NO: Stage 1/2. Expected O(nm).

<strong>Q5:</strong> Are there TWO or MORE AGENTS moving simultaneously?
  â†’ YES: Multi-agent DP.
         Same grid, both go corner-to-corner?
           â†’ Check if step = i+j is conserved â†’ reduce 4D to 3D. Stage 4.
         Different starts/ends?
           â†’ Explicit 3D state (row, c1, c2). Stage 3. O(nÂ·mÂ²).
  â†’ NO: Continue.

<strong>Q6:</strong> Is the per-cell transition an inner SCAN over a row/column?
  â†’ YES: Stage 5 â€” look for optimisation.
         Non-same-column exclusion? â†’ min1/min2 trick. O(1) per cell.
         Range max/min query? â†’ Sparse table or segment tree.
         Max subarray sum â‰¤ K? â†’ Sorted set + binary search.
  â†’ NO: Solution is complete at current stage.

<strong>Stage identification summary:</strong>
  Q3 YES, Q4 NO â†’ Stage 1/2. O(nm).
  Q4 YES (extra dimension) â†’ Stage 3. O(nmÂ·k).
  Q5 YES (multi-agent) â†’ Stage 3 (explicit) or Stage 4 (reduction).
  Q6 YES (inner scan) â†’ Stage 5. O(nm) to O(nm log n).
  If O(nmÂ²) or worse and n,m &gt; 200: look for Stage 5 optimisation.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">When This Technique BREAKS</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 1] Movement allows going UP or LEFT</strong> â€” If movement is not strictly in the direction of increasing (i, j), there is no topological order for a simple row-major scan. The recurrence would form cycles. Use BFS (unweighted) or Dijkstra (weighted) instead.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 2] Reverse DP forgotten for lower-bound problems (Dungeon Game)</strong> â€” Forward DP accumulates the path value achieved â€” it cannot express "minimum resource needed to survive." Problems asking for a lower bound on a resource (HP, fuel) always require reverse traversal from the destination.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 2] Blocked cells in first row/column not stopping propagation</strong> â€” For Unique Paths II, once a blocked cell appears in row 0 or column 0, all cells AFTER it must also be 0. Forgetting to stop propagation gives wrong answers for the first row/column.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 3] Two-agent DP: double-counting cherries when c1==c2</strong> â€” When both agents are at the same column, counting grid[row][c1] + grid[row][c2] gives twice the cherries. Always check: cherries = grid[row][c1] + (grid[row][c2] if c2 != c1 else 0).</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 4] Cherry Pickup I: not enforcing valid cell bounds in 3D state</strong> â€” Since r = step âˆ’ c, when step âˆ’ c &lt; 0 or step âˆ’ c â‰¥ n, the cell is out of bounds. Failing to check 0 â‰¤ r &lt; n for both agents gives wrong transitions.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 4] Applying row-major DP to Longest Increasing Path</strong> â€” The DAG direction is data-dependent (increasing values). Row-major scan processes cells in the wrong order â€” a cell might be computed before all its predecessors. Use DFS + memoisation which discovers the correct topological order implicitly.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 5] min1/min2 trick: forgetting to track the COLUMN of min1</strong> â€” When the current column equals min1_col, you must use min2. If you only track the VALUE of min1 (not its column), you can't determine when to fall back to min2.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 5] Maximal Rectangle: applying histogram stack to the wrong axis</strong> â€” The histogram DP must run on columns (heights of consecutive 1s in each column per row). Running it on rows gives wrong heights. Recompute heights row by row.</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Proof of Correctness Skeleton</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 1 â€” Minimum Path Sum (Induction on i+j)</strong><br>
                        <em>Claim:</em> dp[i][j] = minimum sum path from (0,0) to (i,j).<br>
                        â€¢ <em>Base:</em> dp[0][0] = grid[0][0]. Trivially the only path to itself. âœ“<br>
                        â€¢ <em>Inductive step:</em> Assume dp[i'][j'] correct for all i'+j' &lt; i+j. Any path to (i,j) passes through exactly one of (i-1,j) or (i,j-1) as its last step. Minimum-sum path to (i,j) = grid[i][j] + minimum of the two optimal predecessors. Both predecessors have i'+j' &lt; i+j, so they are correct by hypothesis.<br>
                        â€¢ <em>No other cases:</em> Movement is strictly right/down; no other predecessors exist. â–¡
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 2 â€” Maximal Square (Invariant on dp[i][j])</strong><br>
                        <em>Claim:</em> dp[i][j] = side length of largest all-1s square with bottom-right at (i,j).<br>
                        â€¢ <em>Invariant:</em> A square of side s with bottom-right at (i,j) requires all three sub-squares of side s-1 ending at (i-1,j), (i,j-1), (i-1,j-1). The side is limited by the minimum of all three.<br>
                        â€¢ <em>Forward:</em> If dp[i][j] = k, a kÃ—k all-1s square exists (constructible from the three sub-squares). âœ“<br>
                        â€¢ <em>Reverse:</em> If a kÃ—k all-1s square ends at (i,j), all three neighbours have dp â‰¥ k-1. âœ“<br>
                        â€¢ <em>Combined:</em> dp[i][j] = min(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1], dp[i-1][j-1]) + 1 when grid[i][j]='1'. â–¡
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 4 â€” Cherry Pickup I (Step-Reduction Correctness)</strong><br>
                        <em>Claim:</em> The 4D state dp[r1][c1][r2][c2] (where r1+c1 = r2+c2 = t) reduces correctly to 3D dp[t][c1][c2].<br>
                        â€¢ <em>Reduction validity:</em> On step t, any valid forward path has r+c=t for each agent. Given c1 and c2, r1 and r2 are uniquely determined as r1 = t-c1, r2 = t-c2. No information lost.<br>
                        â€¢ <em>Transition validity:</em> Moving right increments c; moving down keeps r+c=t+1. Transitions (dc1, dc2) âˆˆ {0,1}Â² correctly enumerate all valid joint moves.<br>
                        â€¢ <em>Deduplication:</em> Cherry at (r,c) is collected by both agents only if r1=r2 AND c1=c2, i.e., c1=c2. Correct: add grid[r1][c1] + (grid[r2][c2] if c1â‰ c2 else 0). â–¡
                    </div>

