                    <div class="sec-title">Red Flags / Common Mistakes</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 1] Using the same base case formula for all grid DPs</strong> â€” The base case is NOT always "first row and first column = 1." For min-path-sum it's the prefix sum of costs. For Dungeon Game it's a reverse computation from the exit. For triangle it's the bottom row values. <em>Correct model:</em> "The base case encodes the problem's boundary condition: what is the answer when there are no choices left?"</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 2] Applying forward DP to problems with a survival/resource lower bound</strong> â€” Forward DP accumulates "how much I've collected" â€” it cannot express "minimum I need to start with." Dungeon Game requires the state to be a lower bound, which only makes sense computed backwards. <em>Wrong model:</em> "dp[i][j] = max HP arriving at (i,j)." <em>Correct model:</em> "dp[i][j] = min HP needed at (i,j) to survive to exit."</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 3] Multi-agent DP: processing agents sequentially instead of simultaneously</strong> â€” Computing the first agent's optimal path, then the second agent's "greedy best given what's left" is provably suboptimal. Agents must be modelled with a JOINT state because their collections interact. <em>Wrong model:</em> "Run two separate DPs." <em>Correct model:</em> "State = (row, c1, c2); both agents advance one row per step; deduplication at c1==c2."</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 4] Applying row-major DP to Longest Increasing Path</strong> â€” Row-major DP processes cells in row 0, then row 1. For LIP, cell (0,3) might depend on (1,3) if matrix[1][3] &lt; matrix[0][3]. The DAG direction is data-dependent. <em>Wrong model:</em> "Use bottom-up DP like other grid problems." <em>Correct model:</em> "When topological order is data-dependent, use DFS + memoisation; DFS naturally follows edges in the correct order."</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 3] Number of Paths with Max Score: overwriting count on score tie</strong> â€” When dp[i][j].score == candidate_score, the correct action is to ADD the incoming count to the existing count, not overwrite it. <em>Correct model:</em> "When updating a (score, count) pair: new_score &gt; old â†’ replace; equal â†’ add counts; less â†’ ignore."</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 5] Maximal Rectangle: not resetting heights on 0-cell</strong> â€” If grid[i][j]='0', the height must reset to 0 â€” the consecutive-1s streak is broken. <em>Correct model:</em> heights[j] = heights[j] + 1 if grid[i][j]=='1' else 0.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">ðŸš© <strong>[Stage 2/5] Space optimisation breaking the recurrence (rolling row overwriting needed values)</strong> â€” Rolling a 2D DP into O(m) space requires that dp[i][j] only needs the PREVIOUS row and already-computed current row values. <em>Correct model:</em> "Before optimising space, list which previous cells the recurrence reads; ensure none are overwritten before they are read."</div>

