                    <div class="sec-title">ðŸ”§ Custom Problem 29 â€” Closest Achievable Subset Sum</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Problem:</strong> Given an array <code>nums</code> of N positive integers and an integer <code>target</code>, find the subset of <code>nums</code> whose sum is closest to <code>target</code> (â‰¤ target preferred; if no subset â‰¤ target, return the smallest sum &gt; target). Return the closest achievable sum.<br><br>
                        <strong>Constraints:</strong> 1 â‰¤ N â‰¤ 1000, 1 â‰¤ nums[i] â‰¤ 1000, 1 â‰¤ target â‰¤ 10â¶<br><br>
                        <strong>Example:</strong> nums=[3,7,5,11,2], target=14 â†’ subsets with sum â‰¤ 14: &#123;12,13,14,10,...&#125;; answer = 14 (&#123;3,11&#125; or &#123;7,5,2&#125;)<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 5 solution:</strong> Solve with bitset-optimised 0/1 knapsack. dp is a Python int used as a bitset (bit j = 1 means sum j is achievable). For each num, update: <code>dp |= (dp &lt;&lt; num)</code>. After all items, scan from target downward for the highest set bit â‰¤ target. If none exists, scan upward from target for first set bit &gt; target. In Python: dp = int with bit manipulation; in C++: bitset&lt;MAXW&gt; with shift. The 64Ã— speedup over a bool array is the Stage 5 insight. The "closest to target" directional scan is the Stage 4 reduction applied afterward.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">State Evolution Across Stages</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Group 1: Core 0/1 Knapsack</strong><br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 1 â€” Subset Sum (Boolean):</strong><br>
                        dp[j] = True if sum j is achievable using some subset of items processed so far<br>
                        Recurrence: dp[j] = dp[j] or dp[j - w[i]] (iterate j from W down to w[i])<br>
                        Base cases: dp[0] = True; dp[j] = False for j &gt; 0<br>
                        Preferred: Bottom-up 1D reverse â€” O(W) space; forward would allow reuse<br>
                        Optimisation (Stage 5): Replace bool array with Python int as bitset; dp |= dp &lt;&lt; w[i]; 64Ã— speedup<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 2 â€” Count Ways:</strong><br>
                        dp[j] = number of subsets summing to exactly j<br>
                        Recurrence: dp[j] += dp[j - w[i]] (reverse iterate)<br>
                        Base cases: dp[0] = 1; dp[j] = 0 for j &gt; 0<br>
                        Preferred: Bottom-up 1D reverse; apply % MOD at every step<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 2 â€” Max Value:</strong><br>
                        dp[j] = maximum value achievable with capacity exactly j<br>
                        Recurrence: dp[j] = max(dp[j], dp[j - w[i]] + v[i]) (reverse iterate)<br>
                        Base cases: dp[0] = 0; dp[j] = -âˆž for j &gt; 0 (or 0 if "at most j")<br>
                        Preferred: Bottom-up 1D reverse; initialise to -âˆž for "exactly j", to 0 for "at most j"<br><br>
                        <strong>Group 2: Unbounded Knapsack</strong><br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 2 â€” Min Cost (Coin Change):</strong><br>
                        dp[j] = minimum number of items to reach sum exactly j<br>
                        Recurrence: dp[j] = min(dp[j], dp[j - w[i]] + 1) (forward iterate: j from w[i] to W)<br>
                        Base cases: dp[0] = 0; dp[j] = âˆž for j &gt; 0<br>
                        Preferred: Bottom-up 1D forward â€” forward allows reuse; if dp[W] = âˆž â†’ impossible<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 2 â€” Count Ways Unordered (Coin Change II):</strong><br>
                        dp[j] = number of ways to make sum j using any number of each coin<br>
                        Recurrence: dp[j] += dp[j - c[i]] (items outer, capacity inner, forward)<br>
                        Base cases: dp[0] = 1; dp[j] = 0 for j &gt; 0<br>
                        Key: items-outer â†’ each coin denomination considered in order â†’ no duplicate (same-value, different-order) sequences<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 2 â€” Count Ways Ordered (Combination Sum IV):</strong><br>
                        Same recurrence but loops swapped: capacity outer, items inner, forward<br>
                        <code>for j in 1..W: for c in coins: dp[j] += dp[j-c] if j&gt;=c</code><br>
                        Counts ordered sequences (permutations); [1,2] and [2,1] counted separately<br><br>
                        <strong>Group 3: 2D and Multi-Dimensional Knapsack</strong><br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 â€” 2D Knapsack (Ones and Zeroes):</strong><br>
                        dp[j][k] = max items achievable using at most j zeros and k ones<br>
                        Recurrence: dp[j][k] = max(dp[j][k], dp[j-z][k-o]+1) (reverse iterate BOTH j and k)<br>
                        Base cases: dp[0][0] = 0<br>
                        Preferred: Bottom-up 2D reverse â€” both dimensions are 0/1 capacity; both must iterate high-to-low<br>
                        Space: O(Wâ‚ Ã— Wâ‚‚); for LC474: 100Ã—100 = 10,000 cells<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 â€” 3D Knapsack with Capped Dimension (Profitable Schemes):</strong><br>
                        dp[j][p] = number of crime schemes using exactly j members generating AT LEAST p profit<br>
                        Recurrence: dp[j][p] += dp[j - member[i]][max(0, p - profit[i])] (reverse j and p)<br>
                        Base cases: dp[0][0] = 1<br>
                        Key: max(0, p - profit[i]) caps the profit dimension â€” "at least p" semantics; any excess profit treated as exactly minProfit<br><br>
                        <strong>Group 4: Grouped and Bounded Knapsack</strong><br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 â€” Grouped Knapsack (Dice Rolls / Exam Score):</strong><br>
                        Items partitioned into groups; choose exactly one item from each group<br>
                        dp[j] after processing group g = max/count using one from each of groups 1..g with total weight j<br>
                        Recurrence: for each group g: for j from W down to 0: for item i in g: dp[j] = op(dp[j], dp[j-w[i]] + v[i])<br>
                        Key: The inner item loop runs INSIDE the capacity loop for each group; prevents double-counting within a group<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 â€” Bounded Knapsack (NaÃ¯ve â†’ Binary Split â†’ Deque):</strong><br>
                        NaÃ¯ve: Unroll k[i] copies of item i; run standard 0/1 knapsack â†’ O(nWK)<br>
                        Binary Split (Stage 3): Split k[i] copies into groups of 1, 2, 4, ..., remainder (binary representation); each group is a "big item" in a 0/1 knapsack â†’ O(nW log K)<br>
                        Monotone Deque (Stage 5): For each item type, the recurrence dp[j] = max over t=0..k[i] of (dp[j - t*w[i]] + t*v[i]) is a sliding window max over the remainder classes modulo w[i]; deque maintains the window â†’ O(nW) total<br><br>
                        <strong>Group 5: Disguised Knapsack</strong><br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 4 â€” Tallest Billboard:</strong><br>
                        dp[d] = max common height achievable when one rod is d more than the other<br>
                        Recurrence for each rod with length L:<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;new_dp[d] = max(dp[d]) â€” skip rod<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;new_dp[d+L] = max(new_dp[d+L], dp[d] + L) â€” add to taller side<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;new_dp[|d-L|] = max(new_dp[|d-L|], dp[d] + min(d, L)) â€” add to shorter side<br>
                        Base: dp[0] = 0; dp[d] = -âˆž for d &gt; 0; Answer: dp[0]<br>
                        Preferred: Top-down with memoisation on (rod_index, difference) â€” easier to reason; can also be bottom-up with copy of dp per rod<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 4 â€” Target Sum (Reduction):</strong><br>
                        Assign + or - to each number to hit target<br>
                        Let Sâº = sum of positive group, Sâ» = sum of negative group<br>
                        Sâº + Sâ» = total; Sâº - Sâ» = target â†’ Sâº = (total + target) / 2<br>
                        If (total + target) is odd or (total + target)/2 &lt; 0 â†’ answer = 0<br>
                        Otherwise: count subsets summing to (total + target) / 2 â€” standard 0/1 count DP
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Pattern Recognition Triggers</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Linguistic Triggers:</strong><br>
                        â€¢ "can you partition / divide / split the array into two subsets" â†’ Stage 1/4 0/1 subset sum â€” reduce to sum = total/2<br>
                        â€¢ "minimum number of [coins/tiles/items] to reach exactly [target]" â†’ Stage 2 unbounded knapsack min â€” forward iterate<br>
                        â€¢ "number of ways to make / form / achieve [sum/target]" â†’ Stage 2 count DP â€” check if order matters (combination vs permutation loop nesting)<br>
                        â€¢ "at most [budget1] zeros and [budget2] ones" â†’ Stage 3 2D knapsack â€” both capacity dimensions reverse-iterate<br>
                        â€¢ "assign +/- signs to numbers to reach target" â†’ Stage 4 Target Sum reduction â€” convert to subset sum count on (total+target)/2<br><br>
                        <strong>Structural Triggers:</strong><br>
                        â€¢ Input is a list of items each with a single numeric weight; answer is a scalar about a target sum â†’ 0/1 or unbounded knapsack depending on reuse<br>
                        â€¢ Items are partitioned into groups with exactly one selection per group â†’ Grouped knapsack; inner item loop inside capacity loop<br>
                        â€¢ n â‰¤ 40, target is very large (&gt;10â¶) â†’ Meet-in-the-middle; standard DP infeasible<br><br>
                        <strong>Constraint Triggers:</strong><br>
                        â€¢ W â‰¤ 10â´ and n â‰¤ 10Â³ â†’ standard O(nW) knapsack in time; use 1D rolling array for space<br>
                        â€¢ W â‰¤ 10â¶ and n â‰¤ 10Â³ â†’ bitset optimisation reduces constant by 64Ã—; or meet-in-the-middle if n â‰¤ 40<br><br>
                        <strong>Anti-Triggers:</strong><br>
                        â€¢ "list ALL subsets / combinations that sum to target" â†’ NOT knapsack â†’ Backtracking with pruning (knapsack counts but cannot enumerate)<br>
                        â€¢ "shortest path / minimum edits between two states" â†’ NOT knapsack â†’ BFS or edit-distance DP (items are not selected; states transition)<br>
                        â€¢ "select at most K non-overlapping intervals maximising sum" â†’ NOT pure knapsack â†’ Interval DP + binary search (overlap constraint creates ordering structure)
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Decision Framework</div>
                    <div class="core-box" style="font-family:monospace;white-space:pre-wrap">Q1: Does the problem involve SELECTING a SUBSET of items
    to optimise/count subject to a CAPACITY constraint?
  â†’ NO:  Not knapsack. Consider graph DP, interval DP, or greedy.
  â†’ YES: Continue.

Q2: Can each item be used MORE THAN ONCE?
  â†’ YES (unbounded): Forward iteration. dp[j] uses updated values.
         Minimise? â†’ dp[j] = min(dp[j], dp[j-w]+cost). Base dp[0]=0, rest âˆž.
         Count ways (ordered)? â†’ Capacity outer, items inner.
         Count ways (unordered)? â†’ Items outer, capacity inner.
         Go to Q5.
  â†’ NO (each item once, 0/1): Reverse iteration.
         Go to Q3.

Q3: How many items of each type are allowed?
  â†’ Exactly 0 or 1 (pure 0/1):
       Reverse iterate. Go to Q4.
  â†’ At most k[i] (bounded):
       Binary split into log(k[i]) 0/1 items per type.
       Or: monotone deque for O(nW) â€” Stage 5.
  â†’ Exactly one from each group:
       Grouped knapsack: group outer, capacity inner, item innermost.

Q4: What is the objective?
  â†’ Boolean (can we hit sum j?): dp[j] |= dp[j-w]. Base dp[0]=True.
  â†’ Count ways: dp[j] += dp[j-w]. Base dp[0]=1.
  â†’ Max value: dp[j] = max(dp[j], dp[j-w]+v). Base dp[0]=0 (or -âˆž for exact).
  â†’ Min cost: dp[j] = min(dp[j], dp[j-w]+c). Base dp[0]=0, rest âˆž.
  â†’ Closest to target: Fill boolean dp; scan from target for nearest set bit.

Q5: Are there TWO OR MORE independent capacity dimensions?
  â†’ YES: 2D/3D knapsack. Reverse iterate ALL capacity dimensions.
         Each extra dimension multiplies space by its size.
  â†’ NO: Continue.

Q6: Is the problem disguised? (items/capacity not explicit)
  â†’ Check: "Target Sum" â†’ compute Sâº = (total+target)/2 â†’ count subset.
  â†’ Check: "Billboard" â†’ difference = capacity â†’ dp[diff] = common height.
  â†’ Check: "Partition balanced" â†’ target = total/2 â†’ boolean subset sum.
  â†’ If still not clear: name what "item" = , "weight" = , "capacity" = .

Q7: Is the capacity W too large for standard O(nW)?
  â†’ W &gt; 10â¶ and n â‰¤ 40: Meet-in-the-middle. O(2^(n/2) log n).
  â†’ W &gt; 10âµ and n â‰¤ 1000: Bitset optimisation. O(nW/64).
  â†’ W â‰¤ 10âµ: Standard DP is fine.

Stage identification summary:
  Q2+Q4, no extra dimensions â†’ Stage 1/2. O(nW).
  Q5 YES â†’ Stage 3. O(nÂ·Wâ‚Â·Wâ‚‚).
  Q6 YES (disguised) â†’ Stage 4. O(nW) after transformation.
  Q7 YES â†’ Stage 5. O(nW/64) or O(2^(n/2) log n).
  If O(nW) TLEs: try bitset (W large) or meet-in-the-middle (n small, W huge).</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">When This Technique BREAKS</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>[Stage 1] Item reuse accidentally enabled by forward iteration in 0/1 knapsack:</strong> Forward iteration allows dp[j-w] to reflect item i already being taken once â€” silently turning 0/1 into unbounded. Reverse iteration for ALL 0/1 knapsack variants. No exceptions.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 2] Wrong loop nesting for ordered vs. unordered count:</strong> Items-outer counts unordered combinations; capacity-outer counts ordered permutations. Swapping the loops for the wrong problem produces inflated (permutations) or deflated (combinations) counts.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 2] Base case dp[0]=0 for count-ways DP:</strong> For count-ways, dp[0] must be 1 (there is exactly one way to make sum 0: the empty subset). Setting dp[0]=0 makes every downstream cell 0. For min-cost, dp[0]=0 is correct; for boolean, dp[0]=True.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 3] 2D Knapsack: iterating one dimension forward and one reverse:</strong> Both dimensions must be iterated in REVERSE for 0/1 2D knapsack. Iterating one forward turns that dimension unbounded.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 3] Profitable Schemes: not capping profit at minProfit index:</strong> If p + profit[i] &gt; minProfit, the new index must be minProfit, not p + profit[i]. Without capping, the index overflows the table and "at least minProfit" semantics break.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 4] Target Sum: not checking parity of (total + target):</strong> If (total + target) is odd, the subset size (total+target)/2 is not an integer â€” zero valid subsets. Forgetting this check produces wrong answers for odd-sum inputs.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 4] Tallest Billboard: not copying the dp array before updating:</strong> The recurrence requires dp from the previous rod step. If you update dp[d+L] before reading dp[d], you may use a value already modified by the current rod â€” equivalent to using the same rod twice. Always work on a copy per rod.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 5] Bounded knapsack: binary splitting without handling the remainder:</strong> Binary split produces groups &#123;1, 2, 4, ..., 2^k, remainder&#125;. If the remainder group is omitted, the total represented is 2^(k+1)-1, not k[i] â€” wrong item count.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 5] Bitset: using arithmetic shift instead of logical shift:</strong> In languages with signed integer shift, right-shifting the bitset may propagate sign bits. Use UNSIGNED types or language-level bitset&lt;N&gt; for correctness.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Proof of Correctness Skeleton</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Stage 1 â€” 0/1 Subset Sum: Reverse Iteration Prevents Reuse</strong><br>
                        Claim: After processing item i with weight w[i], dp[j] correctly reflects whether sum j is achievable using items &#123;1..i&#125;, with each item used at most once.<br>
                        Invariant before item i: dp[j] reflects items &#123;1..i-1&#125; correctly.<br>
                        Update (reverse order j = W down to w[i]): When computing the new dp[j], we read dp[j-w[i]]. Since j-w[i] &lt; j and we iterate from high to low, dp[j-w[i]] has NOT yet been updated in this iteration â€” it still reflects items &#123;1..i-1&#125; only.<br>
                        Therefore: dp[j] |= dp[j-w[i]] says "sum j is achievable using items &#123;1..i&#125; IF EITHER it was achievable without item i, OR it was achievable at j-w[i] without item i, plus item i once."<br>
                        Item i counted at most once: dp[j-w[i]] does not yet include item i (reverse order). âœ“ â–¡<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 2 â€” Unbounded Knapsack: Forward Iteration Enables Reuse</strong><br>
                        Claim: After processing all coins, dp[j] = minimum coins to make sum j, with each coin usable unlimited times.<br>
                        Invariant: dp[j] = min coins to make j using coins processed so far, with unlimited reuse.<br>
                        Update (forward order j = w to W): When computing dp[j], we read dp[j-w[i]]. Since j-w[i] &lt; j and we iterate forward, dp[j-w[i]] has ALREADY been updated for coin i â€” it may include coin i one or more times.<br>
                        Therefore: dp[j] = min(dp[j], dp[j-w[i]]+1) correctly captures using coin i one MORE time on top of any number of previous uses. âœ“ â–¡<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 â€” 2D Knapsack: Both Dimensions Must Reverse-Iterate</strong><br>
                        Claim: For 0/1 2D knapsack with capacities (Z, O), reversing both dimensions prevents reuse of any item.<br>
                        Suppose dimension Z is forward-iterated: When computing dp[j][k], dp[j-z][k-o] has already been updated for item i â€” item i can contribute to dp[j-z][k-o], and then again to dp[j][k]: item i counted twice. âœ—<br>
                        With both reverse: dp[j-z][k-o] for j-z &lt; j and k-o &lt; k has not yet been updated in this item's pass (both indices are smaller â†’ processed later in reverse order). Item i counted at most once. âœ“ â–¡
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Implementation Pitfalls (Code-Level)</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Bug 1 â€” 0/1 subset sum: forward iteration causes item reuse</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: forward â†’ dp[j-w] may already include nums[i]
for num in nums:
    for j in range(num, target+1):  # forward
        dp[j] = dp[j] or dp[j-num]
# FIX: reverse
    for j in range(target, num-1, -1):
        dp[j] = dp[j] or dp[j-num]</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 2 â€” Count-ways base case: dp=0 instead of 1</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: zero ways to make any sum (everything stays 0)
dp = [0] * (target + 1)
# FIX:
dp = [0] * (target + 1)
dp[0] = 1  # one way to make sum 0: empty subset</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 3 â€” Coin Change: initialising dp=infinity</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: dp[0]=âˆž â†’ dp[coin]=âˆž+1 â†’ wrong
dp = [float('inf')] * (amount + 1)
# FIX:
dp[0] = 0  # zero coins to make amount 0</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 4 â€” Target Sum: not checking (total+target) parity</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: (total+target)/2 is non-integer â†’ wrong index
target_sum = (total + target) // 2
# FIX:
if (total + target) % 2 != 0 or (total + target) &lt; 0:
    return 0
target_sum = (total + target) // 2</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 5 â€” Combination Sum IV: wrong loop order</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: items outer â†’ counts unordered combinations, not ordered permutations
for num in nums:
    for j in range(num, target+1):
        dp[j] += dp[j-num]
# FIX: capacity outer â†’ counts ordered sequences
for j in range(1, target+1):
    for num in nums:
        if j >= num:
            dp[j] += dp[j-num]</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 6 â€” 2D knapsack: only reverse-iterating one dimension</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: forward loops allow item reuse in both dimensions
for z, o in items:
    for j in range(z, max_z+1):      # BUG: forward
        for k in range(o, max_o+1):  # BUG: forward
            dp[j][k] = max(dp[j][k], dp[j-z][k-o]+1)
# FIX: both dimensions reverse
    for j in range(max_z, z-1, -1):
        for k in range(max_o, o-1, -1):
            dp[j][k] = max(dp[j][k], dp[j-z][k-o]+1)</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 7 â€” Profitable Schemes: profit index overflow without capping</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: p + profit[i] > minProfit â†’ out of bounds or wrong state
dp[j][p + profit[i]] += dp[j - member[i]][p]
# FIX: cap at minProfit
dp[j][min(p + profit[i], minProfit)] += dp[j - member[i]][p]</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 8 â€” Grouped knapsack: capacity loop inside group loop causes within-group reuse</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: item used multiple times within group
for item in group:
    for j in range(w, W+1):
        dp[j] = max(dp[j], dp[j-w]+v)
# FIX: freeze dp before processing group
new_dp = dp.copy()
for item in group:
    for j in range(w, W+1):
        new_dp[j] = max(new_dp[j], dp[j-w]+v)  # read from old dp
dp = new_dp</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 9 â€” Tallest Billboard: modifying dp in-place during rod processing</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: updating dp directly causes current rod used multiple times
for rod_len in rods:
    for d in range(max_diff+1):
        dp[d+rod_len] = max(dp[d+rod_len], dp[d] + rod_len)
# FIX: work on a copy per rod
    new_dp = dp.copy()
    for d in range(max_diff+1):
        if dp[d] >= 0:
            new_dp[d+rod_len] = max(new_dp[d+rod_len], dp[d] + rod_len)
            new_dp[abs(d-rod_len)] = max(new_dp[abs(d-rod_len)], dp[d] + min(d, rod_len))
    dp = new_dp</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 10 â€” Bitset knapsack: using signed integer shift (sign bit propagation)</strong>
                        <pre><code>// BUG in C++: signed int bitshift may propagate sign bit
int dp = 1;
dp |= (dp &lt;&lt; weight);  // undefined behaviour for signed overflow
// FIX: use unsigned or std::bitset&lt;MAXW&gt;
unsigned long long dp = 1ULL;
dp |= (dp &lt;&lt; weight);
// or in Python (arbitrary precision int â€” always correct):
dp |= dp &lt;&lt; weight</code></pre>
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Red Flags / Common Mistakes</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>[Stage 1] Forgetting to check if total sum is odd for partition problems:</strong> If the total sum is odd, it's impossible to partition into two equal halves â€” but the DP will happily run and give a wrong answer (the target (total/2) with integer division is not the correct target). Wrong model: "Just run the DP and check dp[total//2]." Correct model: "If total % 2 != 0, return False immediately. Then target = total // 2."<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 2] Confusing when to use ordered vs. unordered count:</strong> Candidates apply the wrong loop nesting because they think "count ways" always uses items-outer. But [1,2] and [2,1] are the same COMBINATION but different PERMUTATIONS. Correct model: "Items outer = each denomination used in sorted order = combinations. Capacity outer = at each capacity level, any denomination can be the last one added = permutations."<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 3] Initialising 2D DP with dp[0][0]=1 but not resetting the table between items:</strong> For 2D knapsack, the entire table should be initialised to 0 (or -âˆž for max-value) once, then items are processed. Reinitialising the table inside the item loop destroys previously computed values. Correct model: "Initialise the table ONCE before any item loop. The item loop only updates; it never re-initialises."<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 4] Applying 0/1 knapsack to problems requiring ordered selection:</strong> Knapsack is inherently unordered â€” it doesn't care about the sequence in which items are selected. If the problem has an ordering constraint (e.g., items must be selected in a particular sequence, or the reward depends on the order), knapsack gives wrong answers. Correct model: "If the value/validity of selecting item i depends on WHICH OTHER ITEMS have been selected before (not just how many), knapsack is wrong. Use sequence DP instead."<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 3] Profitable Schemes: treating "at least minProfit" as "exactly minProfit":</strong> The "at least" semantics are encoded by capping the profit index at minProfit. Without this cap, the DP computes "exactly p profit" not "at least p profit", and doesn't count schemes that exceed minProfit. Correct model: "min(p + profit[i], minProfit) is not a workaround â€” it IS the correct semantics. Any profit â‰¥ minProfit is a valid scheme."<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 4] Tallest Billboard: not handling the "add to shorter side" case in the recurrence:</strong> When adding rod L to the shorter side, the common height increases only by min(d, L) (the shorter side grows, but only until it catches up or the rod runs out). Missing the shorter-side case causes the algorithm to miss many valid configurations. Correct model: "Each rod has three options: skip it, add to the taller side (difference increases by L), add to the shorter side (difference changes to |d - L|). All three must be checked."<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 5] Meet-in-the-middle: not sorting the second half before binary search:</strong> The meet-in-the-middle approach enumerates all sums of the first half, then for each sum s1, binary-searches the second-half sums for the largest value â‰¤ target - s1. If the second-half list is unsorted, binary search gives wrong results. Correct model: "After enumerating all second-half sums, sort them AND remove dominated entries (keep only the Pareto-optimal suffix). Then binary search."
                    </div>

