                    <div class="sec-title">ðŸ”§ Custom Problem 29 â€” Longest Common Subsequence of K Strings</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Problem:</strong> Given K strings sâ‚, sâ‚‚, ..., sâ‚– each of length at most N, find the length of their longest common subsequence (a subsequence appearing in all K strings).<br><br>
                        <strong>Constraints:</strong> 2 â‰¤ K â‰¤ 5, 1 â‰¤ N â‰¤ 100<br><br>
                        <strong>Example:</strong> K=3, s1="abcde", s2="ace", s3="aec" â†’ LCS = "ac" = 2<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3/4 solution:</strong> Generalise the 2D LCS: state is dp[i1][i2]...[ik] = length of LCS of s1[0..i1-1], s2[0..i2-1], ..., sk[0..ik-1]. Recurrence: if all characters s1[i1-1] == s2[i2-1] == ... == sk[ik-1], then dp[...] = dp[i1-1,...,ik-1] + 1. Otherwise, take max over k options of decrementing one index. Time: O(Ná´·). For K=5, N=100: 10Â¹â° â€” infeasible. For Kâ‰¤3, Nâ‰¤100: 10â¶ â€” feasible. The problem teaches: (1) natural generalisation of 2D to kD DP; (2) exponential blowup and when to stop generalising; (3) the "all-match diagonal" branch scales to k dimensions cleanly.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">State Evolution Across Stages</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Group 1: Two-String Prefix DP</strong><br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 1 â€” LCS:</strong><br>
                        dp[i][j] = length of LCS of s1[0..i-1] and s2[0..j-1]<br>
                        If s1[i-1] == s2[j-1]: dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1] + 1; else: dp[i][j] = max(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1])<br>
                        Base: dp[0][j] = dp[i][0] = 0<br>
                        Preferred: Bottom-up row by row â€” O(min(n,m)) space with single rolling row<br>
                        Optimisation (Stage 5): LCS â†’ LIS reduction for special character sets; O(n log n)<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 2 â€” Edit Distance:</strong><br>
                        dp[i][j] = min edits to convert s1[0..i-1] to s2[0..j-1]<br>
                        If match: dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1]; else: dp[i][j] = 1 + min(dp[i-1][j-1], dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1])<br>
                        Base: dp[0][j] = j; dp[i][0] = i<br>
                        Preferred: Bottom-up â€” two rows sufficient (rolling)<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 2 â€” Longest Common Substring:</strong><br>
                        dp[i][j] = length of common substring ending at s1[i-1] and s2[j-1]<br>
                        dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1] + 1 if s1[i-1]==s2[j-1] else 0; answer = max(dp[i][j])<br>
                        Preferred: Bottom-up; O(min(n,m)) rolling space; track global max<br><br>
                        <strong>Group 2: Single-String Interval DP</strong><br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 2 â€” Longest Palindromic Subsequence:</strong><br>
                        dp[i][j] = length of LPS in s[i..j]<br>
                        If s[i] == s[j]: dp[i][j] = dp[i+1][j-1] + 2; else: dp[i][j] = max(dp[i+1][j], dp[i][j-1])<br>
                        Base: dp[i][i] = 1; dp[i][i-1] = 0<br>
                        Key traversal: <code>for l in range(1, n+1): for i in range(n-l+1): j = i+l-1</code><br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 â€” Palindrome Boolean Table:</strong><br>
                        dp[i][j] = True if s[i..j] is a palindrome<br>
                        dp[i][j] = (s[i]==s[j]) and dp[i+1][j-1]; base: dp[i][i]=True; dp[i][i+1] = (s[i]==s[i+1])<br>
                        Preferred: Bottom-up by increasing length (same traversal as LPS)<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 â€” Min Palindrome Cuts:</strong><br>
                        Phase 1: Build isPalin[i][j] as above<br>
                        Phase 2: cuts[i] = min cuts for s[0..i]; cuts[i] = min(cuts[j-1]+1 for j in 0..i if isPalin[j][i]); cuts[j-1] uses -1 for j==0<br><br>
                        <strong>Group 3: Three-State / Complex Pattern Matching</strong><br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 â€” Regular Expression:</strong><br>
                        dp[i][j] = True if s[0..i-1] matches p[0..j-1]<br>
                        p[j-1]=='*': dp[i][j] = dp[i][j-2] (zero of prev) OR (dp[i-1][j] and (s[i-1]==p[j-2] or p[j-2]=='.'))<br>
                        p[j-1]=='.': dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1]<br>
                        else: dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1] and s[i-1]==p[j-1]<br>
                        Base: dp[0][0]=True; dp[0][j] = dp[0][j-2] if p[j-1]=='*' (handle a*b*c* matching empty)<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 â€” Affine Gap Alignment (3-state machine):</strong><br>
                        Three states per cell: M[i][j] (match/mismatch), X[i][j] (gap in s2), Y[i][j] (gap in s1)<br>
                        M[i][j] = max(M[i-1][j-1], X[i-1][j-1], Y[i-1][j-1]) + score(s1[i-1],s2[j-1])<br>
                        X[i][j] = max(M[i-1][j] - gap_open, X[i-1][j] - gap_extend)<br>
                        Y[i][j] = max(M[i][j-1] - gap_open, Y[i][j-1] - gap_extend)<br>
                        Preferred: Bottom-up â€” each cell computes three values; O(nm) time
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Pattern Recognition Triggers</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Linguistic Triggers:</strong><br>
                        â€¢ "longest common subsequence / substring between two strings" â†’ Stage 1 LCS / Stage 2 substring â€” immediate 2D DP; check contiguous (reset) vs non-contiguous (max)<br>
                        â€¢ "minimum edits / insertions / deletions to transform / match" â†’ Stage 2 Edit Distance â€” three-operation recurrence; base = i or j (delete full prefix)<br>
                        â€¢ "number of distinct ways to form / embed string t in string s" â†’ Stage 3 Distinct Subsequences â€” additive match branch; dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1] + dp[i-1][j] on match<br>
                        â€¢ "is s a valid interleaving of s1 and s2" â†’ Stage 3 Interleaving â€” boolean DP; two source strings contribute to one target<br>
                        â€¢ "minimum cuts to partition string into palindromes" â†’ Stage 3 Palindrome Cuts â€” two-phase: precompute palindrome table; then cut DP<br><br>
                        <strong>Structural Triggers:</strong><br>
                        â€¢ Two strings given as input; answer is a scalar (length, count, cost) â†’ Row-major 2D DP; O(nm) time; check direction (forward accumulation vs. reverse for LPS)<br>
                        â€¢ Single string; answer involves SUBSTRINGS s[i..j] (not prefixes) â†’ Interval DP; fill by increasing length j-i<br>
                        â€¢ Pattern has * or . wildcard characters â†’ Regex or Wildcard matching; * is the distinguishing branch<br><br>
                        <strong>Constraint Triggers:</strong><br>
                        â€¢ n, m â‰¤ 1000 â†’ O(nm) DP is 10â¶ operations; feasible; standard 2D string DP<br>
                        â€¢ n â‰¤ 500 and answer is on single string intervals â†’ O(nÂ²) interval DP; also feasible<br><br>
                        <strong>Anti-Triggers:</strong><br>
                        â€¢ "find if pattern exists as substring (not subsequence)" â†’ NOT DP â†’ Use KMP or Z-function; substring matching has linear algorithms<br>
                        â€¢ "find all occurrences of a set of words in a stream" â†’ NOT subsequence DP â†’ Use Aho-Corasick automaton; multiple pattern matching â‰  subsequence DP<br>
                        â€¢ "longest duplicate substring for n â‰¥ 10â´" â†’ NOT LCS(s,s) because O(nÂ²) TLEs â†’ Use binary search + Rabin-Karp rolling hash for O(n log n)
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Decision Framework</div>
                    <div class="core-box" style="font-family:monospace;white-space:pre-wrap">Q1: Does the problem involve one or two strings and ask for
    a scalar about character relationships (length, count, cost)?
  â†’ NO:  Not string DP. Consider graph, greedy, or hashing.
  â†’ YES: Continue.

Q2: Are there TWO strings (or does the problem compare a string
    with another string / its reverse / a pattern)?
  â†’ YES: Two-string prefix DP. dp[i][j] on prefix pair.
         Go to Q3.
  â†’ NO (single string, intervals): Interval DP.
         Fill by increasing length. Go to Q6.

Q3: What is the relationship on MATCH (s1[i-1] == s2[j-1])?
  â†’ Extend (dp = dp[i-1][j-1]+1): LCS / common substring.
       Contiguous? â†’ Reset on mismatch (dp[i][j]=0 on mismatch).
       Non-contiguous? â†’ max(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1]) on mismatch.
  â†’ No cost (dp = dp[i-1][j-1]): Edit Distance on match.
       Three-operation mismatch: dp[i][j] = 1 + min(diag, up, left).
  â†’ Count (dp += dp[i-1][j-1] + dp[i-1][j]): Distinct Subsequences.
  â†’ Boolean (True): Regex / Wildcard / Interleaving.
         Has '*'? â†’ Regex (with prev char) or Wildcard (standalone).
         Two source strings â†’ one target? â†’ Interleaving.

Q4: Is there an additional constraint (k mismatches, k deletions)?
  â†’ YES: Add k as third dimension. O(nmk). Stage 3.
  â†’ NO: Continue.

Q5: Is the problem disguised?
  â†’ Sequence of arrays/integers matching a pattern?
       â†’ Treat array elements as characters. Same 2D DP.
  â†’ Column-frequency from word list?
       â†’ Preprocess to frequency table; then subsequence count DP.
  â†’ YES to any: Stage 4. O(nm) after transformation.

Q6 (Interval DP path): What does dp[i][j] represent?
  â†’ Is s[i..j] a palindrome? â†’ Boolean interval DP. Base dp[i][i]=True.
  â†’ Length of LPS in s[i..j]? â†’ LPS interval DP. Base dp[i][i]=1.
  â†’ Min cuts in s[i..j]? â†’ Cut DP after palindrome precomputation.
  â†’ Can s1[i..l] scramble to s2[j..l]? â†’ 3D interval DP. Stage 4.

Q7: Is the solution too slow?
  â†’ O(nm) with n,m &gt; 10â´: LCS â†’ LIS reduction â†’ O(n log n).
  â†’ O(nÂ²) with n &gt; 10â´: Binary search + rolling hash for substring problems.
  â†’ Suffix array + LCP array for LRS / distinct substrings.

Stage identification:
  Q3 (simple match/mismatch) â†’ Stage 1/2. O(nm).
  Q4 (extra dimension) â†’ Stage 3. O(nmk).
  Q5 (disguised) â†’ Stage 4. O(nm) after transform.
  Q7 (TLE) â†’ Stage 5. O(n log n).</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">When This Technique BREAKS</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>[Stage 1] Using LCS recurrence for contiguous substring:</strong> The LCS max(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1]) propagates length forward even through mismatches. For contiguous substrings, this is wrong â€” reset to 0 on mismatch. Applying LCS to "longest common substring" gives inflated lengths.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 2] Edit distance with wrong base cases:</strong> dp[i][0] must equal i (delete all i characters from s1 to reach empty). Setting dp[i][0]=0 makes the first column wrong, corrupting the entire table. Similarly dp[0][j]=j.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 3] Distinct subsequences: missing the skip branch on match:</strong> On s[i-1]==t[j-1], the correct recurrence is dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1] + dp[i-1][j]. The + dp[i-1][j] term counts the cases where s[i-1] is NOT used to match t[j-1]. Missing this gives wrong counts by ignoring valid matchings.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 3] Regex matching: wrong base case for patterns like a*b*c* matching empty string:</strong> dp[0][j] must handle patterns that can match empty: if p[j-1]=='*', then dp[0][j] = dp[0][j-2]. Without this, a* can't match an empty string â€” breaking all downstream cells.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 3] Interval DP wrong traversal order:</strong> Filling dp[i][j] row by row (increasing i, then j) processes dp[i+1][j-1] before dp[i][j] only if i+1 &gt; i â€” which means the diagonal is computed AFTER, not before. Must fill by INCREASING LENGTH l = j-i+1, otherwise inner intervals aren't ready.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 4] Applying 2D prefix DP to interval DP problems:</strong> For problems about substrings s[i..j] (not prefixes), the state is not "first i characters vs first j characters" but "characters from i to j." The recurrence and traversal order are fundamentally different. Mixing them gives wrong answers.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 5] LCS for large n using O(nÂ²) DP (TLE):</strong> When n &gt; 10â´, the standard O(nm) DP TLEs. For strings over small alphabets, reduce to LIS: find the positions of each character of s1 in s2 (reverse-sorted), concatenate, run LIS â†’ O(n log n). Not recognising this reduction leads to TLE.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Proof of Correctness Skeleton</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Stage 1 â€” LCS (Optimal Substructure by Cases)</strong><br>
                        Claim: dp[i][j] = length of LCS of s1[0..i-1] and s2[0..j-1].<br>
                        Case 1 (s1[i-1] == s2[j-1]): The LCS must end with this character (exchange argument: any LCS of the prefixes that doesn't end with this character can be extended by appending it, contradicting maximality). So dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1] + 1. âœ“<br>
                        Case 2 (mismatch): The LCS cannot use both s1[i-1] and s2[j-1] (they differ). It either uses s1[i-1] (meaning s2[j-1] is excluded â†’ dp[i][j-1]), or uses s2[j-1] (meaning s1[i-1] excluded â†’ dp[i-1][j]), or neither (bounded by both). The max of the first two covers all cases. âœ“<br>
                        Induction: Both cases use values at strictly smaller (i+j), which are correct by induction. â–¡<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 2 â€” Edit Distance (Correctness of Three Operations)</strong><br>
                        Claim: dp[i][j] = minimum edits to transform s1[0..i-1] into s2[0..j-1].<br>
                        Base cases: dp[0][j] = j (insert j characters); dp[i][0] = i (delete i characters). Both correct.<br>
                        Inductive step: To transform s1[0..i-1] to s2[0..j-1], the last operation is one of:<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;Match/replace s1[i-1] â†’ s2[j-1]: cost = dp[i-1][j-1] + (0 if match else 1)<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;Delete s1[i-1] (not in s2 prefix): cost = dp[i-1][j] + 1<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;Insert s2[j-1] (after processing s1[0..i-1]): cost = dp[i][j-1] + 1<br>
                        These three cases are exhaustive (every sequence of edits has a last operation that falls into one of these categories). Taking the minimum gives the optimal. â–¡<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 â€” Interval DP Palindrome (Correctness of Length-Based Filling)</strong><br>
                        Claim: If we fill dp[i][j] for all intervals with j-i = l before processing j-i = l+1, then dp[i][j] is correctly computed when needed by larger intervals.<br>
                        Invariant: When computing dp[i][j] (interval of length l+1), the recurrence uses dp[i+1][j-1] (length l-1) and dp[i+1][j], dp[i][j-1] (length l). All three have length â‰¤ l, so they were computed in earlier iterations. âœ“<br>
                        Row-major order fails: If we fill row i before row i+1, dp[i][j] needs dp[i+1][j-1] which is in row i+1 â€” not yet computed. This demonstrates why length-based filling is mandatory for interval DP. â–¡
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Implementation Pitfalls (Code-Level)</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Bug 1 â€” LCS: using 0-indexed strings with 1-indexed DP without offset</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: dp[i][j] reads s1[i] instead of s1[i-1]
if s1[i] == s2[j]:
    dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1] + 1
# FIX: DP is 1-indexed; strings are 0-indexed
if s1[i-1] == s2[j-1]:
    dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1] + 1</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 2 â€” Edit distance: wrong base case dp[0][0]=1</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: dp[0][0]=1 â†’ transforming empty to empty costs 1
dp[0][0] = 1  # BUG
# FIX:
dp[0][0] = 0  # empty to empty = 0 edits</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 3 â€” Edit distance: not initialising first row and column</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: base cases for first row and column not set
dp = [[0]*(m+1) for _ in range(n+1)]
# FIX: fill entire first row and column
for i in range(n+1): dp[i][0] = i
for j in range(m+1): dp[0][j] = j</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 4 â€” Longest common substring: propagating length through mismatch</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: max(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1]) gives LCS not substring
if s1[i-1] != s2[j-1]:
    dp[i][j] = max(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1])  # BUG
# FIX: reset to 0 on mismatch for contiguous
    dp[i][j] = 0</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 5 â€” Distinct subsequences: forgetting skip branch on match</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: only counts matchings that USE s[i-1]
if s[i-1] == t[j-1]:
    dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1]  # BUG: missing + dp[i-1][j]
# FIX:
    dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1] + dp[i-1][j]</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 6 â€” Regex matching: missing dp[0][j] for patterns with *</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: dp[0][j]=False for all j â†’ "a*" can't match ""
dp = [[False]*(len(p)+1) for _ in range(len(s)+1)]
dp[0][0] = True
# FIX: handle patterns that match empty string
for j in range(2, len(p)+1):
    if p[j-1] == '*':
        dp[0][j] = dp[0][j-2]  # "x*" matches empty</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 7 â€” Interval DP: filling by row instead of by length</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: dp[i+1][j-1] not computed yet in row-major order
for i in range(n):
    for j in range(i, n):    # BUG: row-major
        if s[i]==s[j]: dp[i][j] = dp[i+1][j-1] and True
# FIX: fill by increasing length
for l in range(2, n+1):
    for i in range(n-l+1):
        j = i + l - 1
        dp[i][j] = (s[i]==s[j]) and dp[i+1][j-1]</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 8 â€” Palindrome cuts: off-by-one in cuts array</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: cuts[j-1] when j=0 â†’ cuts[-1] (Python wraps to last element)
for i in range(n):
    for j in range(i+1):
        if isPalin[j][i]:
            cuts[i] = min(cuts[i], cuts[j-1] + 1)  # BUG when j=0
# FIX:
            cuts[i] = min(cuts[i], 0 if j == 0 else cuts[j-1] + 1)</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 9 â€” LPS via LCS(s, reverse): passing same string twice</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: LCS of s with itself gives len(s), not LPS
lps = LCS(s, s)   # BUG: trivial self-match
# FIX:
lps = LCS(s, s[::-1])  # reverse s; LCS with reversed gives LPS</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 10 â€” Rolling row LCS: overwriting values in current row</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: dp[j-1] in current row already updated; prev diagonal lost
for i in range(m):
    for j in range(n):
        if s1[i] == s2[j]:
            dp[j] = prev_dp[j-1] + 1
        else:
            dp[j] = max(prev_dp[j], dp[j-1])
# FIX: copy prev_dp BEFORE the inner loop
