                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Red Flags / Common Mistakes</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>[Stage 1] Treating LCS and Longest Common Substring as the same problem:</strong> LCS is non-contiguous (characters can be scattered). Longest Common Substring is contiguous (characters must be adjacent). The recurrence differs in one critical place: LCS takes max(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1]) on mismatch; substring resets to 0. Wrong model: "Both find 'common' characters." Correct model: "Subsequence = characters in order but not necessarily adjacent; substring = characters in order AND adjacent."<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 2] Edit distance: counting match as cost 1 instead of 0:</strong> The diagonal transition on match is dp[i-1][j-1] (no cost added), not dp[i-1][j-1]+1. This mistake makes the algorithm count the total number of character pairs, not the minimum edits. Correct model: "Match costs 0 (no edit needed). Only the three mismatch operations cost 1 each."<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 3] Interval DP filled in row-major order:</strong> For interval DP, dp[i][j] depends on dp[i+1][j-1] â€” which is in the NEXT row. Row-major order computes row i before row i+1, so dp[i+1][j-1] isn't ready. This gives wrong answers for all intervals of length â‰¥ 3. Correct model: "Interval DP must be filled in increasing ORDER OF INTERVAL LENGTH, not row by row."<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 3] Regex matching: treating * as standalone (like wildcard) instead of bound to previous character:</strong> In regex, * means "zero or more of the PRECEDING character." The pattern index jumps by 2 (j-2) to consume both x and *. Treating * as standalone makes it match any single character â€” wrong. Correct model: "a* in regex is a unit; it matches '', 'a', 'aa', etc. The * consumes both itself and its predecessor from the pattern."<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 3] Distinct subsequences: confusing dp[i][j] semantics:</strong> The outer loop should iterate over s (i from 1 to m) and inner over t (j from 1 to n). Swapping them gives wrong state semantics where j advances over s and i over t, inverting the "embedding" direction. Correct model: "dp[i][j] = number of ways to form t[0..j-1] using characters from s[0..i-1]. s is the longer string; t is the pattern being embedded."<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 4] Using two-pointer for distinct subsequences count:</strong> Two-pointer correctly determines IF t is a subsequence of s (O(n) time). But it cannot COUNT the distinct ways â€” it greedily takes the first available match. Counting requires the full 2D DP. Correct model: "Two-pointer for boolean IS-subsequence. 2D DP for COUNT of distinct subsequence occurrences."<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 5] Not applying LCSâ†’LIS reduction when n is large:</strong> For strings with small alphabets (binary, DNA), LCS can be reduced to LIS using position lists, giving O(n log n). Applying the O(nm) DP for n=m=10âµ gives 10Â¹â° operations â€” always TLE. Correct model: "If n,m &gt; 5Ã—10Â³ for LCS, immediately ask: is a reduction to LIS or suffix array possible?"
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Interviewer Follow-Up Questions</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 2 Follow-Ups:</strong></div>
