                    <div class="sec-title">ðŸ”§ Custom Problem 7 â€” At Most K Transactions with Cooldown</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Problem:</strong> Given an array prices of length n and integers k and cooldown, find the maximum profit from at most k buy-sell transactions where after each sell, you must wait exactly cooldown days before buying again.<br><br>
                        <strong>Constraints:</strong> 1 â‰¤ n â‰¤ 1000, 1 â‰¤ k â‰¤ 100, 1 â‰¤ cooldown â‰¤ 3<br><br>
                        <strong>Example:</strong> prices=[1,3,1,5], k=2, cooldown=1 â†’ buy day 0 (cost 1), sell day 1 (profit +2), wait day 2, buy day 3 (cost 1), sellâ€¦ â†’ answer = 6<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 solution:</strong> State is dp[t][state] where t âˆˆ &#123;0..k&#125;, state âˆˆ &#123;HOLD, REST_0, REST_1, ..., REST_&#123;cooldown-1&#125;&#125;. When you sell, you enter REST_0, which transitions to REST_1, ..., REST_&#123;cooldown-1&#125;, which finally enables buy again. The number of states is k Ã— (cooldown + 1). For k=100, cooldown=3: 400 states, each updated in O(1) â†’ O(400n) total. This problem teaches: (1) cooldown = a CHAIN of intermediate REST states; (2) k-dimension and cooldown-dimension compose independently; (3) compositional state machine design is mechanical once each sub-machine is mastered.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">State Evolution Across Stages</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Group 1: Stock DP State Machine</strong><br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 1 â€” Two variables (buy once):</strong><br>
                        hold = max profit achievable while holding a stock<br>
                        rest = max profit achievable while not holding a stock<br>
                        hold = max(hold, -prices[i]); rest = max(rest, hold + prices[i])<br>
                        Base: hold = -prices[0], rest = 0; Answer: rest<br>
                        Preferred: Bottom-up O(1) space â€” two rolling variables<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 1 â€” Two variables (unlimited transactions):</strong><br>
                        hold = max(hold, rest - prices[i]) â† can buy after any sell<br>
                        rest = max(rest, hold + prices[i])<br>
                        ONE difference from "buy once": hold now references rest (prior accumulated profit)<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 2 â€” Three variables (cooldown):</strong><br>
                        hold, rest, cool (the day after selling)<br>
                        new_hold = max(hold, cool - prices[i]) â† buy only from COOL<br>
                        new_rest = max(rest, cool) â† skip during cooldown or after resting<br>
                        new_cool = hold + prices[i] â† sell today; tomorrow enters COOL<br>
                        Base: hold = -prices[0], rest = 0, cool = -âˆž<br>
                        Key: use new_ variables â€” all new states computed from old states simultaneously<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 â€” kÃ—2 table (at most k transactions):</strong><br>
                        dp[t][0] = max profit with t sells completed, NOT holding<br>
                        dp[t][1] = max profit with t sells completed, HOLDING<br>
                        dp[t][1] = max(dp[t][1], dp[t][0] - prices[i]) â† buy (doesn't increase t yet)<br>
                        dp[t][0] = max(dp[t][0], dp[t-1][1] + prices[i]) â† sell (increases t by 1)<br>
                        Base: dp[0][0] = 0, dp[t][1] = -âˆž for tâ‰¥0, dp[t][0] = -âˆž for t&gt;0<br>
                        Optimisation: If k â‰¥ n//2, answer = unlimited transactions solution (O(n))<br><br>
                        <strong>Group 2: Sign-Tracking / Alternating State Machine</strong><br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 4 â€” Positive Product Subarray:</strong><br>
                        pos = length of longest subarray ending here with positive product<br>
                        neg = length of longest subarray ending here with negative product<br>
                        When a[i] &gt; 0: pos = pos + 1; neg = neg + 1 if neg &gt; 0 else 0<br>
                        When a[i] &lt; 0: new_pos = neg + 1 if neg &gt; 0 else 0; new_neg = pos + 1<br>
                        When a[i] == 0: pos = neg = 0 (reset both)<br>
                        Answer: max(pos) across all days<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 4 â€” Maximum Alternating Subsequence Sum:</strong><br>
                        even = max sum ending at even-indexed position; odd = max sum ending at odd-indexed position<br>
                        new_even = max(even, odd + a[i]); new_odd = max(odd, even - a[i])<br>
                        Base: even = 0, odd = 0; Answer: even<br>
                        Key: BOTH transitions always run each step; no conditional on direction<br><br>
                        <strong>Group 3: Position-Tracking State Machine</strong><br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 â€” Number of Ways to Stay in Same Place:</strong><br>
                        dp[step][pos] = number of ways to be at position pos after step steps<br>
                        dp[step+1][pos] += dp[step][pos] (stay)<br>
                        dp[step+1][pos+1] += dp[step][pos] (move right, if pos+1 &lt; arrLen)<br>
                        dp[step+1][pos-1] += dp[step][pos] (move left, if pos-1 â‰¥ 0)<br>
                        Base: dp[0][0] = 1; Answer: dp[steps][0]<br>
                        Optimisation: Position never exceeds min(arrLen-1, steps//2) â€” critical bound<br><br>
                        <strong>Group 4: Sequence-Type State Machine</strong><br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 4 â€” Number of Ways to Select Buildings:</strong><br>
                        Want to count subsequences that are "010" or "101"<br>
                        For "010": zeros = count of single 0s; ones_after_zero = (0,1) pairs; twos = (0,1,0) triples<br>
                        At each building b: if b==0: zeros+=1; twos+=ones_after_zero<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;if b==1: ones+=1; ones_after_zero+=zeros<br>
                        Run two separate DPs for "010" and "101"; sum the answers<br>
                        Preferred: Single pass with 6 counters â€” three per pattern; O(1) space
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Pattern Recognition Triggers</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Linguistic Triggers:</strong><br>
                        â€¢ "at most k transactions / operations / flips" â†’ Stage 3 k-dimension state machine â€” add k as second state dimension<br>
                        â€¢ "cooldown of d days after each [sell/action]" â†’ Stage 2 â€” add d intermediate REST states between transitions<br>
                        â€¢ "alternating [sign/type/direction]" â†’ Stage 4 â€” 2-state forced alternation machine; both transitions run every step<br>
                        â€¢ "transaction fee on each [buy/sell]" â†’ Stage 2 â€” one constant term in one transition; no new states<br>
                        â€¢ "maximum score / profit / sum by selecting elements with [parity/type] constraint" â†’ Stage 4 â€” states = type of last selected element<br><br>
                        <strong>Structural Triggers:</strong><br>
                        â€¢ Input is a 1D sequence; output is a scalar (max profit/score/sum); answer depends on "mode" (holding/not, bought/not, type of last action) â†’ State machine DP; K states; O(nK)<br>
                        â€¢ Problem has explicit "cooldown" or "wait N periods" between actions â†’ State chain for the cooldown; K = actions + cooldown states<br>
                        â€¢ Sequence must alternate between two types (0/1, +/-) with value maximisation â†’ 2-state alternating machine; both transitions fire every step<br><br>
                        <strong>Constraint Triggers:</strong><br>
                        â€¢ k â‰¤ 100 or k â‰¤ n in stock-type problems â†’ O(nk) is feasible; add k as state dimension<br>
                        â€¢ n â‰¤ 500 and state space involves pairs â†’ O(nÂ·states) is fine; full 2D table<br><br>
                        <strong>Anti-Triggers:</strong><br>
                        â€¢ "no two adjacent elements selected" â†’ NOT state machine DP â†’ Linear DP dp[i] = max(dp[i-1], dp[i-2]+a[i]); state machine overcomplicated<br>
                        â€¢ "shortest path between two positions" â†’ NOT state machine DP â†’ BFS/Dijkstra; states don't capture "path cost" without O(n) blowup<br>
                        â€¢ "maximum product subarray" â†’ NOT stock state machine â†’ Two-variable Kadane tracking running max and min; categorically different recurrence
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Decision Framework</div>
                    <div class="core-box" style="font-family:monospace;white-space:pre-wrap">Q1: Is the problem a 1D sequence where the optimal decision at
    each element depends on a FINITE "mode" you are currently in?
  â†’ NO:  Not state machine DP. Check grid DP, interval DP, or greedy.
  â†’ YES: Continue.

Q2: Can you enumerate ALL possible modes (states)?
  â†’ YES: List them explicitly. Count = K.
         K = 2 â†’ 2-state machine. K = 3 â†’ add cooldown or sign.
         K = 2k â†’ k transaction levels.
         K = 2^n â†’ bitmask state machine (n â‰¤ 20).
  â†’ NO:  State space continuous/too large â†’ LIS, interval DP, or greedy.

Q3: Are transactions bounded (at most k)?
  â†’ YES: Add k as second dimension. dp[k][state]. O(nK).
         k â‰¥ n//2? â†’ Unlimited equivalent; drop k dimension.
  â†’ NO:  1D state machine. O(nÂ·K).

Q4: Is there a cooldown of d days between actions?
  â†’ YES: Add d intermediate states between "sell" and "buy-enabled."
         Chain: SELL â†’ COOL_1 â†’ ... â†’ COOL_d â†’ CAN_BUY. K increases by d.
  â†’ NO:  Continue.

Q5: Is the problem DISGUISED (no explicit "buy/sell/hold")?
  â†’ Check: alternating types â†’ 2-state alternation.
  â†’ Check: sign tracking â†’ POS/NEG/ZERO states.
  â†’ Check: last-selected-type constraint â†’ states = types.
  â†’ Check: counting length-k subsequences of a pattern â†’ k-state counter.
  â†’ If disguised: name states explicitly, draw transition diagram,
    THEN write the recurrence.

Q6: Is n or K too large?
  â†’ n â‰¤ 10^5, K â‰¤ 100: Standard O(nK) fine.
  â†’ n â‰¤ 10^18, K â‰¤ 20: Matrix exponentiation. O(KÂ² log n).
  â†’ K â‰¤ 20, states are bitmasks: Bitmask DP. O(2^K Â· n).

Stage identification:
  Q2 (K=2, no constraints) â†’ Stage 1. O(n).
  Q4 (cooldown) or fee â†’ Stage 2. O(n).
  Q3 (k transactions) â†’ Stage 3. O(nk).
  Q5 (disguised) â†’ Stage 4. O(nÂ·K) after identification.
  Q6 (matrix exp) â†’ Stage 5. O(KÂ² log n).</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">When This Technique BREAKS</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>[Stage 1] States are not independent:</strong> State machine DP requires that each state's value is computed independently from other states at the same step using only the previous step's values. If state A can only have a certain value IF state B has a specific value (not just "â‰¤ best B"), the simple max-over-predecessors recurrence is insufficient. Use min-cost-flow or constraint programming.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 2] Cooldown uses wrong transition source:</strong> With cooldown, hold must source from the COOLDOWN state, NOT from the generic REST state. Sourcing from REST allows buying on the day after selling â€” violating the cooldown. This is a Stage 2 bug that produces silently inflated profits.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 3] Stale-read in k-transaction DP:</strong> When iterating over k and days in a nested loop, if dp[t][1] is updated and then immediately used to update dp[t][0] in the same day's loop iteration, the sell transition uses a SAME-DAY buy â€” meaning you buy and sell on the same day using the same transaction slot. Fix: process sells AFTER all buys, or use temporary variables.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 4] Treating "last selected type" problems as position DP:</strong> When the constraint is on the TYPE of the last selected element (not its position), position-indexed DP dp[i] doesn't capture enough state. Need dp[type] = best score ending with that type. Missing the state dimension gives wrong greedy-like answers.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 5] Matrix exponentiation: wrong state vector initialisation:</strong> The initial state vector must precisely encode the base case of the state machine. Off-by-one in which step's state vector is used (step 0 vs step 1) shifts all subsequent states and gives wrong answers for large n.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Proof of Correctness Skeleton</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Stage 1 â€” Two-State Stock (Buy Once): Correctness of Rolling Variables</strong><br>
                        Claim: At each day i, hold = max(-prices[j] for j â‰¤ i) and rest = max(0, max(-prices[j] + prices[k]) for j &lt; k â‰¤ i).<br>
                        hold invariant: hold = max(hold_prev, -prices[i]). By induction, hold_prev = max(-prices[j] for j &lt; i). After update: hold = max(-prices[j] for j â‰¤ i). âœ“<br>
                        rest invariant: rest = max(rest_prev, hold_prev + prices[i]). hold_prev + prices[i] = max one-transaction profit ending at day i. Taking max with rest_prev gives the global best profit up to day i. âœ“<br>
                        Strict buy-before-sell: hold_prev reflects purchases strictly before day i, so hold_prev + prices[i] represents selling on day i after a past purchase. âœ“ â–¡<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 2 â€” Cooldown State Machine: Correctness of Three-State Separation</strong><br>
                        Claim: The three-state machine (HOLD, REST, COOL) correctly models the cooldown constraint.<br>
                        State completeness: Any configuration is exactly one of: holding stock (HOLD), not holding and can buy (REST), not holding and cannot buy yet â€” day immediately after a sell (COOL). These three are exhaustive and mutually exclusive. âœ“<br>
                        COOL â†’ REST transition: After one day in COOL, you move to REST (can buy again). The transition rest = max(rest, cool) on the NEXT day correctly delays buy eligibility by one day. âœ“<br>
                        No-stale-read guarantee: Using temporary new_hold, new_rest, new_cool ensures all three new states use the previous day's configuration â€” not a partially-updated current day. â–¡<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 â€” K-Transaction DP: Induction on Transactions</strong><br>
                        Claim: dp[t][0] = max profit using at most t complete transactions, not holding; dp[t][1] = max profit using t-1 complete sells and currently holding.<br>
                        Base: t=0: dp[0][0] = 0 (no transactions, no stock). dp[0][1] = -âˆž (holding without any context). âœ“<br>
                        Induction on t: dp[t][0] = max(dp[t][0], dp[t-1][1] + prices[i]). This correctly sources from t-1 completed transactions. âœ“<br>
                        Why dp[t-1] for the sell? Holding with t-1 completed sells means the t-th transaction is open; selling it completes the t-th transaction. â–¡
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Implementation Pitfalls (Code-Level)</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Bug 1 â€” Stale-read in cooldown: updating hold before cool is read</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: hold updated first; cool references NEW hold (wrong)
hold = max(hold, cool - prices[i])   # new hold computed
cool = hold + prices[i]              # BUG: uses new hold
# FIX: compute all new states from old values simultaneously
new_hold = max(hold, cool - prices[i])
new_cool = hold + prices[i]          # old hold
hold, cool = new_hold, new_cool</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 2 â€” Buy-once stock: using rest - prices[i] instead of -prices[i]</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: allows buying multiple times (uses accumulated rest profit)
hold = max(hold, rest - prices[i])  # BUG for buy-once
# FIX for buy ONCE:
hold = max(hold, -prices[i])        # can only spend cash, not prior profit</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 3 â€” Fee: applying fee on BOTH buy and sell</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: fee deducted twice per transaction
hold = max(hold, rest - prices[i] - fee)  # BUG: fee on buy
rest = max(rest, hold + prices[i] - fee)  # AND on sell = double fee
# FIX: apply fee once â€” on SELL only
hold = max(hold, rest - prices[i])
rest = max(rest, hold + prices[i] - fee)</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 4 â€” K-transaction: stale-read sell uses same-day buy</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: sell reads dp[k][1] that was just updated this same day
for k in range(1, K+1):
    dp[k][1] = max(dp[k][1], dp[k][0] - prices[i])   # buy
    dp[k][0] = max(dp[k][0], dp[k][1] + prices[i])   # BUG: same-day buy
# FIX: sell sources from PREVIOUS transaction's buy
    dp[k][0] = max(dp[k][0], dp[k-1][1] + prices[i])  # sell increases count
    dp[k][1] = max(dp[k][1], dp[k][0] - prices[i])    # buy at count k</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 5 â€” At most k: not handling k â‰¥ n//2 edge case</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: for k = n = 10^5, allocating dp[k][2] â†’ MLE or TLE
dp = [[0, -float('inf')] for _ in range(k+1)]  # BUG: k up to 10^5
# FIX: reduce to unlimited when k is large
if k >= len(prices) // 2:
    return solve_unlimited(prices)</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 6 â€” Alternating subsequence: updating even and odd in wrong order</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: even updated first; odd uses NEW even (wrong)
even = max(even, odd + a[i])   # new even
odd = max(odd, even - a[i])    # BUG: uses new even
# FIX: use temp variables
new_even = max(even, odd + a[i])
new_odd = max(odd, even - a[i])   # old even
even, odd = new_even, new_odd</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 7 â€” Positive product: not resetting BOTH pos and neg on zero</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: only resetting pos on zero; neg carries stale state
if a[i] == 0:
    pos = 0   # BUG: neg not reset
# FIX:
    pos, neg = 0, 0  # zero resets ALL product-length tracking</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 8 â€” Number of ways to select buildings: missing "101" pattern</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: only counts "010" patterns, missing "101"
ans = count_pattern(buildings, pattern="010")  # BUG
# FIX:
ans = count_pattern(buildings, "010") + count_pattern(buildings, "101")</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 9 â€” Matrix exponentiation: off-by-one in initial state vector</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: applying transition matrix n times instead of n-1
result = matrix_pow(transition, n) @ initial_vector  # BUG: one extra step
# FIX: initial_vector is state AFTER day 0; apply n-1 more transitions
result = matrix_pow(transition, n-1) @ initial_vector</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 10 â€” Random walk DP: not clamping position to min(arrLen, steps//2)</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: iterating pos up to arrLen â†’ huge state space for large arrLen
for pos in range(arrLen):   # BUG for arrLen=10^6
    ...
# FIX: position can never exceed steps//2 moves from start
max_pos = min(arrLen - 1, steps // 2)
for pos in range(max_pos + 1):
    ...</code></pre>
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Red Flags / Common Mistakes</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>[Stage 1] Forgetting that "buy once" and "unlimited" differ by one term in one transition:</strong> For buy-once, rest before the first buy is always 0, so rest - prices[i] = -prices[i] â€” equivalent ONLY in that sense. But adding rest's accumulated profit conceptually allows a second "free buy." Correct model: "Buy-once: hold = max(hold, -prices[i]). Unlimited: hold = max(hold, rest - prices[i]). The ONLY difference is whether prior profit is reinvested."<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 2] Cooldown: sourcing the buy transition from REST instead of COOL:</strong> If you buy from REST, you allow buying the day after selling â€” violating the cooldown. The buy must source from COOL. Correct model: "Cooldown creates a directed chain: HOLD â†’ (sell) â†’ COOL â†’ (next day) â†’ REST â†’ (buy) â†’ HOLD. The buy arrow comes from REST, but REST is only reachable from COOL."<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 3] K-transaction: updating buy and sell in same loop iteration without temporary variables:</strong> The sell transition dp[t][0] = dp[t-1][1] + prices[i] correctly uses t-1 transaction buy. But if buy dp[t][1] = dp[t][0] - prices[i] runs first and updates dp[t][0], then the sell reads a same-day value. Correct model: "Compute ALL new state values into temporary variables first. Write ALL new values simultaneously."<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 4] Missing the state in disguised problems:</strong> When a problem says "select elements with alternating types" or "build a sequence with no two consecutive same elements," candidates jump to greedy or brute-force. The state IS the type of the last selected element. Correct model: "For any problem with 'the last selected element must satisfy property P,' make P the state. Draw K states. Fill the state machine."<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 3] Not detecting the k â‰¥ n//2 threshold for unlimited equivalence:</strong> When k â‰¥ n//2, you can never exhaust k transactions (a transaction requires at least 2 days). Allocating O(nk) DP table for k=10^9 is MLE. Correct model: "Before writing the k-transaction DP, check: if k â‰¥ len(prices)//2, return the unlimited-transactions answer. This is not an optimisation â€” it's a correctness requirement for large k."<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 4] Treating alternating subsequence as a greedy problem:</strong> The alternating subsequence sum looks like it could be solved greedily. In fact, the optimal can skip profitable segments to enable future gains. Correct model: "Greedy works for LONGEST alternating (count direction changes), but for MAXIMUM SUM alternating, you must track even and odd states explicitly."<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 2] Fee applied twice:</strong> Some candidates apply fee on both the buy (rest - prices[i] - fee) and the sell (hold + prices[i] - fee). This charges double per transaction. Correct model: "One transaction = one buy + one sell = one fee. Apply fee on exactly ONE of the two transitions (convention: on sell). Never on both."
                    </div>

