            <!-- â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•
                 TOPIC 35 â€” INTERVAL DP (MASTERY)
            â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â•â• -->
            <div class="topic-card" id="tp35">
                <div class="topic-header">
                    <div class="topic-num">35</div>
                    <div style="flex:1">
                        <div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:.5rem;flex-wrap:wrap">
                            <div class="topic-title">Interval DP</div>
                            <span class="tier-badge tier-T1">Dynamic Programming</span>
                            <span class="topic-type">Palindrome Â· Merge/Chain Â· Burst Balloons Â· Polygon Â· Strange Printer Â· Remove Boxes Â· Knuth-Yao</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="topic-meta">28 problems Â· 5 stages Â· palindrome shrink, split-point merge, last-one-standing, state-expanded, two-boundary, Knuth-Yao optimisation</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="topic-body">
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Why It Matters:</strong> Interval DP solves problems where the answer for a sequence s[i..j] is built from the answers for all strict sub-intervals s[i..k] and s[k+1..j] (or s[i..k-1] and s[k..j]), with an additional cost or value contributed by the split point k or the boundary elements. The core invariant is: <strong>dp[i][j] = optimal value for the sub-problem on interval [i,j], computed after all dp[i'][j'] with j'-i' &lt; j-i</strong> â€” that is, after all strictly shorter intervals are solved. This mandatory fill-order by increasing length is what distinguishes interval DP from every other 2D DP pattern. It appears relentlessly in top-tier interviews and ICPC/IOI competitions because: (1) the state definition is always dp[i][j] on a contiguous range â€” learnable and systematic; (2) the split-point loop <code>for k in range(i, j)</code> is the universal recurrence skeleton; (3) disguised variants (balloon popping, matrix chain, stone merging, polygon triangulation) look wildly different on the surface but reduce to the same O(nÂ³) structure; and (4) the hard problems require identifying the CORRECT split-point semantics, which is the single skill that separates good candidates from great ones.</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">The Mental Model</div>
                    <div class="info-box">Interval DP is <strong>recursive demolition</strong>. You have a row of objects. To solve a problem on range [i,j], you decide LAST which object at position k is the "last one standing" (the last to be processed, removed, or merged). Everything to its left ([i,k-1]) and everything to its right ([k+1,j]) must be fully resolved first. The cost of the current decision depends on what remains at the boundaries when k is processed last.<br><br>This <strong>"last one standing" framing</strong> is the universal template. The key question for every new interval DP problem is: <em>"What object, when processed last, makes its cost easy to compute?"</em><br><br><strong>How this scales through the 5 stages:</strong><br><strong>Stage 1:</strong> dp[i][j] = cost to solve [i,j] by splitting at k; uniform cost per split; fill by length j-i ascending.<br><strong>Stage 2:</strong> Same structure, ONE constraint changes: circular boundary (wrap-around), penalty depends on boundary elements (not just split), or the answer is a COUNT not a cost.<br><strong>Stage 3:</strong> State gains a dimension: dp[i][j][k] where k tracks a count, a color/group, or a number of remaining merges. The split recurrence is identical but the third dimension gates transitions.<br><strong>Stage 4:</strong> Problem looks nothing like interval DP. The "interval" must be identified: balloons burst in an order (frame as "last to burst"), polygon diagonals (triangles = splits), matrix chain (parenthesisation = split). The reduction IS the insight.<br><strong>Stage 5:</strong> The O(nÂ³) solution TLEs. Apply the Knuth-Yao optimisation: if the split point opt[i][j] is monotone, the total work reduces from O(nÂ³) to O(nÂ²).</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Core Invariant / Proof Sketch</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Invariant:</strong> dp[i][j] is correct for all intervals of length L = j-i+1, computed before any interval of length L+1 is computed.<br><br><strong>Proof sketch (strong induction on interval length L):</strong><br><strong>Base case (L=1):</strong> dp[i][i] is trivially correct â€” a single element has no split point; its value is defined directly (zero cost, or the element itself). âœ“<br><strong>Base case (L=2):</strong> dp[i][i+1] has exactly one split point k=i; computed directly from the two length-1 sub-problems, which are already correct. âœ“<br><strong>Inductive step:</strong> Assume dp[i'][j'] is correct for all j'-i' &lt; L. For interval [i,j] with length L+1, the recurrence dp[i][j] = min/max over k in [i,j-1] of (dp[i][k] + dp[k+1][j] + cost(i,k,j)) references only sub-intervals of length â‰¤ L. By the inductive hypothesis, all of these are correct. Therefore dp[i][j] is correct. âœ“<br><strong>Fill order guarantee:</strong> Filling in increasing order of L = j-i+1 (outer loop) ensures that when computing dp[i][j], all dp[i][k] and dp[k+1][j] for k âˆˆ [i,j-1] have already been computed (they are shorter intervals). â–¡<br><br><strong>Why "last one standing" works for non-standard problems (e.g., Burst Balloons):</strong> When the cost of removing element k depends on its neighbours, we need those neighbours to still be present when k is removed. Framing k as "the LAST removed" guarantees its neighbours a[i-1] and a[j+1] are still present (they are outside the interval being solved). This converts a variable-cost dependent problem into a well-defined subproblem. â–¡</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Sub-Variants to Master</div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>Sub-Variant</th><th>Stage</th><th>Time</th><th>Space</th><th>New Idea</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>Matrix Chain Multiplication / Optimal Parenthesisation</td><td>Stage 1</td><td>O(nÂ³)</td><td>O(nÂ²)</td><td>THE baseline â€” dp[i][j] = min over k of dp[i][k] + dp[k+1][j] + cost(i,k,j); split-point k divides [i,j] into two independent sub-chains; 2D table + split-point loop</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Palindrome interval DP (is/length/count)</td><td>Stage 1</td><td>O(nÂ²)</td><td>O(nÂ²)</td><td>dp[i][j] depends on dp[i+1][j-1] (SHRINK from both ends), not a split-point; teaches the SHRINK variant of interval DP; fill by increasing length</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Optimal BST</td><td>Stage 2</td><td>O(nÂ³) â†’ O(nÂ²)</td><td>O(nÂ²)</td><td>Cost of split = sum(freq[i..j]) (all elements in interval contribute); prefix sums needed; Knuth-Yao applicable; dp[i][j] = min over k of dp[i][k-1] + dp[k+1][j] + pre[j+1]-pre[i]</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Burst Balloons</td><td>Stage 4</td><td>O(nÂ³)</td><td>O(nÂ²)</td><td>Cost of removing k DEPENDS ON ITS CURRENT NEIGHBOURS â€” must frame k as LAST removed so boundaries are predictable; add sentinel 1s; the most important non-obvious transformation in interval DP</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Minimum Score Triangulation of a Polygon</td><td>Stage 4</td><td>O(nÂ³)</td><td>O(nÂ²)</td><td>Polygon â†’ interval DP by fixing one vertex; split = third vertex of a triangle whose base is always [i,j]; dp[i][j] = min over k of dp[i][k]+dp[k][j]+V[i]*V[k]*V[j]; sub-problems SHARE endpoints</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Strange Printer</td><td>Stage 4</td><td>O(nÂ³)</td><td>O(nÂ²)</td><td>If s[i]==s[k], the turn for s[i] can extend to cover s[k] at no extra cost; dp[i][j] = min(dp[i+1][k]+dp[k+1][j]) when s[i]==s[k]; "last interval printed" insight</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Minimum Cost to Merge Stones</td><td>Stage 3</td><td>O(nÂ³)</td><td>O(nÂ²)</td><td>Not all intervals are mergeable â€” feasibility check: (j-i) % (K-1) == 0; only add final merge cost when feasible; gated split recurrence</td></tr>
