                    <div class="sec-title">ðŸ”§ Custom Problem 4 â€” Minimum Cost to Merge N Piles into 1 (K=2)</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Problem:</strong> You have n piles of stones in a row. Each move, you pick two adjacent piles and merge them, paying a cost equal to the total number of stones in the two merged piles. Find the minimum total cost to merge all n piles into one.<br><br>
                        <strong>Constraints:</strong> 2 â‰¤ n â‰¤ 300, 1 â‰¤ piles[i] â‰¤ 100<br><br>
                        <strong>Example:</strong> piles=[3,2,4,1] â†’ merge (3,2)=5 cost 5, (5,4)=9 cost 9, (9,1)=10 cost 10 â†’ total=24. Optimal: merge (3,2)=5, (4,1)=5, (5,5)=10 â†’ total=20.<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 1 solution:</strong> dp[i][j] = min cost to merge piles[i..j] into one pile. Recurrence: dp[i][j] = min over k in [i,j-1] of (dp[i][k] + dp[k+1][j] + prefix[j+1]-prefix[i]) where prefix is the prefix sum array. Base: dp[i][i] = 0. Fill by increasing length L = j-i+1 from 2 to n. Answer: dp[0][n-1].<br><br>
                        <strong>Why this exists:</strong> This is the simplest problem that establishes ALL of: (1) dp[i][j] on a range, (2) split-point loop over all k, (3) prefix sums for the merge cost, (4) fill-by-length traversal. Every subsequent interval DP problem in this guide inherits this exact template.
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">State Evolution Across Stages</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Group 1: Palindrome Interval DP (Shrink from Ends)</strong><br>
                        <strong>Stage 1 â€” LPS / Min Insertions:</strong><br>
                        dp[i][j] = LPS length in s[i..j] (or min insertions)<br>
                        Recurrence: If s[i] == s[j]: dp[i][j] = dp[i+1][j-1] + 2; Else: dp[i][j] = max(dp[i+1][j], dp[i][j-1]) for LPS, or 1 + min(...) for min insertions<br>
                        Base: dp[i][i] = 1; dp[i][i-1] = 0 (empty interval)<br>
                        Fill order: <code>for length in range(1, n+1): for i in range(n-length+1): j = i+length-1</code><br>
                        Preferred: Bottom-up by length; space optimisation: two rows sufficient (length L depends on length L-2)<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 1 â€” Boolean Palindrome:</strong><br>
                        dp[i][j] = True if s[i..j] is a palindrome<br>
                        Recurrence: dp[i][j] = (s[i] == s[j]) and dp[i+1][j-1]; Base: dp[i][i] = True; dp[i][i+1] = (s[i]==s[i+1])<br>
                        Fill: same length-ascending order; dp[i+1][j-1] requires length â‰¥ 3 check<br><br>
                        <strong>Group 2: Split-Point Interval DP (Merge/Cost)</strong><br>
                        <strong>Stage 1 â€” Merge Piles:</strong><br>
                        dp[i][j] = min cost to merge piles[i..j]; Recurrence: dp[i][j] = min over k in [i,j-1] of dp[i][k] + dp[k+1][j] + pre[j+1] - pre[i]; Base: dp[i][i] = 0<br>
                        Preferred: Bottom-up by length; top-down memoisation works but bottom-up gives cleaner control for Knuth optimisation<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 2 â€” Optimal BST:</strong><br>
                        dp[i][j] = min search cost for keys[i..j]; Recurrence: dp[i][j] = min over k in [i,j] of dp[i][k-1] + dp[k+1][j] + (pre[j+1] - pre[i])<br>
                        Note: k is the ROOT (not a split midpoint); left subtree is [i,k-1], right is [k+1,j]; Base: dp[i][i] = freq[i]; dp[i][i-1] = 0<br>
                        Optimisation (Stage 5): Track opt[i][j] = optimal root; by Knuth-Yao: opt[i][j-1] â‰¤ opt[i][j] â‰¤ opt[i+1][j]; reduces O(nÂ³) to O(nÂ²)<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 â€” Minimum Cost Merge Stones (K piles):</strong><br>
                        dp[i][j] = min cost to merge piles[i..j] into the minimum number of piles<br>
                        Recurrence: dp[i][j] = min over k in [i,j-K+1] stepping by (K-1) of dp[i][k] + dp[k+1][j]; then if (j-i) % (K-1) == 0: dp[i][j] += prefix[j+1]-prefix[i]<br>
                        Feasibility: (j-i) % (K-1) == 0 iff interval can be fully merged to 1 pile; Base: dp[i][i] = 0; dp[i][j] = INF if not feasible<br><br>
                        <strong>Group 3: "Last One Standing" Interval DP (Burst Balloons / Strange Printer)</strong><br>
                        <strong>Stage 4 â€” Burst Balloons:</strong><br>
                        dp[i][j] = max coins from bursting ALL balloons STRICTLY between i and j (exclusive; i and j are sentinels/boundaries)<br>
                        Recurrence: dp[i][j] = max over k in (i+1, j) of dp[i][k] + dp[k][j] + nums[i]*nums[k]*nums[j]<br>
                        k is the LAST balloon burst between i and j; when k is burst, i and j are still present (they are the current boundaries)<br>
                        Base: dp[i][j] = 0 when j-i &lt;= 1; Fill: by increasing j-i; outer loop len = 2..n+1, inner loop i = 0..n+1-len<br>
                        Note: nums array has 1 prepended and 1 appended as sentinels; dp indices run 0 to n+1<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 4 â€” Strange Printer:</strong><br>
                        dp[i][j] = min turns to print s[i..j]; Base case: dp[i][j] = dp[i+1][j] + 1 (print s[i] alone costs one extra turn)<br>
                        Optimisation: for k in range(i+1, j+1) where s[k] == s[i]: dp[i][j] = min(dp[i][j], dp[i+1][k] + dp[k][j])<br>
                        When s[i] == s[k], the turn for s[i] can extend to cover position k at no extra cost; Base: dp[i][i] = 1<br>
                        Fill: by decreasing i, increasing j (or by increasing length)<br><br>
                        <strong>Group 4: State-Expanded Interval DP (Remove Boxes)</strong><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 â€” Remove Boxes:</strong><br>
                        dp[i][j][k] = max points for boxes[i..j] with k EXTRA boxes identical to boxes[i] attached to the LEFT of i<br>
                        Base case (use boxes[i] alone with its k attachments): dp[i][j][k] = dp[i+1][j][0] + (k+1)Â²<br>
                        Teleport: for m in range(i+1, j+1) where boxes[m] == boxes[i]: dp[i][j][k] = max(dp[i][j][k], dp[i+1][m-1][0] + dp[m][j][k+1])<br>
                        Remove boxes[i+1..m-1] first, then solve [m..j] with k+1 boxes of type boxes[i] attached<br>
                        Preferred: Top-down memoisation â€” the three-dimensional state with the "teleport" structure is much cleaner with recursion + cache<br><br>
                        <strong>Group 5: Two-Boundary (Outside-In) DP</strong><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 â€” Maximum Score from Multiplication:</strong><br>
                        dp[i][j] = max score using i elements from left and j from right; ops = i+j; right index in nums = n-j<br>
                        Recurrence: Take from left: dp[i+1][j] = max(dp[i+1][j], dp[i][j] + mult[ops]*nums[i]); Take from right: dp[i][j+1] = max(dp[i][j+1], dp[i][j] + mult[ops]*nums[n-1-j])<br>
                        Base: dp[0][0] = 0; Fill: by increasing ops = i+j from 0 to m-1; answer = max(dp[i][m-i] for i in range(m+1))<br>
                        Preferred: Bottom-up by diagonal (constant ops = i+j); O(mÂ²) states
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">Pattern Recognition Triggers</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Linguistic Triggers:</strong><br>
                        "minimum cost to [merge/combine/reduce] all elements into one" â†’ Stage 1/3 split-merge interval DP â€” dp[i][j] + split-point loop + prefix sum cost<br>
                        "remove / burst / clear a contiguous range and earn coins based on boundary values" â†’ Stage 4 "last one standing" â€” k is the last removed; boundary values as cost multipliers<br>
                        "minimum number of [print/paint/operations] to cover a string" â†’ Stage 4 Strange Printer variant â€” same character can be covered in one pass; merge-on-match recurrence<br>
                        "triangulate a polygon to minimise total weight" â†’ Stage 4 polygon split â€” fix one vertex; k is third triangle vertex; dp[i][k]+dp[k][j]+cost(i,k,j)<br>
                        "minimum guaranteed cost / min max strategy over range [1..n]" â†’ Stage 2 minimax interval DP â€” adversarial max inside optimal min; k + max(left, right)<br><br>
                        <strong>Structural Triggers:</strong><br>
                        Input is a 1D sequence/array; the answer on the full array depends on the answer on ALL strict sub-arrays â†’ Interval DP; O(nÂ³) base; dp[i][j] filled by length<br>
                        Input is a polygon or circular sequence; the problem decomposes into triangles or sub-arcs â†’ Polygon interval DP; fix one vertex to linearise<br>
                        Problem involves removing groups of identical elements for bonus scoring (squared reward, exponential reward) â†’ State-expanded interval DP with count dimension dp[i][j][k]<br><br>
                        <strong>Constraint Triggers:</strong><br>
                        n â‰¤ 500 â†’ O(nÂ³) interval DP is 1.25Ã—10â¸ operations; tight but feasible in C++; use bottom-up to avoid recursion overhead<br>
                        n â‰¤ 100 with a third dimension â‰¤ n â†’ O(nâ´) is 10â¸; feasible for Remove Boxes-type problems<br><br>
                        <strong>Anti-Triggers:</strong><br>
                        "minimum cuts to partition string into palindromes" â†’ NOT O(nÂ³) interval DP â†’ O(nÂ²) two-phase DP: precompute palindrome table (interval DP), then 1D cut DP<br>
                        "longest palindromic SUBSTRING (contiguous)" â†’ NOT interval DP (O(nÂ²)) â†’ Manacher's algorithm O(n); interval DP is 10Ã— slower<br>
                        "minimum operations to make array non-decreasing by removing elements" â†’ NOT interval DP â†’ Greedy or LIS (n âˆ’ LIS = min removals); interval DP structure doesn't apply to global ordering constraints
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Decision Framework</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Q1:</strong> Is the answer for the full input computable from answers on CONTIGUOUS SUB-INTERVALS of the input?<br>
                        â†’ NO: Not interval DP. Check prefix DP, LIS, or greedy.<br>
                        â†’ YES: Continue.<br><br>
                        <strong>Q2:</strong> Which direction does the interval shrink?<br>
                        â†’ From BOTH ENDS (palindrome-style): s[i]==s[j] gives a bonus. dp[i][j] depends on dp[i+1][j-1], dp[i+1][j], dp[i][j-1]. â†’ Palindrome / LPS / Strange Printer family.<br>
                        â†’ By SPLITTING in the MIDDLE: dp[i][j] = over all k in [i,j-1]. â†’ Merge / Chain / Balloon / Triangulation family.<br>
                        â†’ From the OUTSIDE IN: take from left OR right at each step. â†’ Maximum Score from Multiplication / Stone Game family.<br><br>
                        <strong>Q3:</strong> What is the cost of the split at position k?<br>
                        â†’ Fixed function of the sub-interval (e.g., sum of merged piles) â†’ Add prefix sum array; standard O(nÂ³).<br>
                        â†’ Depends on BOUNDARY values of the current interval [i,j] (not internal values): â†’ "Last one standing" framing; k is the last removed; cost = product of boundary Ã— k value.<br>
                        â†’ Adversarial (takes max of two sub-problems): â†’ Minimax; dp[i][j] = min(k + max(dp[i][k-1], dp[k+1][j])).<br>
                        â†’ Has a COUNT attached at the boundary: â†’ Third dimension k = count; Remove Boxes / similar.<br><br>
                        <strong>Q4:</strong> Is there a feasibility constraint on which intervals are valid?<br>
                        â†’ YES: Add the check (e.g., (j-i)%(K-1)==0); skip infeasible.<br>
                        â†’ NO: All intervals valid.<br><br>
                        <strong>Q5:</strong> Is n â‰¤ 100 with a third dimension â‰¤ n? Or n â‰¤ 500?<br>
                        â†’ n â‰¤ 500: O(nÂ³) bottom-up feasible.<br>
                        â†’ n â‰¤ 1000: Need Knuth-Yao O(nÂ²) if cost satisfies quadrangle inequality.<br>
                        â†’ n â‰¤ 10âµ: Interval DP likely TLEs; consider divide-and-conquer DP or greedy.<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage identification:</strong> Q2 (palindrome shrink) â†’ Stage 1, O(nÂ²). Q2 (split) + Q3 (fixed cost) â†’ Stage 1, O(nÂ³). Q2 + one minimax/circular/count constraint â†’ Stage 2, O(nÂ³). Q3 (boundary-dependent cost) â†’ Stage 4, O(nÂ³). Q3 (count at boundary) â†’ Stage 3, O(nâ´) â†’ reduce with "teleport". Q5 (Knuth-Yao) â†’ Stage 5, O(nÂ²). If O(nÂ³) TLEs: check if cost satisfies quadrangle inequality â†’ Knuth O(nÂ²).
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">When This Technique BREAKS</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>[Stage 1] Non-contiguous dependencies:</strong> Interval DP requires that dp[i][j] depends ONLY on sub-intervals of [i,j]. If the cost of solving [i,j] depends on elements OUTSIDE [i,j] (e.g., global max, elements at other positions), the subproblem is not self-contained. Fix: expand the state to include the external dependency as an additional dimension, or use a different DP formulation (prefix DP, tree DP).<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 2] Circular arrays without breaking the circle:</strong> Applying linear interval DP directly to a circular array gives wrong answers because the first and last elements are neighbours but the interval [0,n-1] doesn't capture this adjacency. Fix: fix one element's state (e.g., fix element 0 as "not in the optimal solution" and run one pass; fix it as "in the optimal solution" and run another), then take the maximum.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 3] Wrong fill order for three-dimensional interval DP:</strong> With dp[i][j][k], filling by length j-i in the outer loop is necessary. Filling by i descending and j ascending (as in 2D) fails because dp[m][j][k+1] (used in Remove Boxes) requires m &gt; i â€” a longer interval in the middle dimension, which may not yet be computed. Fix: top-down memoisation handles fill order automatically; use it when the 3D fill order is non-trivial.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 4] Applying direct "order of operations" DP instead of "last one standing":</strong> For problems where the cost of removing element k depends on its current neighbours (Burst Balloons), DP on the ORDER of operations is exponential â€” the state must track which elements are present. Fix: reverse to "last removed" framing; k's cost is always well-defined because boundaries are fixed.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 5] Applying Knuth-Yao without verifying the quadrangle inequality:</strong> Knuth-Yao requires that the cost function w(i,j) satisfies w(a,c) + w(b,d) â‰¤ w(a,d) + w(b,c) for a â‰¤ b â‰¤ c â‰¤ d. Not all cost functions satisfy this. Applying Knuth-Yao to an invalid cost function gives silently wrong optimal split points. Fix: verify the quadrangle inequality holds for your specific cost function before applying the optimisation.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Proof of Correctness Skeleton</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Stage 1 â€” Merge Piles (Split-Point DP): Optimal Substructure</strong><br>
                        <strong>Claim:</strong> dp[i][j] = min over k of dp[i][k] + dp[k+1][j] + sum(piles[i..j]) is the true minimum cost.<br>
                        <strong>Optimal substructure:</strong> Consider the optimal sequence of merges for [i,j]. There exists a LAST merge that combines piles [i,k] and [k+1,j] into one. The cost of this last merge is sum(piles[i..j]) (total elements). The cost of ALL prior merges is cost([i,k]) + cost([k+1,j]).<br>
                        <strong>Minimality:</strong> The optimal solution to [i,j] uses the optimal solutions to [i,k] and [k+1,j]. If either sub-solution were non-optimal, we could replace it and reduce the total â€” contradicting optimality. Induction follows from single piles (length 1) costing 0. â–¡<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 4 â€” Burst Balloons: "Last to Burst" Correctness</strong><br>
                        <strong>Claim:</strong> dp[i][j] = max over k of dp[i][k] + dp[k][j] + nums[i]*nums[k]*nums[j] correctly computes the max coins from bursting all balloons strictly between i and j.<br>
                        <strong>Well-definedness of boundary:</strong> When k is burst LAST among balloons in (i,j), all balloons in (i,k) and (k,j) have already been burst. Therefore k's current neighbours are EXACTLY i and j. The cost nums[i]*nums[k]*nums[j] is correct.<br>
                        <strong>Independence of sub-problems:</strong> Since k is burst last, the operations on (i,k) and (k,j) are completely independent â€” no balloon in one half affects the other half's cost. The two sub-problems dp[i][k] and dp[k][j] are correctly independent.<br>
                        <strong>Completeness:</strong> Every balloon in (i,j) is accounted for: each is either in (i,k) or (k,j) and will be counted as k in some sub-problem. No balloon is missed or double-counted. â–¡<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 â€” Remove Boxes: State Validity</strong><br>
                        <strong>Claim:</strong> dp[i][j][k] = max points for boxes[i..j] with k extra boxes of type boxes[i] attached to the left correctly decomposes the problem.<br>
                        <strong>Transition correctness (base):</strong> Remove all k+1 boxes together with boxes[i] immediately: score = (k+1)Â² + solve dp[i+1][j][0] independently. âœ“<br>
                        <strong>Transition correctness (teleport):</strong> Find m in (i,j) where boxes[m] == boxes[i]. Remove boxes in (i+1,m-1) first, then solve dp[m][j][k+1] â€” boxes[m] is the new "front" with k+1 attachments (including boxes[i]). This correctly models grouping non-adjacent equal boxes.<br>
                        <strong>Consistency:</strong> The final group score (k+1)Â² is only counted once â€” in the base case when all k+1 boxes are removed together. The teleport case delays this removal; it never double-counts. â–¡
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Implementation Pitfalls (Code-Level)</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Bug 1 â€” Wrong fill order (row-major instead of by length):</strong><br>
                        <code># BUG: dp[i+1][j-1] not yet computed when processing row i<br>
                        for i in range(n-1, -1, -1):<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;for j in range(i+1, n):<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;dp[i][j] = dp[i+1][j-1] + 2 if s[i]==s[j] else ...  # BUG for some (i,j)<br>
                        # FIX: iterate by length<br>
                        for length in range(2, n+1):<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;for i in range(n - length + 1):<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;j = i + length - 1; dp[i][j] = ...</code><br><br>
                        <strong>Bug 2 â€” Balloon burst: not adding sentinel values:</strong><br>
                        <code># BUG: boundary multiplications use missing indices<br>
                        nums = [3,1,5,8]  # no sentinels â€” out-of-bounds at edges<br>
                        # FIX: add sentinels<br>
                        nums = [1] + nums + [1]  # sentinel 1s at both ends<br>
                        n_ext = len(nums)  # n+2<br>
                        dp = [[0]*n_ext for _ in range(n_ext)]</code><br><br>
                        <strong>Bug 3 â€” Strange Printer: wrong base initialisation:</strong><br>
                        <code># BUG: dp[i][j] = dp[i][j-1] + 1 â€” wrong base<br>
                        dp[i][j] = dp[i][j-1] + 1  # BUG: should reference dp[i+1][j]<br>
                        # FIX: print s[i] alone; then solve rest<br>
                        dp[i][j] = dp[i+1][j] + 1</code><br><br>
                        <strong>Bug 4 â€” Guess Number: using min instead of max for adversary:</strong><br>
                        <code># BUG: taking min of two sub-problems (adversary picks best for US)<br>
                        dp[i][j] = min(k + min(dp[i][k-1], dp[k+1][j]) for k in range(i, j+1))  # BUG<br>
                        # FIX: adversary picks worst case for us<br>
                        dp[i][j] = min(k + max(dp[i][k-1], dp[k+1][j]) for k in range(i, j+1))</code><br><br>
                        <strong>Bug 5 â€” Merge Stones: not checking feasibility before final merge:</strong><br>
                        <code># BUG: always adds merge cost even if infeasible<br>
                        dp[i][j] += prefix[j+1] - prefix[i]   # BUG: skips feasibility check<br>
                        # FIX: only add when (j-i) % (K-1) == 0<br>
                        if (j - i) % (K - 1) == 0:<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;dp[i][j] += prefix[j+1] - prefix[i]</code><br><br>
                        <strong>Bug 6 â€” Remove Boxes: teleport passes k instead of k+1:</strong><br>
                        <code># BUG: solving right sub-problem without the accumulated count<br>
                        dp[i][j][k] = max(dp[i][j][k], dp[i+1][m-1][0] + dp[m][j][k])  # BUG: k not k+1<br>
                        # FIX: boxes[i] is still attached â€” pass k+1<br>
                        dp[i][j][k] = max(dp[i][j][k], dp[i+1][m-1][0] + dp[m][j][k+1])</code><br><br>
                        <strong>Bug 7 â€” Polygon triangulation: k over [i,j] inclusive instead of (i,j) exclusive:</strong><br>
                        <code># BUG: k=i or k=j creates a degenerate triangle<br>
                        for k in range(i, j+1):   # BUG: includes k=i and k=j<br>
                        # FIX: k must be strictly between i and j<br>
                        for k in range(i+1, j):   # exclusive of both endpoints</code><br><br>
                        <strong>Bug 8 â€” Strange Printer: not checking s[i]==s[k] before merge transition:</strong><br>
                        <code># BUG: applying free extension for all k, not just when s[i]==s[k]<br>
                        for k in range(i+1, j+1):<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;dp[i][j] = min(dp[i][j], dp[i+1][k] + dp[k][j])  # BUG: always merges<br>
                        # FIX: only when characters match<br>
                        for k in range(i+1, j+1):<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;if s[k] == s[i]:<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;dp[i][j] = min(dp[i][j], dp[i+1][k] + dp[k][j])</code><br><br>
                        <strong>Bug 9 â€” Knuth-Yao: wrong bounds for opt array update:</strong><br>
                        <code># BUG: unconstrained inner loop ignores monotonicity<br>
                        for k in range(i, j):   # BUG: should use Knuth bounds<br>
                        # FIX: constrain by monotonicity<br>
                        for k in range(opt[i][j-1], opt[i+1][j]+1):  # Knuth bounds</code>
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">Red Flags / Common Mistakes</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>[Stage 1] Filling the DP by row instead of by length:</strong> The recurrence dp[i][j] depends on dp[i+1][j-1], which requires both a later row AND an earlier column. Row-major fill processes dp[i+1][...] AFTER row i, so dp[i+1][j-1] may not yet be computed. Correct model: <em>"Always fill interval DP by INCREASING LENGTH L = j-i+1. For L=1, L=2, ..., L=n. Within each length, iterate i from 0 to n-L."</em><br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 4] Applying direct "order of removal" DP to Burst Balloons:</strong> The natural DP dp[mask] = max coins is correct but exponential O(2â¿Â·n). Candidates who don't recognise the "last to burst" insight get TLE. Correct model: <em>"When the cost of removing element k depends on its current neighbours (which change as others are removed), REVERSE the problem: decide which element is removed LAST. Its neighbours are then FIXED as the interval boundaries."</em><br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 2] Predicting the Winner: using absolute scores instead of score difference:</strong> dp[i][j] should represent the DIFFERENCE between the current player's score and the other player's score, not the absolute score. Correct model: <em>"Score difference encodes both players' optimality in ONE value. dp[i][j] = max(a[i]âˆ’dp[i+1][j], a[j]âˆ’dp[i][j-1]) handles this automatically."</em><br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 3] Remove Boxes: forgetting the third dimension exists:</strong> Candidates attempt O(nÂ³) interval DP and get Wrong Answer. The cost of removing a group of identical boxes is countÂ², so the NUMBER of boxes in the current group MUST be tracked. Correct model: <em>"Whenever a problem's cost for removing/processing an element depends on HOW MANY IDENTICAL elements are being processed simultaneously (including ones 'attached' from outside), add a count dimension to the state."</em><br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 4] Strange Printer: thinking each character requires its own turn:</strong> The baseline dp[i][j] = dp[i+1][j] + 1 overcounts. A single printer turn can cover ANY contiguous block of the SAME character. Correct model: <em>"The printer can start printing s[i] and EXTEND that same print to cover s[k] wherever s[k]==s[i], without using an extra turn. The dp[i+1][k] + dp[k][j] transition removes the need for a separate turn for s[k] by merging it with s[i]'s turn."</em><br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 5] Applying Knuth-Yao without verifying the quadrangle inequality:</strong> Not every cost function satisfies the monotone optimal split property. If w(i,j) does not satisfy w(a,c) + w(b,d) â‰¤ w(a,d) + w(b,c) for aâ‰¤bâ‰¤câ‰¤d, the opt array is NOT monotone and Knuth-Yao gives WRONG ANSWERS silently. Correct model: <em>"Before applying Knuth-Yao: verify that your cost function satisfies the quadrangle inequality. For merge problems with cost = sum of merged elements (prefix sum), this is satisfied. For arbitrary cost functions, prove it or test it empirically on small cases."</em><br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 3] Minimum Cost Merge Stones: skipping the feasibility check:</strong> Not all intervals can be reduced to 1 pile when K&gt;2. An interval of length L can be reduced to 1 pile iff (L-1) % (K-1) == 0. Without this check, wrong minimums result. Correct model: <em>"For K-merge problems, FIRST check feasibility: can this interval be reduced to 1 pile? Only add the final merge cost (+= prefix[j+1]-prefix[i]) when the feasibility condition holds."</em>
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Interviewer Follow-Up Questions</div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Stage</th><th>Question</th><th>Intended Answer Direction</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>1</td><td>2</td><td>"What if we can only merge adjacent piles of exactly equal size (like merge sort)?"</td><td>Only merge piles of equal size; dp[i][j] only valid when piles are equal after recursive merging; same structure but gated transitions; O(n log n) for power-of-2 sizes</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>2</td><td>2</td><td>"What if the cost of merging piles is their PRODUCT instead of their sum?"</td><td>Same split-point structure; cost function changes from sum to product; verify if Knuth-Yao still applies (check quadrangle inequality for product cost â€” it generally does not hold, so O(nÂ³) remains)</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>3</td><td>3</td><td>"Burst Balloons: now you must burst balloons in groups of exactly 3 adjacent ones. How does the DP change?"</td><td>"Last group to burst" framing extended: k is the middle of the last group of 3; dp[i][j] = max over k in (i+1,j-1) of dp[i][k-1] + dp[k+1][j] + cost(k-1,k,k+1); intervals shrink by 3 at minimum</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>4</td><td>3</td><td>"How do you reconstruct the optimal order of operations (not just the cost)?"</td><td>Parent pointer array choice[i][j] = optimal k for each interval; backtrack recursively: choice[i][j] gives the split; recurse into [i,choice[i][j]] and [choice[i][j]+1,j]; produces a binary tree of operations</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>5</td><td>4</td><td>"Can you identify a problem where interval DP over a TREE is needed?"</td><td>Euler tour of a tree converts tree sub-problems to linear intervals; dp[i][j] on the Euler tour = DP on the subtree rooted at LCA(tour[i], tour[j]); used for tree path optimisation problems</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>6</td><td>4</td><td>"Strange Printer with 2 printers operating simultaneously â€” how does the state change?"</td><td>State becomes dp[i][j][k][l] = min turns for two printers covering [i,j] and [k,l]; 4D interval DP; turns taken = max of both printers' turns (parallel); non-trivial to enumerate valid split assignments</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>7</td><td>5</td><td>"When does O(nÂ³) interval DP improve to O(nÂ²) and how?"</td><td>Knuth-Yao optimisation: when cost w(i,j) satisfies the quadrangle inequality AND optimal split opt[i][j] is monotone: opt[i][j-1] â‰¤ opt[i][j] â‰¤ opt[i+1][j]; inner loop runs from opt[i][j-1] to opt[i+1][j]; amortised O(1) per cell</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>8</td><td>5</td><td>"Can you do better than O(nÂ²) for Longest Palindromic Subsequence?"</td><td>O(nÂ²) is the known lower bound for arbitrary strings using DP; Manacher's O(n) only applies to SUBSTRING (not subsequence); for LPS, O(nÂ²) with O(n) space (two rolling rows) is optimal for general strings</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>9</td><td>Beyond</td><td>"Distribute the Burst Balloons DP across 10 machines. How?"</td><td>Interval DP parallelises naturally by LENGTH: all intervals of length L are independent of each other (they only depend on length &lt; L intervals). Assign each diagonal (fixed length) to a separate machine; synchronise between diagonals. Communication cost = O(nÂ²) per sync round</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>10</td><td>Beyond</td><td>"Burst Balloons but n = 10â¶ balloons. Is O(nÂ³) the best you can do?"</td><td>For general balloon values: O(nÂ³) is optimal (no known sub-cubic algorithm for general interval DP). For special structure (e.g., all values equal, sorted values): greedy or divide-and-conquer DP might give O(n log n). For n=10â¶, approximation algorithms or online/streaming variants are necessary</td></tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table></div>

