            <div class="topic-card" id="tp36">
            <div class="topic-header">
                <div class="topic-num">36</div>
                <div>
                    <div class="topic-title">Partition DP</div>
                    <div class="topic-meta">
                        <span class="tier-badge tier-T5">T5</span>
                        <span class="topic-type">Dynamic Programming</span>
                        <span class="topic-type">1D Partition DP</span>
                        <span class="topic-type">2D Partition DP</span>
                        <span class="topic-type">3D Partition DP</span>
                        <span class="topic-type">Convex Hull Trick</span>
                        <span class="topic-type">Divide &amp; Conquer DP</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="topic-body">
                    <div class="sec-title">Why This Topic Matters</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        Partition DP solves problems where a 1D sequence must be cut into contiguous segments, and the optimal answer is built by deciding WHERE to place each cut. The core invariant is: <strong>dp[i] = optimal value for the prefix a[0..i-1]</strong>, computed by scanning all possible last segments a[j..i-1] and taking the best over all valid cut points j. This pattern is distinct from Interval DP (which optimises the ORDER of operations) and from Knapsack (which selects non-contiguous items) â€” Partition DP always produces a sequential, non-overlapping, exhaustive division of the array. It dominates top-tier interviews because: (1) the recurrence <code>dp[i] = min/max over j &lt; i of (dp[j] + cost(j, i))</code> is a 3-line template that solves a vast class of problems; (2) the cost function <code>cost(j, i)</code> is what varies â€” sometimes a sum, sometimes a max, sometimes a string match, sometimes a painting cost â€” and recognising which is the only skill needed; and (3) the Stage 5 optimisation (Divide &amp; Conquer DP or Convex Hull Trick) converts O(nÂ²) to O(n log n) and is a ICPC/IOI-essential technique.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">The Mental Model</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        Partition DP is a <strong>cutting problem</strong>. You have a ribbon of length n. You must cut it into segments. Each segment [j..i-1] has a cost or score. You want to minimise the total cost (or maximise the total score) over all ways to cut. <code>dp[i]</code> = best total cost when you've made all cuts within the first i elements. For each i, you try every possible "last cut position" j and ask: <em>"What if the last segment is [j..i-1]?"</em><br><br>
                        The universal recurrence:<br>
                        <code>dp[i] = min over 0 â‰¤ j &lt; i of (dp[j] + cost(j, i))</code><br><br>
                        Everything in Partition DP is a variation of this formula. The ONLY thing that changes across problems is <code>cost(j, i)</code>.<br><br>
                        <strong>How this scales through the 5 stages:</strong><br>
                        <strong>Stage 1:</strong> cost(j,i) is trivial (sum of elements in segment, fixed penalty per cut, or dictionary word match). O(nÂ²) or O(nÂ·m) where m = dictionary size.<br>
                        <strong>Stage 2:</strong> Same structure; ONE constraint changes â€” bounded number of cuts k (adds a second dimension), or the cost function requires a running max instead of a sum.<br>
                        <strong>Stage 3:</strong> State expands: dp[i][k] = optimal value for first i elements using exactly k segments. The recurrence iterates over j AND k simultaneously.<br>
                        <strong>Stage 4:</strong> Problem doesn't say "partition." The "sequence" must be identified: a bookcase where each shelf is a segment, a job schedule where each day-range is a segment, paint costs where colour groups are segments.<br>
                        <strong>Stage 5:</strong> O(nÂ²) is too slow. The cost function is linear in j â†’ apply Convex Hull Trick (O(n log n)). Or the optimal cut point j* for dp[i] is monotone in i â†’ apply Divide &amp; Conquer DP (O(n log n)).
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Core Invariant / Proof Sketch</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Invariant:</strong> dp[i] = optimal value achievable for a partition of the prefix a[0..i-1] into any number of valid contiguous segments.<br><br>
                        <strong>Proof sketch (strong induction on i):</strong><br>
                        <strong>Base case:</strong> dp[0] = 0 â€” empty prefix costs nothing; zero segments. âœ“<br>
                        <strong>Inductive step:</strong> Assume dp[j] is correct for all j &lt; i. For prefix a[0..i-1], consider any optimal partition. There exists a last segment a[j..i-1] for some j âˆˆ [0,i). The rest of the partition covers a[0..j-1], contributing dp[j] (optimal by hypothesis). The last segment contributes cost(j,i). Total = dp[j] + cost(j,i).<br>
                        <strong>Minimality:</strong> The optimal last-segment choice minimises over all valid j: dp[i] = min(dp[j] + cost(j,i)). Since we try ALL j, the optimal j is included. âœ“<br>
                        <strong>Correctness of dp[j]:</strong> Since dp[j] was computed correctly before dp[i] (j &lt; i, left-to-right fill), the induction holds. â–¡<br><br>
                        <strong>Why this works for maximisation too:</strong> Replace min with max. The exchange argument is identical â€” any optimal partition has a "last segment"; fixing it and optimising the prefix is the same decomposition.
                    </div>

