                    <div class="sec-title">State Evolution Across Stages</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Group 1: 1D Partition DP (Single Dimension)</strong><br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 1 â€” Word Break / Decode Ways:</strong><br>
                        <code>dp[i]</code> = boolean (can prefix of length i be partitioned?) or integer (count/cost for prefix of length i)<br>
                        Recurrence: <code>dp[i] = OR(dp[j] AND valid(j,i))</code> for boolean; <code>dp[i] = SUM(dp[j] for valid j)</code> for count; <code>dp[i] = MIN(dp[j] + cost(j,i))</code> for optimisation<br>
                        Base: <code>dp[0] = True</code> (or 1 for count, 0 for min-cost)<br>
                        Fill: left to right; dp[i] uses all dp[j] for j &lt; i<br>
                        Preferred: Bottom-up left-to-right â€” memoised top-down also works; bottom-up avoids recursion overhead for n â‰¤ 10âµ<br>
                        Space: O(n) â€” only the dp array needed<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 1 â€” Partition Array for Maximum Sum:</strong><br>
                        <code>dp[i]</code> = max sum partitioning a[0..i-1] with each segment length â‰¤ k<br>
                        Recurrence: <code>dp[i] = max(dp[j] + (i-j) * max(a[j..i-1]) for j in range(max(0,i-k), i))</code><br>
                        Running max: as j decreases from i-1 to i-k, maintain <code>cur_max = max(cur_max, a[j])</code>; avoids O(k) recompute per j<br>
                        Base: <code>dp[0] = 0</code><br>
                        Fill: left to right; inner loop runs at most k iterations â†’ O(nÂ·k)
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Group 2: 2D Partition DP (Position Ã— Count)</strong><br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 â€” Largest Sum of Averages / Min Job Difficulty / Split Array:</strong><br>
                        <code>dp[i][k]</code> = optimal value for first i elements partitioned into exactly k segments<br>
                        Recurrence: <code>dp[i][k] = opt(dp[j][k-1] + cost(j, i) for j in range(k-1, i))</code><br>
                        j â‰¥ k-1 ensures prior k-1 segments had at least one element each<br>
                        Base: <code>dp[0][0] = 0</code>; <code>dp[i][k] = +âˆž</code> (or <code>-âˆž</code>) for k &gt; i (not enough elements)<br>
                        Cost functions:<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;Sum of averages: cost(j,i) = (prefix[i] - prefix[j]) / (i-j) â€” O(1) with prefix sums<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;Job difficulty: cost(j,i) = max(jobs[j..i-1]) â€” O(1) with sliding max during j-scan<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;Split array: cost(j,i) = max(a[j..i-1]) â€” same as job difficulty<br>
                        Preferred: Bottom-up, outer loop over k (1 to K), inner loop over i (k to n), innermost over j â€” fill order guarantees dp[j][k-1] is available when computing dp[i][k]<br>
                        Optimisation (Stage 5): If cost(j,i) satisfies the concave SMAWK condition, D&amp;C DP applies â†’ O(n log n)
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Group 3: 3D Partition DP (Position Ã— Count Ã— Mode)</strong><br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3/4 â€” Paint House III / String Compression / Word Break with Budget:</strong><br>
                        <code>dp[i][k][c]</code> = optimal value for first i elements, k "groups/segments used", last-segment type/color c<br>
                        Recurrence: <code>dp[i][k][c] = opt(dp[j][k-1][c'] + cost(j,i,c) for all j &lt; i and c' compatible with c)</code><br>
                        Base: depends on problem; typically <code>dp[0][0][*] = 0</code>; all others +âˆž<br>
                        Key: the third dimension c GATES transitions â€” same color c as previous â†’ don't increment k; different â†’ increment k<br>
                        Preferred: Top-down memoisation â€” three-dimensional state with conditional third-dimension transitions is error-prone in bottom-up; memoisation handles order automatically
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Group 4: Optimised Partition DP (Stage 5)</strong><br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 5a â€” Convex Hull Trick:</strong><br>
                        Applicable when: <code>dp[i] = min over j of (dp[j] + a[j]*i + b[j])</code> â€” cost is a linear function of the query variable i<br>
                        View each j as a line <code>y = a[j]*x + b[j]</code> where y = dp[j] + cost; query at x=i<br>
                        Maintain lower convex hull of lines; binary search for minimum â†’ O(log n) per query<br>
                        Total: O(n log n); or O(n) if queries are monotone (deque-based CHT)<br>
                        Li Chao tree: alternative for non-monotone j or i; O(n log V) where V = value range<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 5b â€” Divide &amp; Conquer DP:</strong><br>
                        Applicable when: opt[i] (optimal j for dp[i]) is monotone: opt[i] â‰¤ opt[i+1]<br>
                        Condition: cost function satisfies the quadrangle inequality: cost(a,c) + cost(b,d) â‰¤ cost(a,d) + cost(b,c) for a â‰¤ b â‰¤ c â‰¤ d<br>
                        Algorithm:<br>
                        <code>solve(lo, hi, opt_lo, opt_hi):<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;mid = (lo + hi) // 2<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;scan j from opt_lo to min(opt_hi, mid-1); find opt_mid<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;dp[mid] = best value found<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;solve(lo, mid-1, opt_lo, opt_mid)<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;solve(mid+1, hi, opt_mid, opt_hi)</code><br>
                        Total: O(n log n) â€” each level of recursion scans O(n) j values total; O(log n) levels
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">Pattern Recognition Triggers</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Linguistic Triggers:</strong><br>
                        "partition / split / divide array into [k] contiguous parts" â†’ Stage 3 2D partition DP â€” dp[i][k]; cost = function of last segment<br>
                        "minimum number of [cuts / splits] to make each segment satisfy property P" â†’ Stage 1/2 1D partition DP â€” dp[i] = min cuts; cost(j,i) = âˆž if P not satisfied<br>

                        "fill shelves / schedule jobs / assign tasks to days" â†’ Stage 4 disguised partition DP â€” identify what a "segment" is; cost = max or sum per segment<br>
                        "word break / can string be decoded as [words / codes]" â†’ Stage 1 feasibility partition DP â€” dp[i] boolean; hash set for O(1) segment validity<br>
                        "maximum score from partitioning where score = f(segment)" â†’ Stage 1/2 optimisation partition DP â€” dp[i] = max(dp[j] + f(s[j:i]))<br><br>
                        <strong>Structural Triggers:</strong><br>
                        Input is a 1D sequence; output is a scalar (min cost, max score, count); answer requires dividing the sequence into non-overlapping contiguous parts â†’ Partition DP; O(nÂ²) base; dp[i] with inner j-loop<br>
                        Problem has an explicit "k parts" or "d days" constraint â€” answer depends on BOTH position AND count â†’ 2D partition DP dp[i][k]; O(nÂ²k)<br>
                        Third dimension appears when the "type" or "color" of the last segment affects future segment costs â†’ 3D dp[i][k][c]<br><br>
                        <strong>Constraint Triggers:</strong><br>
                        n â‰¤ 1000 and k â‰¤ 100 â†’ O(nÂ²k) feasible; standard 2D partition DP<br>
                        n â‰¤ 10âµ with O(nÂ²) TLE â†’ check if cost function is linear in j (CHT) or if opt is monotone (D&amp;C)<br><br>
                        <strong>Anti-Triggers:</strong><br>
                        "partition array into two subsets with minimum difference" â†’ NOT contiguous partition DP â†’ 0/1 Knapsack dp[s]; elements need not be contiguous<br>
                        "burst balloons / remove elements with cost depending on neighbours" â†’ NOT partition DP â†’ Interval DP ("last one standing"); cost has cross-segment dependencies<br>
                        "minimum cost to merge non-adjacent segments" â†’ NOT 1D partition DP â†’ Interval DP (arbitrary split order); the "non-adjacent" or "arbitrary order" property breaks partition DP's left-to-right structure
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Decision Framework</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Q1:</strong> Does the problem ask for optimal value (min/max/count) of a partition of a 1D sequence into CONTIGUOUS, NON-OVERLAPPING segments covering all elements?<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;â†’ NO: Not partition DP. Check knapsack (non-contiguous), interval DP (arbitrary order), or greedy.<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;â†’ YES: Continue.<br><br>
                        <strong>Q2:</strong> What does cost(j, i) depend on?<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;â†’ Segment content (sum, max, avg, dict lookup, palindrome check): â†’ Standard partition DP. O(nÂ²). Go to Q3.<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;â†’ Cross-segment interaction (cost of segment [j,i] depends on what's in [0,j-1] or [i,n-1]): â†’ NOT partition DP. Use interval DP or state machine DP.<br><br>
                        <strong>Q3:</strong> Is there a BOUND on the number of segments (exactly k or at most k)?<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;â†’ YES: Add k as second dimension. dp[i][k]. O(nÂ²k). Go to Q4.<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;â†’ NO: 1D dp[i]. O(nÂ²). Go to Q5.<br><br>
                        <strong>Q4:</strong> Does the cost or transition also depend on the TYPE/COLOR/MODE of the last segment?<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;â†’ YES: Third dimension. dp[i][k][c]. O(nÂ²Â·kÂ·C). Top-down recommended.<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;â†’ NO: Standard 2D. dp[i][k].<br><br>
                        <strong>Q5:</strong> Is n &gt; 5000 and O(nÂ²) TLEs?<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;â†’ Is cost(j,i) LINEAR in j? â†’ YES: Convex Hull Trick. O(n log n).<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;â†’ Is the optimal j* monotone (opt[i] â‰¤ opt[i+1])? â†’ YES: Divide &amp; Conquer DP. O(n log n).<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;â†’ Is the window of valid j fixed (e.g., |j-i| â‰¤ k)? â†’ YES: Sliding window max/deque DP. O(nÂ·k) â†’ O(n).<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;â†’ None apply: O(nÂ²) may be unavoidable. Check if n â‰¤ 5000.<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage identification:</strong><br>
                        Q2 (simple cost) + Q3 (no k) â†’ Stage 1. O(nÂ²) or better.<br>
                        Q2 + Q3 (k bound) â†’ Stage 3. O(nÂ²k).<br>
                        Q4 (color/type) â†’ Stage 3. O(nÂ²Â·kÂ·C). Use top-down.<br>
                        Problem disguised (shelves/jobs/paint) â†’ Stage 4. Same complexity.<br>
                        Q5 (CHT or D&amp;C) â†’ Stage 5. O(n log n).<br>
                        If O(nÂ²) TLEs: check linearity of cost (CHT) or opt monotonicity (D&amp;C).
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">When This Technique BREAKS</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">
                        <strong>[Stage 1] Cost function has cross-segment dependencies:</strong> Partition DP requires that cost(j,i) depends ONLY on the segment a[j..i-1], never on segments outside it. If the cost of a segment changes based on what's already been computed, the subproblem is not self-contained. Fix: expand the state to include the relevant property of the adjacent segment as a dimension (making it a state machine DP or 3D partition DP).<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 2] Counting ALL partitions without dp pruning (Word Break II):</strong> Enumerating all valid partitions by backtracking without first building the feasibility dp table leads to exponential time on strings where many prefixes are reachable but the full string is not. Fix: always run the O(nÂ²) boolean dp pass first; only DFS from positions where dp[pos] = True.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 3] Wrong boundary for the j-loop in k-segment DP:</strong> In dp[i][k], the inner j-loop must start at j = k-1 (not j = 0). Starting at j = 0 allows segments where previous k-1 groups don't have enough elements â€” dp[j][k-1] would be -âˆž or invalid. Additionally, dp[i][k] is only valid for i â‰¥ k (need at least k elements for k segments). Fix: always enforce j â‰¥ k-1 in the inner loop and initialise dp[i][k] = +âˆž for i &lt; k.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 5] Applying CHT when cost is not linear in j:</strong> CHT requires cost(j,i) = a(j)*i + b(j) â€” strictly linear in the query variable i. If the cost involves max/min of segment (not sum), it is NOT linear â†’ CHT doesn't apply. Use D&amp;C DP if opt is monotone, or accept O(nÂ²). Silently applying CHT to a non-linear cost gives wrong answers.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 5] D&amp;C DP when opt is NOT monotone:</strong> If the cost function does not satisfy the quadrangle inequality, opt[i] is not monotone and D&amp;C DP gives wrong answers. Fix: always verify opt monotonicity on small cases before applying D&amp;C DP. If in doubt, verify the quadrangle inequality algebraically.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 4] Treating "Burst Balloons" / "Remove Boxes" as partition DP:</strong> These problems have costs that depend on what's adjacent to the current segment â€” which changes as elements are removed. Partition DP assumes each segment's cost is fixed once the endpoints are known. Fix: use Interval DP with the "last one standing" framing.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Proof of Correctness Skeleton</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Stage 1 â€” Word Break: Optimal Substructure</strong><br>
                        Claim: dp[i] = OR(dp[j] AND s[j:i] in dictionary for j in 0..i-1) correctly determines if s[0..i-1] can be word-broken.<br>
                        Optimal substructure: If s[0..i-1] can be word-broken, there exists a LAST word s[j..i-1] in the dictionary, and s[0..j-1] can also be word-broken (dp[j] = True).<br>
                        Completeness: We try ALL j âˆˆ [0,i); therefore the correct last-word split point is always considered.<br>
                        Base case: dp[0] = True â€” empty string is trivially word-breakable (zero words).<br>
                        Induction: dp[i] uses only dp[j] for j &lt; i (computed before i in left-to-right order). âœ“ â–¡<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 â€” Largest Sum of Averages: Correctness of 2D DP</strong><br>
                        Claim: dp[i][k] = max(dp[j][k-1] + sum(a[j..i-1])/(i-j) for j in k-1..i-1) = max sum of k group averages for a[0..i-1].<br>
                        Invariant: dp[i][k] = max sum of k group averages for ANY k-partition of a[0..i-1].<br>
                        Base: dp[i][1] = avg(a[0..i-1]) = average of the single group. âœ“<br>
                        Induction on k: For k groups, the LAST group is a[j..i-1] for some j. Its average is sum(a[j..i-1])/(i-j). The first k-1 groups cover a[0..j-1], contributing dp[j][k-1] (optimal by induction). Since we maximise over all valid j (j â‰¥ k-1 ensures k-1 groups have â‰¥ 1 element each), we find the true optimum. âœ“<br>
                        Prefix sums: sum(a[j..i-1]) = prefix[i] - prefix[j] in O(1); does not affect correctness, only efficiency. â–¡<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 5 â€” Divide &amp; Conquer DP: Correctness of Pruned Search</strong><br>
                        Claim: If opt[lo] â‰¤ opt[mid] â‰¤ opt[hi] (monotone optimal split), the D&amp;C search finds the true optimal j for every i.<br>
                        Monotonicity assumption: The cost function satisfies the quadrangle inequality, ensuring opt[i] is non-decreasing.<br>
                        D&amp;C invariant: When solve(lo, hi, opt_lo, opt_hi) is called, the true opt[i] for any i âˆˆ [lo,hi] lies in [opt_lo, opt_hi]. We scan only this range for i = mid.<br>
                        Left recursion: For i âˆˆ [lo, mid-1], opt[i] â‰¤ opt[mid], so the true opt lies in [opt_lo, opt_mid]. âœ“<br>
                        Right recursion: For i âˆˆ [mid+1, hi], opt[i] â‰¥ opt[mid], so the true opt lies in [opt_mid, opt_hi]. âœ“<br>
                        Work per level: At each recursion level, the sum of opt_hi - opt_lo across all calls = O(n). With O(log n) levels, total work = O(n log n). â–¡
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Implementation Pitfalls (Code-Level)</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">
                        <strong>Bug 1 â€” Word Break: using s[i:j] instead of s[j:i]</strong><br>
                        <code># BUG: slice indices reversed<br>
                        if dp[j] and s[i:j] in word_set:   # BUG: i &gt; j always here<br>
                        # FIX:<br>
                        if dp[j] and s[j:i] in word_set:   # segment from j to i (exclusive)</code><br><br>
                        <strong>Bug 2 â€” Decode Ways: not handling leading zero / single-digit zero</strong><br>
                        <code># BUG omission: "0" should NOT be decoded as a single digit<br>
                        if s[i-1] != '0':     # missing this guard<br>
                            dp[i] += dp[i-1]<br>
                        # FIX: always add this zero-guard for single-digit check</code><br><br>
                        <strong>Bug 3 â€” Palindrome Partitioning II: initialising dp[i] = i instead of i-1</strong><br>
                        <code># BUG: worst case is i-1 cuts (each char separate), not i cuts<br>
                        dp = list(range(n+1))   # dp[i] = i: BUG, off by 1<br>
                        # FIX:<br>
                        dp[0] = -1  # sentinel so dp[0]+1 = 0 cuts for valid palindrome at 0<br>
                        dp = [i-1 for i in range(n+1)]</code><br><br>
                        <strong>Bug 4 â€” Partition Array for Max Sum: not resetting running max per i</strong><br>
                        <code># BUG: cur_max carries over from previous i<br>
                        for i in range(1, n+1):<br>
                            for j in range(max(0, i-k), i):<br>
                                cur_max = max(cur_max, a[j])   # BUG: not reset<br>
                        # FIX: reset cur_max inside outer loop<br>
                        for i in range(1, n+1):<br>
                            cur_max = 0<br>
                            for j in range(i-1, max(-1, i-k-1), -1):<br>
                                cur_max = max(cur_max, a[j])<br>
                                dp[i] = max(dp[i], dp[j] + (i-j) * cur_max)</code><br><br>
                        <strong>Bug 5 â€” 2D DP: j-loop starting at 0 instead of k-1</strong><br>
                        <code># BUG: allows k-1 prior groups over 0 elements (infeasible)<br>
                        for j in range(0, i):   # BUG<br>
                        # FIX:<br>
                        for j in range(k-1, i):   # j must be at least k-1</code><br><br>
                        <strong>Bug 6 â€” Min Job Difficulty: not checking i â‰¥ d</strong><br>
                        <code># BUG: dp[i][d] computed even when i &lt; d<br>
                        for d in range(1, D+1):<br>
                            for i in range(1, n+1): ...   # BUG: no check for i &gt;= d<br>
                        # FIX:<br>
                        for d in range(1, D+1):<br>
                            for i in range(d, n+1):<br>
                                for j in range(d-1, i): ...</code><br><br>
                        <strong>Bug 7 â€” Paint House III: overwriting pre-painted houses</strong><br>
                        <code># BUG: ignores houses[i-1] != 0 constraint<br>
                        for c in range(1, m+1):<br>
                            dp[i][k][c] = min(...)   # BUG<br>
                        # FIX: if house is pre-painted, only update its actual color<br>
                        if houses[i-1] != 0:<br>
                            c = houses[i-1]<br>
                            dp[i][...][c] = ...</code><br><br>
                        <strong>Bug 8 â€” Filling Bookcase Shelves: missing width constraint check</strong><br>
                        <code># BUG: no width constraint<br>
                        for j in range(i-1, -1, -1):<br>
                            cur_max = max(cur_max, height[j])<br>
                            dp[i] = min(dp[i], dp[j] + cur_max)   # BUG<br>
                        # FIX: break when width exceeded<br>
                        for j in range(i-1, -1, -1):<br>
                            total_width += width[j]<br>
                            if total_width &gt; shelf_width: break<br>
                            cur_max = max(cur_max, height[j])<br>
                            dp[i] = min(dp[i], dp[j] + cur_max)</code><br><br>
                        <strong>Bug 9 â€” D&amp;C DP: processing hi half before computing opt_mid</strong><br>
                        <code># BUG: left half uses stale opt before opt_mid is found<br>
                        def solve(lo, hi, opt_lo, opt_hi):<br>
                            mid = (lo + hi) // 2<br>
                            solve(lo, mid-1, opt_lo, mid)    # BUG: opt_mid not computed yet<br>
                        # FIX: compute opt_mid FIRST<br>
                        def solve(lo, hi, opt_lo, opt_hi):<br>
                            mid = (lo + hi) // 2<br>
                            opt_mid = find_opt(mid, opt_lo, min(opt_hi, mid))<br>
                            solve(lo, mid-1, opt_lo, opt_mid)<br>
                            solve(mid+1, hi, opt_mid, opt_hi)</code><br><br>
                        <strong>Bug 10 â€” CHT: inserting lines non-monotonically into deque-CHT</strong><br>
                        <code># BUG: deque-CHT requires slopes to be monotone; arbitrary order breaks hull<br>
                        for j in range(n):<br>
                            hull.add_line(slope=a[j], intercept=dp[j])   # BUG if a[j] non-monotone<br>
                        # FIX: use Li Chao tree for arbitrary insertion order<br>
                        tree = LiChaoTree(x_range)<br>
                        for j in range(n):<br>
                            tree.add_line(a[j], dp[j])<br>
                            dp[i] = tree.query(i)</code>
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">Red Flags / Common Mistakes</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">
                        <strong>[Stage 1] Confusing partition DP with knapsack DP:</strong> "Partition array into two equal-sum subsets" (LC 416) looks like a partition problem but is a 0/1 Knapsack because the subsets need not be contiguous. Partition DP ONLY applies when every element must belong to exactly one contiguous segment. The word "partition" in a problem title does NOT guarantee partition DP â€” check for contiguity.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 2] Palindrome Partitioning II: building O(nÂ³) DP instead of O(nÂ²) two-phase:</strong> Candidates attempt dp[i][j][k] (start, end, cuts) which is O(nÂ³) in space and O(nâ´) in time. The correct model separates the palindrome table (O(nÂ²) interval DP) from the cut DP (O(n) partition DP). The cut DP is 1D: dp[i] = min cuts for prefix of length i. NEVER combine these into a single 2D or 3D table.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 3] 2D partition DP: wrong initialisation of base cases:</strong> dp[0][0] = 0 and all other dp[0][k] = +âˆž (or dp[i][0] = +âˆž for i &gt; 0). A common mistake is initialising dp[i][1] = cost(0,i) manually instead of letting the recurrence handle it â€” this creates inconsistencies when k=1 is computed both manually and through the recurrence, sometimes double-counting or missing valid partitions.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 5] Applying D&amp;C DP without verifying opt monotonicity:</strong> The D&amp;C DP prunes the j-search range for each i. If opt[i] is NOT monotone, this pruning is INCORRECT â€” it will skip the true optimal j for some i and return wrong answers. Fix: verify the quadrangle inequality on paper (or empirically compute opt[] for small inputs and check monotonicity) before applying D&amp;C DP.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 3] Paint House III: incrementing neighborhood count incorrectly:</strong> The neighborhood count k increments when the current house's color DIFFERS from the previous house's color. A common mistake is incrementing k when the same color is used again (off-by-one in the "same color" check). The invariant is: k = number of maximal monochromatic runs so far; it increments exactly when a color TRANSITION happens.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 1] Word Break: O(nÂ³) from naÃ¯ve string hashing:</strong> s[j:i] in word_set is O(i-j) (string hashing). The total cost is O(nÂ² Â· avg_word_length). For n=10â´ and avg_word_length=10, this is 10â¹ operations. Fix: use a Trie to match words starting from each position in one O(nÂ·max_word_length) pass.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 5] CHT: using it when the cost function has MAX/MIN (not SUM/PRODUCT):</strong> CHT requires cost(j,i) = m(j)*i + b(j) â€” a linear function of i. Costs like max(a[j..i-1]) are NOT linear in i (they depend on all elements between j and i). Applying CHT to max-based costs gives wrong answers. Fix: for max-based costs, check if D&amp;C DP applies (via sliding window for monotone opt) or accept O(nÂ²).
                    </div>

