            <div class="topic-card" id="tp37">
                <div class="topic-header">
                    <div class="topic-num">37</div>
                    <div>
                        <div class="topic-title">Game Theory &amp; Minimax</div>
                        <div class="topic-meta">
                            <span class="tier-badge tier-T5">T5</span>
                            <span class="topic-type">Dynamic Programming</span>
                            <span class="topic-type">Game Theory</span>
                            <span class="topic-type">Minimax DP</span>
                            <span class="topic-type">Sprague-Grundy</span>
                            <span class="topic-type">Nim &amp; Variants</span>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="topic-body">
                    <div class="sec-title">Why This Topic Matters</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        Game Theory &amp; Minimax DP solves problems where two rational players alternate making decisions with opposing objectives, and the question is either who wins under perfect play, what score can the first player guarantee, or what is the optimal strategy. The core invariant is: every reachable game position is either a W-position (the player to move wins with perfect play) or an L-position (the player to move loses regardless of their moves), and this labelling propagates deterministically from terminal positions backwards through the game graph. This topic dominates competitive programming and top-tier interviews because it is a forcing structure — once you understand the W/L labelling invariant, every variant (score-difference games, Nim, Sprague-Grundy, bitmask games, graph games) becomes a coating on the same skeleton. The hard problems require identifying WHAT the game state is and HOW the game graph is structured, not inventing a new algorithm. Sprague-Grundy theory — which unifies all impartial games through XOR of Grundy values — is the single most powerful reduction in combinatorial game theory and converts multi-pile exponential problems into O(n) one-liners.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">The Mental Model</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        Every game position is a node in a directed graph. Terminal nodes (no moves) are coloured LOSS for the player to move. Propagate backwards: colour a node WIN if it has at least one edge to a LOSS node; colour it LOSS if ALL its edges lead to WIN nodes. Your entire job is to compute this colouring for the starting position. Everything else — score differences, Grundy values, Nim equivalences — is a refinement of this single colouring rule.<br><br>
                        <strong>Universal W/L recurrence:</strong><br>
                        dp[pos] = L if no moves exist; W if ∃ move to an L-position; L if all moves lead to W-positions.<br><br>
                        <strong>How this mental model scales through the 5 stages:</strong><br>
                        <strong>Stage 1 — Simplest form:</strong> The game graph is a line (pile sizes 0, 1, 2, …n). Terminal = pile 0. Colour left to right. dp[n] = W or L.<br>
                        <strong>Stage 2 — What changes:</strong> The winning/losing condition flips (misère), or the move options become asymmetric (divisors, perfect squares). The colouring rule is identical — only the terminal definition or the edge set changes.<br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 — What expands:</strong> The game state requires two or more dimensions. dp[i][j] = score-difference for interval games (both ends available), or dp[i][M] when the move-budget M is itself a state variable.<br>
                        <strong>Stage 4 — What is hidden:</strong> The game is disguised. The "game positions" are bitmasks of chosen numbers, node-pairs in a graph, or pile configurations after reductions. The Sprague-Grundy theorem maps any impartial game to an equivalent Nim pile via mex — the reduction IS the hard part.<br>
                        <strong>Stage 5 — What is optimised:</strong> The Grundy sequence for a take-away game is eventually periodic. Instead of computing O(n·|S|) for n up to 10¹⁸, detect the period in O(P·|S|) and answer any query in O(1).
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Core Invariant / Proof Sketch</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Invariant (W/L labelling completeness):</strong> In any finite, acyclic, two-player, zero-sum, perfect-information game, every position receives exactly one label: W or L.<br><br>
                        <strong>Proof sketch (strong induction on game-graph depth):</strong><br>
                        Base case (depth 0): Positions with no legal moves — the player to move cannot act and loses. Label = L. ✓<br>
                        Inductive step: Assume all positions at depth &lt; d are correctly labelled. For a position P at depth d:<br>
                        If any successor S has label L: the current player moves to S, leaving the opponent in a losing state. Label P = W. ✓<br>
                        If ALL successors have label W: every move leaves the opponent in a winning state. Label P = L. ✓<br>
                        Uniqueness: P cannot be both W and L — the two cases are mutually exclusive and exhaustive (some successor is L, or none is L). ✓<br>
                        Finiteness guarantees termination: The game is acyclic (a finite DAG), so every branch reaches a terminal in finite steps. The induction bottoms out. □<br><br>
                        <strong>Score-difference correctness sketch:</strong> Define dp[i][j] = (current player's score) − (opponent's score) for sub-game on interval [i,j]. The recurrence dp[i][j] = max(a[i] − dp[i+1][j], a[j] − dp[i][j-1]) is correct because: after the current player takes a[i] and the game state moves to [i+1,j], the NEW current player (the original opponent) achieves dp[i+1][j] advantage over the NEW opponent (the original player). So the original player's advantage is a[i] − dp[i+1][j]. The subtraction is the perspective flip.<br><br>
                        <strong>Sprague-Grundy theorem sketch:</strong> Define G(P) = mex&#123;G(P') : P' reachable from P&#125;. Then P is an L-position iff G(P) = 0, and for a sum of independent games, G(combined) = XOR(G(components)). The first claim follows directly from the W/L induction: G(P) = 0 iff mex&#123;...&#125; = 0 iff 0 is NOT in the reachable Grundy values iff every successor has Grundy value ≥ 1 iff every successor is a W-position (G ≥ 1 → W) iff P is an L-position. The XOR composition follows from Bouton's theorem on multi-pile Nim, extended to all impartial games via Grundy equivalence.
                    </div>
