                    <div class="sec-title">🔧 Custom Problem 3 — Take-Away Game with Set S</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Problem:</strong> Two players alternate taking stones from a pile of n stones. On each turn, the current player must take exactly s stones where s ∈ S (a given set of positive integers). The player who CANNOT move loses. Given n and S, output W if the first player wins, L otherwise.<br><br>
                        <strong>Constraints:</strong> 1 ≤ n ≤ 10⁵, 1 ≤ |S| ≤ 20, 1 ≤ s ≤ 100 for all s ∈ S.<br><br>
                        <strong>Example:</strong> S = &#123;2, 5&#125;, n = 1. dp[0]=L, dp[1]=L (no move ≤ 1 in S), dp[2]=W, dp[3]=W (can go to dp=L), dp[4]=L, dp[5]=W, dp[6]=W, dp[7]=L. Period = 7. Answer for n=1: L.<br><br>
                        <strong>Solution:</strong> dp[0] = False; for n ≥ 1: dp[n] = any(not dp[n-s] for s in S if s ≤ n). Answer = dp[n]. Time: O(n·|S|). The Grundy sequence is eventually periodic with period ≤ LCM(elements of S)+max(S).<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage:</strong> 1 — establishes the universal take-away template. The ONE new idea over S.No 2 is that the move set is FIXED and arbitrary (not state-dependent).
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">🔧 Custom Problem 16 — Compute Grundy Values</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Problem:</strong> Same setup as Custom Problem 3. Instead of outputting W/L, output the full Grundy sequence grundy[0], grundy[1], ..., grundy[N]. Then, given Q queries of multi-pile Nim where each query specifies k pile sizes, output W or L for each query.<br><br>
                        <strong>Constraints:</strong> Same as Custom Problem 3; 1 ≤ Q ≤ 10⁵; k ≤ 100 piles per query.<br><br>
                        <strong>Solution:</strong> grundy[0] = 0; for n ≥ 1: grundy[n] = mex(&#123;grundy[n-s] for s in S if s ≤ n&#125;) where mex(T) = min non-negative integer not in T. For each query: XOR all pile Grundy values; L iff result = 0. Time: O(n·|S|) precompute + O(k) per query.<br><br>
                        <strong>Why this exists:</strong> Bridges Stage 1 (boolean W/L) to Stage 4 (Sprague-Grundy XOR). The single new idea is the mex function, which generalises the any(not dp[...]) into a full Grundy value. Without understanding mex, all Stage 4 problems are inaccessible.
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">State Evolution Across Stages</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Group 1: Single-Pile W/L Take-Away DP</strong><br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 1 — Fixed move set:</strong><br>
                        dp[n] = True (W) or False (L)<br>
                        Recurrence: dp[n] = any(not dp[n-s] for s in S if s ≤ n)<br>
                        Base: dp[0] = False (normal play: no moves = lose)<br>
                        Fill: left to right, n = 0, 1, 2, ..., N<br>
                        Preferred: Bottom-up — trivial left-to-right; no dependencies on future states<br>
                        Space optimisation: if sequence is periodic with period P, only store dp[0..P-1] and answer = dp[n % P]<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 2 — Misère variant (last to move loses):</strong><br>
                        Same recurrence, ONE change: dp[0] = True (cannot move = WIN, because opponent took the last stone and loses)<br>
                        Note: for Nim specifically, misère strategy = standard Nim EXCEPT when all piles ≤ 1; at that point, aim for ODD number of size-1 piles<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 4 — Grundy values:</strong><br>
                        grundy[n] = Grundy value (nimber) of position n<br>
                        Recurrence: grundy[n] = mex(&#123;grundy[n-s] for s in S if s ≤ n&#125;)<br>
                        Base: grundy[0] = 0 (mex of empty set = 0)<br>
                        Fill: left to right; W/L determination: L iff grundy[n] == 0<br>
                        Multi-pile query: L iff XOR(grundy[p] for p in piles) == 0<br><br>
                        <strong>Group 2: Score-Difference Interval DP</strong><br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 2 — Take from either end:</strong><br>
                        dp[i][j] = (current player score) − (opponent score) for piles[i..j]<br>
                        Recurrence: dp[i][j] = max(piles[i] − dp[i+1][j], piles[j] − dp[i][j-1])<br>
                        Base: dp[i][i] = piles[i]; dp[i][i-1] = 0 (empty interval)<br>
                        Fill: by increasing length L = j-i+1; ensures dp[i+1][j] and dp[i][j-1] computed before dp[i][j]<br>
                        Answer: first player wins iff dp[0][n-1] ≥ 0; player 1 score = (total_sum + dp[0][n-1]) / 2<br>
                        Preferred: Bottom-up by length — memoised top-down also works for interval DP; bottom-up avoids recursion for large n<br>
                        Space: O(n) with two rolling rows if only final answer needed; O(n²) to reconstruct moves<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 2 — Take from front only (Stone Game III):</strong><br>
                        dp[i] = max score-diff from piles[i:]<br>
                        Recurrence: dp[i] = max(piles[i] − dp[i+1], sum(p[i:i+2]) − dp[i+2], sum(p[i:i+3]) − dp[i+3])<br>
                        Base: dp[n] = dp[n+1] = dp[n+2] = 0 (past end)<br>
                        Fill: right to left; O(1) space with 3-variable rolling<br>
                        Preferred: Bottom-up right-to-left — no 2D table needed; O(n) time, O(1) space<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 — Stone Game II (M-parameter):</strong><br>
                        dp[i][M] = max stones current player gets from piles[i:] when current M = M<br>
                        Recurrence: dp[i][M] = max(suffix[i] − dp[i+X][max(M,X)] for X in 1..2M)<br>
                        Taking X piles → opponent faces suffix[i+X:] with M' = max(M, X)<br>
                        Since opponent maximises, dp[i][M] = suffix[i] − min(dp[i+X][max(M,X)] for X in 1..2M)<br>
                        Base: dp[i][M] = suffix[i] when i + 2*M ≥ n (can take everything)<br>
                        Fill: right to left on i; for each i, all M values; suffix prefix sums precomputed<br>
                        Preferred: Top-down memoisation — the M dimension ranges irregularly (1 to n/2); top-down avoids over-computing states with large M that are never reached<br><br>
                        <strong>Group 3: Bitmask Game DP</strong><br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 — Can I Win:</strong><br>
                        dp[mask] = True (W) or False (L) where mask = bitmask of integers already chosen<br>
                        Running sum from mask = sum(i+1 for i in range(n) if mask &amp; (1&lt;&lt;i))<br>
                        Recurrence: dp[mask] = any(not dp[mask | (1&lt;&lt;i)] for i in range(n) if not (mask &amp; (1&lt;&lt;i)) and running_sum + (i+1) ≥ desiredTotal) — if adding i reaches target, this is immediately a WIN move<br>
                        More precisely: dp[mask] = any(running_sum + (i+1) ≥ desiredTotal OR not dp[mask|(1&lt;&lt;i)] for unused i)<br>
                        Base: dp[full_mask] = False (no moves; but this state is reached after total ≥ target already resolved)<br>
                        Early termination: if sum(1..maxChoosableInteger) &lt; desiredTotal → always False<br>
                        Preferred: Top-down memoisation with mask as dictionary key — fill order is complex (depends on which bits are set)<br><br>
                        <strong>Group 4: Graph Game DP (Cat and Mouse)</strong><br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 — Cat and Mouse (cyclic game graph):</strong><br>
                        dp[mouse][cat][turn] ∈ &#123;MOUSE_WIN, CAT_WIN, DRAW&#125;<br>
                        Terminal states: mouse == 0 → MOUSE_WIN (for any cat, any turn); mouse == cat → CAT_WIN (cat catches mouse)<br>
                        Recurrence (NOT standard bottom-up — uses reverse BFS):<br>
                        Algorithm: propagate from known terminals backwards.<br>
                        1. Initialise all terminal positions as MOUSE_WIN or CAT_WIN.<br>
                        2. For each terminal T, propagate to all predecessor positions P: if P is a MOUSE_WIN position reaching T (mouse's turn) and T = MOUSE_WIN → P = MOUSE_WIN immediately; if P is a CAT_WIN position reaching T (cat's turn) and T = CAT_WIN → P = CAT_WIN immediately; Count: decrement out-degree of P; if all moves lead to same outcome → P gets that label.<br>
                        3. Any position never labelled = DRAW.<br>
                        Preferred: Reverse BFS from terminal states — ONLY correct approach for cyclic game graphs; standard DP produces wrong answers.
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">Pattern Recognition Triggers</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Linguistic Triggers:</strong><br>
                        "two players take turns; player who cannot move LOSES / WINS" → Stage 1 W/L take-away DP; dp[0]=L (normal play) or dp[0]=W (misère); identify move set immediately<br>
                        "both players play OPTIMALLY; who wins / what is the maximum score the first player can guarantee" → Stage 2/3 score-difference DP; dp[i][j] = max(a[i]−dp[i+1][j], a[j]−dp[i][j-1])<br>
                        "remove from piles; player wins if all piles empty / XOR" → Stage 4 Sprague-Grundy; check if multi-pile; XOR of Grundy values<br>
                        "choose from a set of integers 1..N; first player to reach target or exceed it wins" → Stage 3 bitmask game DP; state = mask of used integers; O(2ⁿ·n)<br>
                        "two entities move on a graph; one is predator, one is prey; who catches whom" → Stage 3 graph game DP; three-outcome (W/L/DRAW); reverse-BFS required if graph has cycles<br><br>
                        <strong>Structural Triggers:</strong><br>
                        Two players, alternating, perfect information, no randomness, finite acyclic game → W/L DP or score-diff DP; classify as impartial (Sprague-Grundy applies) or partisan (score-diff or turn-dimension DP)<br>
                        Game positions form an INTERVAL [i, j] that shrinks from both ends on each turn → Score-difference interval DP; dp[i][j]; fill by increasing length<br>
                        The "move" is taking a number from a set and the chosen number is REMOVED permanently → Bitmask game state; dp[mask]; N ≤ 20<br><br>
                        <strong>Constraint Triggers:</strong><br>
                        n ≤ 20 → Bitmask game DP; O(2ⁿ·n) feasible<br>
                        n ≤ 10¹⁸ → O(n) DP impossible; look for periodic Grundy sequence or closed-form (Nim: XOR; Wythoff: golden ratio)<br><br>
                        <strong>Anti-Triggers:</strong><br>
                        "two players cooperate to maximise TOTAL score" → NOT minimax → Standard maximisation DP; no adversarial structure<br>
                        "maximise your score (single player)" → NOT game theory → 1D/2D optimisation DP or greedy<br>
                        "who wins if both play optimally (n even)" → MIGHT NOT need DP → check for parity/symmetry shortcut first
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">Decision Framework</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Q1:</strong> Are there EXACTLY TWO players making alternating decisions with OPPOSING objectives? NO → Not game theory. YES → Continue.<br><br>
                        <strong>Q2:</strong> Is the game IMPARTIAL (both players have IDENTICAL legal moves from any position)? YES → Sprague-Grundy applies; Q3. NO (Partisan) → Score-diff or turn-dimension DP; Q5.<br><br>
                        <strong>Q3:</strong> MULTIPLE INDEPENDENT PILES/subgames simultaneously? YES → XOR of Grundy values; L iff XOR=0. Standard Nim: G(pile n)=n. Stage 4. NO → Compute Grundy/W/L directly; Q4.<br><br>
                        <strong>Q4:</strong> Is n so large that O(n·|S|) TLEs (n &gt; 10⁶)? YES → Detect period P; O(P·|S|)+O(1) query. Stage 5. NO → Standard grundy[n] = mex&#123;...&#125; or dp[n] = any(not dp[n-s]). Stage 1. O(n·|S|).<br><br>
                        <strong>Q5 (Partisan):</strong> Does score per move depend on BOTH players' positions (take from either end)? YES → Score-diff interval DP dp[i][j]. O(n²); Q6. NO → 1D dp[i]. O(n). Rolling window if window ≤ k.<br><br>
                        <strong>Q6:</strong> Does state need MORE than two dimensions? YES → Add M (move budget) → dp[i][M]. O(n²). Or color → dp[i][j][c]. O(n²·C). NO → Standard 2D dp[i][j]. O(n²).<br><br>
                        <strong>Q7:</strong> Is the game state EXPONENTIAL? Bitmask (N ≤ 20): dp[mask]. O(2ⁿ·n). Graph with cycles: REVERSE-BFS from terminals. Three outcomes: W, L, DRAW.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">When This Technique BREAKS</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>[Stage 1] Standard W/L DP on a cyclic game graph:</strong> The bottom-up W/L recurrence assumes a DAG. Cycles make DRAW possible. Fix: use reverse BFS from terminals; uncoloured positions = DRAW (Cat and Mouse).<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 2] Applying standard Nim strategy to Misère Nim throughout:</strong> Misère strategy = standard Nim EXCEPT when all piles ≤ 1. Then aim for ODD number of size-1 piles. Applying inversion mid-game gives wrong answers.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 4] Applying Sprague-Grundy to a PARTISAN game:</strong> SG works only for impartial games (identical moves). Partisan: track turn dp[pos][turn] or temperature theory.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 3] Period detection without full verification:</strong> Single-value match is coincidental. Fix: verify grundy[n] = grundy[n % P] for n = P..3P.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 2] Score-diff DP: adding instead of subtracting:</strong> dp[i][j] = max(a[i]+dp[i+1][j], ...) is WRONG. Must SUBTRACT: a[move] − dp[subgame] (perspective flip).<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 4] Assuming Grundy periodicity for state-dependent move sets:</strong> Periodicity holds only for FIXED move sets (octal games). State-dependent moves (divisors) → no guarantee.
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">Proof of Correctness Skeleton</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Stage 1 — W/L Take-Away DP: Invariant Maintenance</strong><br>
                        Claim: dp[n] = True iff the player to move from pile-size n wins under perfect play with move set S.<br>
                        Terminal: dp[0] = False; no moves → current player loses. ✓<br>
                        W-step: If ∃ s ∈ S, s ≤ n, with dp[n-s] = False: take s; opponent in L. dp[n] = True. ✓<br>
                        L-step: If ∀ s ∈ S with s ≤ n: dp[n-s] = True. Every move leaves opponent in W. dp[n] = False. ✓<br>
                        Induction: dp[n] only references dp[n-s] for s ≥ 1 (smaller). By strong induction, all correct. □<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 2 — Score-Difference DP: Perspective-Flip</strong><br>
                        Claim: dp[i][j] = max(a[i] − dp[i+1][j], a[j] − dp[i][j-1]) equals (current player's score) − (opponent's score) for piles[i..j].<br>
                        Base: dp[i][i] = a[i]. ✓<br>
                        Inductive step: Current takes a[i]; game → [i+1,j]. Opponent is now "current" and achieves dp[i+1][j] over original. So original advantage = a[i] − dp[i+1][j]. Symmetric for a[j]. ✓<br>
                        Score recovery: S₁ + S₂ = total_sum and S₁ − S₂ = dp[0][n-1]. Wins iff dp[0][n-1] ≥ 0. ✓ □<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 4 — Sprague-Grundy: mex Correctness</strong><br>
                        Claim: G(P) = mex(&#123;G(P') : P' reachable from P&#125;) correctly encodes W/L, and P is L iff G(P)=0.<br>
                        G(P)=0 → L: 0 ∉ &#123;G(P')&#125; means all successors have G ≥ 1 (W). So P is L. ✓<br>
                        G(P)&gt;0 → W: mex=k&gt;0 means 0 ∈ &#123;G(P')&#125;. Some successor is L → P is W. ✓<br>
                        XOR composition: Bouton's theorem; move in component i changes XOR by replacing G(Gᵢ) with smaller, mirroring moves in single Nim pile. □
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Implementation Pitfalls (Code-Level)</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Stage 1–2 Bugs:</strong><br><br>
                        <strong>Bug 1 — Wrong terminal:</strong> dp = [True] * (n+1) — misère base applied to normal-play; FIX: dp[0] = False; for i in range(1, n+1): dp[i] = any(not dp[i-s] for s in S if s &lt;= i).<br><br>
                        <strong>Bug 2 — Adding instead of subtracting:</strong> dp[i][j] = max(piles[i] + dp[i+1][j], ...) — accumulates instead of difference; FIX: dp[i][j] = max(piles[i] - dp[i+1][j], piles[j] - dp[i][j-1]).<br><br>
                        <strong>Bug 3 — Wrong fill order:</strong> Row-major iteration can reference uncomputed dp[i+1][j]; FIX: iterate by increasing length: for length in range(2, n+1): for i in range(n - length + 1): j = i + length - 1; dp[i][j] = max(piles[i] - dp[i+1][j], piles[j] - dp[i][j-1]).<br><br>
                        <strong>Bug 4 — mex using max+1:</strong> mex(&#123;0,1,3&#125;) = 2, NOT max+1=4; FIX: def mex(s): i = 0; while i in s: i += 1; return i.<br><br>
                        <strong>Bug 5 — Predict the Winner strict inequality:</strong> return dp[0][n-1] &gt; 0 misses ties; FIX: return dp[0][n-1] &gt;= 0.<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 Bugs:</strong><br><br>
                        <strong>Bug 6 — Stone Game II wrong M update:</strong> using dp[i+X][M] instead of dp[i+X][max(M,X)]; FIX: val = suffix[i+X] - dp[i+X][max(M, X)].<br><br>
                        <strong>Bug 7 — Can I Win no early termination:</strong> runs expensive bitmask DP even when sum(1..max) &lt; desiredTotal (always False); FIX: early return False if impossible, True if desiredTotal &lt;= 0.<br><br>
                        <strong>Bug 8 — Cat and Mouse forward DP:</strong> forward fill on cyclic graph never settles DRAW; FIX: reverse-BFS from terminals; never-reached = DRAW.<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 4 Bugs:</strong><br><br>
                        <strong>Bug 9 — Multi-pile Nim XOR of indices:</strong> for i, pile in enumerate(piles): result ^= i is WRONG; FIX: XOR pile VALUES, not indices.<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 5 Bugs:</strong><br><br>
                        <strong>Bug 10 — Declaring period from single match:</strong> grundy[i] == grundy[0] once ≠ period; FIX: verify_period(grundy, P) checking all values in [P, 3P].
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">Red Flags / Common Mistakes</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>[Stage 1] Confusing normal play with misère — dp[0]:</strong> Normal play ("last to move wins"): dp[0]=False. Misère ("last to move loses"): dp[0]=True. OPPOSITE base cases, IDENTICAL recurrences. Read the losing condition first.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 2] Score-diff DP: using absolute scores with turn flag:</strong> dp[i][j][turn] is O(n²·2) and requires special-casing the turn. Score-difference encoding dp[i][j] is O(n²) with NO turn dimension — subtraction handles the flip automatically.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 3] Can I Win: forgetting current_sum check:</strong> Game ends when running sum ≥ desiredTotal, not just when all chosen. Must check current_sum + (i+1) ≥ desiredTotal in recurrence.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 4] Applying Sprague-Grundy to Cat and Mouse:</strong> Cat and Mouse is CYCLIC with DRAWS — NOT impartial acyclic. SG via mex on cyclic graphs → infinite loops or wrong values. Check acyclicity before applying SG.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 4] Assuming independence of subgames without verification:</strong> XOR composition is correct ONLY when components are truly independent. Moves affecting multiple components simultaneously → XOR gives wrong answers.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 2] Stone Game VI: applying minimax when greedy suffices:</strong> When each player values items INDEPENDENTLY (Alice values a[], Bob values b[]), joint-value sort a[i]+b[i] desc always dominates — O(n log n) greedy, not O(n²) DP.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 5] Period detection on non-fixed move sets:</strong> Only works for FIXED S. Divisor Game and similar have non-periodic Grundy sequences.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Interviewer Follow-Up Questions</div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Stage</th><th>Question</th><th>Intended Answer Direction</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>1</td><td>2</td><td>"Nim Game: what if a player can take at most K stones (not just 1/2/3)?"</td><td>Generalise to move set &#123;1,...,K&#125;; L-positions are multiples of K+1; n % (K+1) == 0 → L; period = K+1; pure formula</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>2</td><td>2</td><td>"Stone Game: what if the array is circular (last adjacent to first)?"</td><td>dp[i][j] on linear can't model circular; fix element 0: run two passes — one where element 0 goes to player 1 first, one where it doesn't; take max; O(n²) still</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>3</td><td>3</td><td>"Predict the Winner: reconstruct the actual sequence of optimal moves."</td><td>Parent pointer array choice[i][j] ∈ &#123;'L','R'&#125;; backtrack from dp[n-1]; O(n) reconstruction</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>4</td><td>3</td><td>"Can I Win: n increases to 40. How does complexity change?"</td><td>2⁴⁰ ≈ 10¹² infeasible; meet-in-the-middle: split into two halves of 20; enumerate (sum, parity) pairs per half; combine in O(2²⁰ · 20) ≈ 2×10⁷</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>5</td><td>4</td><td>"Explain Staircase Nim and prove why only odd-indexed piles matter."</td><td>Moves transfer k stones from i to i-1; moves from EVEN positions are mirrored by opponent (same k, i-1 to i-2); only ODD positions affect XOR; mirror strategy maintains invariant</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>6</td><td>4</td><td>"How do you handle Cat and Mouse if the graph has self-loops?"</td><td>Self-loops at non-terminals → player can "stay" indefinitely → DRAW; in reverse-BFS such nodes are never forced to a terminal and remain uncoloured (DRAW); no algorithm change</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>7</td><td>5</td><td>"Grundy values for take-away where n can be 10¹⁸?"</td><td>Detect period P; compute grundy[0..3P]; verify; answer = grundy[n % P]; period P ≤ LCM(S)+max(S) empirically; total O(P·|S|)</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>8</td><td>5</td><td>"Stone Game V: optimise from O(n³) to O(n²)?"</td><td>Inner k-scan is O(n); if optimal split k*[i][j] is monotone → D&amp;C DP → O(n² log n); concave SMAWK holds → O(n²); or two-pointer on crossing point of left_sum &lt; right_sum</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>9</td><td>Beyond</td><td>"Distribute Nim across 10 machines with 10⁹ piles. How?"</td><td>XOR is associative/commutative; each machine XORs its piles (O(n/m)); coordinator XORs machine results (O(m)); total O(n/m + m); optimal m = √n for O(√n); L iff global XOR = 0</td></tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table></div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="topic-card" id="tp38"><div class="coming">Content for Tree DP is coming soon.<br><br>Covers: House Robber III (tree), Diameter of Binary Tree, Binary Tree Cameras, Maximum Path Sum, Count Nodes Equal to Average of Subtree, Longest Path with Same Values, Rerooting technique, Tree Knapsack &amp; more.</div></div>
            <div class="topic-card" id="tp39"><div class="coming">Content for Digit DP is coming soon.<br><br>Covers: Count numbers with digit sum = k, Count numbers without repeated digits, Numbers with even number of digits, Digit DP template (tight/free bounds), Non-decreasing digits, At most N given digit set &amp; more.</div></div>
            <div class="topic-card" id="tp40"><div class="coming">Content for DAGs &amp; Probability DP is coming soon.<br><br>Covers: Longest Path in DAG, Count paths in DAG, Dice Roll simulation, Knight Probability in Chessboard, New 21 Game, Soup Servings, Probability of reaching target &amp; more.</div></div>
            <div class="topic-card" id="tp41"><div class="coming">Content for Combinatorial &amp; Modulo DP is coming soon.<br><br>Covers: Number of Ways to Reorder Array, Unique BSTs (Catalan), Count Vowels Permutation, K Inverse Pairs Array, Count different palindromic subsequences, MOD arithmetic in DP &amp; more.</div></div>
            <div class="topic-card" id="tp42"><div class="coming">Content for Data Structure Optimized DP is coming soon.<br><br>Covers: Segment Tree + DP, BIT/Fenwick Tree + DP (LIS in O(n log n)), Monotonic Deque + DP (Sliding Window DP), Divide &amp; Conquer DP optimization, Convex Hull Trick, Knuth's optimization &amp; more.</div></div>

        </div>
    </div>

